<HEAD>Water Restrictions Tighten, Mississippi Still Blocked</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Subs 6 grafs for 3rd graf, ``Rain fell ...'' to UPDATE with
possibility of diverting water to Mississippi River, Perpich's
comments after returning from Washington, and crop analyst's
comments. Picks up 4th graf pvs, ``Temperatures hit ...'' INSERTS 2
grafs after 6th graf pvs `The temperature ...'' for details on
circus train. Picks up 7th graf pvs, ``Salt concentrations ...''
INSERTS one graf after 10th graf `Cooper, deputy' to explain impact
on plants. SUBS 19th graf pvs, ``Leonard made ...'' to conform.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By ROGER PETTERSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
 A federal official warned Thursday that two more months of drought could close plants along three rivers in <LOCATION> Alabama </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Georgia </LOCATION>, as temperature records continued to fall, and circus elephants were taken to a river to cool off in 101-degree <LOCATION> Pittsburgh </LOCATION>. One official in drought-stricken <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION> warned Thursday of likely statewide water restrictions. Low water again kept barges from moving on the lower <LOCATION> Mississippi </LOCATION> <LOCATION> River </LOCATION> and part of the <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION> was closed. An official of the <ORGANIZATION> Minnesota </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Natural </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Resources </ORGANIZATION> said the river dipped closer Wednesday to a level that would trigger a recommendation to divert water from lakes in northern <LOCATION> Minnesota </LOCATION>. <LOCATION> Minnesota </LOCATION> Gov. <PERSON> Rudy </PERSON> <PERSON> Perpich </PERSON>, upon returning from <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> Thursday night, said he persuaded <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Agriculture Secretary <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Lyng </PERSON> to allow farmers to donate their hay on Conservation Reserve Program land without forfeiting any of their payment's under it `` This is a very critical time for livestock and dairy farmers. These people are on the verge of bankruptcy,'' <PERSON> Perpich </PERSON> said at the Minneapolis-St. Paul International Airport `` But it wo n't work unless we get the farmers to donate the hay and the private and commercial truckers to donate the transportation. I'll contribute my time and drive one of those trucks.'' Private crop analyst <PERSON> Conrad </PERSON> <PERSON> Leslie </PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION> Leslie </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Analytical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Organization </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION> said corn yields from irrigated fields of <LOCATION> Nebraska </LOCATION> and parts of <LOCATION> Iowa </LOCATION> could be good, but some other fields in the <LOCATION> Midwest </LOCATION> already are `` beyond recovery.'' `` This is a disaster under development,'' said <PERSON> Leslie </PERSON>. `` We're in uncharted waters The great difficulty is that we do n't know what the moisture situation will be a year from now and whether we can make a recovery.'' Rain fell on some dry sections of <LOCATION> Minnesota </LOCATION>, but <LOCATION> Pennsylvania </LOCATION> officials declared a statewide drought watch Thursday, triggering voluntary reductions in water use and a ban on open fires in state parks and forests. Temperatures hit record highs for the date Thursday in at least 28 cities from the <LOCATION> Great </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Lakes </LOCATION> to the <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Coast </LOCATION>, including 102 at <LOCATION> Fort </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Wayne </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ind. </LOCATION>, the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Weather </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> said. <LOCATION> Detroit </LOCATION>'s high of 100 degrees toppled a record that had been on the books since 1874, when thermometers reached 97. In the normally cool mountains of <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Virginia </LOCATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Elkins </ORGANIZATION> hit a record 93, the ninth record temperature there since June 1. The temperature at <LOCATION> Pittsburgh </LOCATION> hit a record 101 degrees and four elephants from the <LOCATION> Syria </LOCATION> Temple Shrine Circus were taken to the <LOCATION> Allegheny </LOCATION> <LOCATION> River </LOCATION> for a cooling wallow. Only one of the animals, natives of hot climates, got in and rolled around in the water. The drought also knocked the steam out of the annual railroad journey transporting vintage, restored circus wagons to <LOCATION> Milwaukee </LOCATION> for the city's Circus Parade. Officials said Thursday that the steam locomotive used to pull the train wo n't make the run this year because of the danger of setting track-side fires from sparks. Salt concentrations in <LOCATION> Mississippi </LOCATION> <LOCATION> River </LOCATION> water climbed higher Thursday at drinking water intakes of the nearest downriver suburb of <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Orleans </LOCATION>, and officials of <LOCATION> St. </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bernard </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Parish </LOCATION> began reserving barges to float in fresh water. The river's reduced flow is not strong enough to push the dense salt water back into the <LOCATION> Gulf </LOCATION> <LOCATION> of </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION>. Lower Plaquemines Parish is already bringing fresh water by barge to mix with the salty flow at its intakes 30 miles downriver from <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Orleans </LOCATION>. The salt concentration there is already strong enough to taste. A continuation of the drought for two more months could threaten municipal water supplies and close plants along three major rivers in <LOCATION> Alabama </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Georgia </LOCATION>, Lt. Col. <PERSON> Garry </PERSON> <PERSON> Cooper </PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corps </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Engineers </ORGANIZATION> said Thursday. <PERSON> Cooper </PERSON>, deputy district engineer for the Corps' Mobile District, addressed a drought management meeting of the <ORGANIZATION> Apalachicola-Chattahoochee-Flint </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Drought </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Management </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>, made up of the <ORGANIZATION> Corps </ORGANIZATION>, the three states and other organizations. The committee announced that navigation on <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION>'s <LOCATION> Apalachicola </LOCATION> <LOCATION> River </LOCATION> would virtually end on July 13 because of low water. <PERSON> Cooper </PERSON> referred to both plants that use water to run turbines and generate electricity and those that use water for industrial purposes, such as rinsing textiles and cooling machinery. The lack of rain already has forced <ORGANIZATION> Alabama </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Power </ORGANIZATION> to shut down nearly all hydroelectric production and have coal-burning plants make up the difference. The <LOCATION> Mississippi </LOCATION> <LOCATION> River </LOCATION> remained closed at <LOCATION> Black </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hills </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Miss. </LOCATION>, about 20 miles south of <LOCATION> Natchez </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Miss. </LOCATION>, where water had been as low as five feet. `` Hopefully by this weekend we will have the river open if somebody does n't mess up,'' L.C. Fumbanks, chief of navigation for the <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corps </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Engineers </ORGANIZATION>, said in a radio-telephone interview from aboard the dredge <PERSON> Jadwin </PERSON>. The <PERSON> Jadwin </PERSON> worked south of <LOCATION> Greenville </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Miss. </LOCATION>, where traffic resumed Wednesday, while another dredge pumped sand from the blockage at <LOCATION> Black </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hills </LOCATION>. The <ORGANIZATION> Coast </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Guard </ORGANIZATION> decided Thursday to close the <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION> <LOCATION> River </LOCATION> at <LOCATION> Mound </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ill. </LOCATION>, for 12-hour shifts to clear a build-up of sand and silt from the channel, said <ORGANIZATION> Coast </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Guard </ORGANIZATION> Lt. j.g. <PERSON> Jim </PERSON> <PERSON> Clifton </PERSON>. He said the affected two-mile stretch would be opened for six hours Friday morning, closed for 12 hours, then reopened for six hours. `` It will just alternate back and forth like that until they get it cleared through,'' <PERSON> Clifton </PERSON> said, adding that he had no estimate how long that would take. Traffic on the <LOCATION> Missouri </LOCATION> <LOCATION> River </LOCATION> is normal, although barges are carrying lighter loads, thanks to reservoirs upstream, said <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> Johnston </PERSON>, director of public affairs for the <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corps </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Engineers </ORGANIZATION> at <LOCATION> Omaha </LOCATION>, Neb. <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION> Lt. Gov. <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> Leonard </PERSON> said Thursday that voluntary water conservation measures are not working. `` Most of the cities we're checking with regularly indicate the program is not paying dividends,'' <PERSON> Leonard </PERSON> said in <LOCATION> Dayton </LOCATION>. `` My guess is that if the drought continues for another two weeks to 30 days, we're going to need -LRB- statewide -RRB- mandatory water restrictions.'' <PERSON> Leonard </PERSON> made his remarks before leaving for <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, where he, like <PERSON> Perpich </PERSON> and officials from seven states met with <PERSON> Lyng </PERSON>. <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Shank </PERSON>, director of <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Environmental </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Protection </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION>, has asked the state's 2,500 largest water systems to aim for a a minimum 25 percent reduction in water use by all customers, and some cities have already banned lawn sprinkling. <LOCATION> Georgia </LOCATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Natural </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Resources </ORGANIZATION> fined <LOCATION> Gwinnett </LOCATION> and Cobb counties $ 75,000 each Wednesday for taking too much water in June and told them they must cut consumption, possibly including round-the-clock bans on outdoor water use. Up to 1.5 inches of rain fell on parts of west-central and northern <LOCATION> Minnesota </LOCATION> late Wednesday and early Thursday, somewhat easing drought conditions, the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Weather </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> said today. `` Every little bit helps,'' said <LOCATION> Clay </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> extension agent <PERSON> Eddie </PERSON> <PERSON> Bernhardson </PERSON>. However, he added: `` the rain's been really limited in most areas of the county, and high temperatures are complicating'' the situation. Wheat, <LOCATION> Clay </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION>'s biggest crop, `` is getting to the point where in some areas they'll get 8 to 10 bushels an acre maximum'' compared to a normal average of 40 to 50 bushels, he said. Approximately 545 bales of hay from <ORGANIZATION> Elon </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> College </ORGANIZATION>, <LOCATION> N.C. </LOCATION>, arrived Thursday at <LOCATION> Shelbyville </LOCATION>, Ky. It was a `` gesture of thanks'' for the 2,300 tons of hay <LOCATION> Kentucky </LOCATION> farmers sent by train to <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Carolina </LOCATION> two years ago, said <PERSON> Roger </PERSON> <PERSON> Nesbitt </PERSON>, a spokesman for the <ORGANIZATION> Kentucky </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agriculture </ORGANIZATION>. `` I gave about 50 bales two years ago. Now it's my turn to receive,'' said O.L. <PERSON> Jeffries </PERSON>, who farms near <LOCATION> Shelbyville </LOCATION>. `` I do n't know which way to turn. It's pitiful.''
