<FIRST>r w PM-Drought-Congress Bjt   07-07 0757</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Drought-Congress, Bjt,750</SECOND>
<HEAD>No Big Jump In Food Prices, Ag Official Says</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MIKE ROBINSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Increases in food prices should remain moderate this year despite the drought as the nation begins to draw on its large grain reserves, says the <ORGANIZATION> Agriculture </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>'s top economist. `` The immediate problem is not one of food shortage or food price inflation, except in certain specific instances, but rather the problem is one of responding in a compassionate way to the losses faced by American farmers,'' Assistant Secretary of Agriculture <PERSON> Ewen </PERSON> <PERSON> M. </PERSON> <PERSON> Wilson </PERSON> said Wednesday. Appearing before three <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> subcommittees, <PERSON> Wilson </PERSON> forecast tight supplies of soybeans and oats. He also acknowledged that while the winter wheat harvest is actually ahead of schedule, there has been severe damage to spring wheat and much of the corn crop is in bad shape. He said, however, that <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> soybeans will be available to meet <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> needs and added that reserves of wheat and feed grains are ample to ensure that Americans will not have to endure any calamitous food shortage. The testimony came as <LOCATION> Capitol </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hill </LOCATION> began to focus more intently on food prices, with lawmakers saying there was no immediate reason to warrant major increases. Rep. <PERSON> Byron </PERSON> <PERSON> Dorgan </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-N.D. </LOCATION>, called on the congressional <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Accounting </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Office </ORGANIZATION> to monitor food prices in the next six months. He expressed concern that food processors and others might engage in `` price gouging.'' `` It simply would n't wash with economic reality to cite the drought as a reason for a quick runup of food prices,'' he said in a statement. `` It would be inexcusable for any company to use the drought as a way to make a quick buck.'' <PERSON> Wilson </PERSON> did say that prolonged drought would send wheat prices higher, guaranteeing `` some additional pressure on retail prices of bakery products and cereals'' but not a major increase. He said, however, that farm-level prices account for only 8 percent of the retail value of cereal and bakery products. `` If wheat prices for the entire season average 30 percent above last year, this alone would translate into a 2.4 percent rise in the retail price of bakery and cereal products,'' <PERSON> Wilson </PERSON> said. He said any increases would be `` moderate'' in scale. <PERSON> Wilson </PERSON> said that while no major shortages were in sight, there could be a squeeze in the supply of some crops. He also said grazing conditions on June 1 were rated 68 percent of ideal and that hay prices are up 22 percent from last year. But 65 percent of the winter wheat crop, which amounts to three-quarters of all <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> wheat production, already has been harvested and progress is `` well ahead of normal,'' <PERSON> Wilson </PERSON> said. In contrast, `` the spring wheat crop is in bad shape with almost two-thirds of the crop rated in poor to very poor condition due to the drought,'' he said. Wheat reserves at the start of the year totaled 1.27 billion bushels, well above the average of the last decade, <PERSON> Wilson </PERSON> said. He said that amount plus winter wheat already in the bins from the current harvest add up to a 10-month supply. That includes wheat for export, he said. The greatest production loss is in durum wheat, which is used for pasta, he said. The condition of hard red spring wheat also is generally poor, but stocks equal to 80 percent of annual use are available, he said. Turning to feed grains, he said, corn is generally in fair condition. In 10 of the 17 major producing states, 25 percent or more of the crop is rated poor or very poor, he said. In six of the 11 major sorghum-producing states, at least 25 percent of sorghum acreage is rated poor or very poor, he said. There are no weekly reports on the condition of oats and barley, <PERSON> Wilson </PERSON> said. But he noted that more than half the nation's barley and one-third of its oats come from the Grain Belt where the drought is worst. Nonetheless, corn stocks on hand as of Sept. 1 are projected to equal 50 percent of annual use and sorghum stocks 90 percent of annual use. <PERSON> Wilson </PERSON> said corn supply should be ample to prevent any serious shortage. `` Even with a very pessimistic scenario you end up with a carryover of a billion bushels,'' he said. <PERSON> Wilson </PERSON> said the soybean crop is generally rated fair to poor. In 11 of the 19 major producing states, `` anywhere from one-fourth to more than one-half of the crop is rated poor or worse,'' he said.
</TEXT>
