<HEAD>Jackson Criticizes Bush Stance On Plane Downing</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By VICTORIA GRAHAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Jesse </PERSON> <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> is calling for a period of mourning for the victims of the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> missile attack on an Iranian jetliner, and urging the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> to pay reparations to the victims' families. He also criticized Vice President <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> for statements the likely Republican nominee made this week in response to the deaths of 290 people in the downing of the Iranian commercial jet. `` I thought it was a bit in bad taste, if not downright vulgar, to be running around on July 4, getting applause lines, talking about the honor of the <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION>, as if it were in question, and not expressing the profound sense of humanity that the <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> people have and our sense of sharing the grief of the tragedy,'' <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> said at the <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nations </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> expressed his deep regrets on Monday as he campaigned through the <LOCATION> Midwest </LOCATION>, saying, `` Obviously, as we celebrate our great national holiday our hearts go out to the loved ones and families of those who were lost and also -LRB- hearts -RRB- go out to those kids, those young Americans who are defending freedom halfway around the world.'' However, <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> also said he could identify with the captain of the <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> cruiser, who made the decision to fire because he believed his ship was in danger. And <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> said he did not believe <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> policy in the region would change as a result of the incident. `` Life goes on,' the vice president said. <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON>, who met with <PERSON> Arab </PERSON> leaders at the <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nations </ORGANIZATION>, emphasized that the downing of the Iranian plane was `` an accident, an error ... No one assumes that the <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> is without compassion, that it moved to engage in an act of war.'' `` We should say to <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> that we sincerely regret the accident occurred, that we offer reparations or compensation to the families of the victims, if they will accept them,'' said <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON>, repeating a call he made over the holiday weekend in the wake of the incident. At the <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION>, <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> met with envoys of the <ORGANIZATION> Arab </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> League </ORGANIZATION>, including <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Djibouti </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Mauritania </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Sudan </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Libya </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Somalia </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Syria </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Yemen </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Saudi </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Arabia </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Oman </LOCATION>, Democratic <LOCATION> Yemen </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Algeria </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Morocco </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Qatar </LOCATION>. He repeated his plea for the release of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> hostages and all other captives in <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> also said he favored a new international naval peacekeeping force in the gulf. `` I hope the <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nations </ORGANIZATION> will hav a much more prominent rule in the gulf in the future,'' <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> said. Earlier, when asked if he had any interest in becoming <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> ambassador to the <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nations </ORGANIZATION>, <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> replied, `` None whatsoever.''
