<SECOND>PM-Convention Protests, Bjt,570</SECOND>
<HEAD>Demonstrators of All Stripes Get Soapbox Time At The Convention</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOSEPH B. FRAZIER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 When the <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Convention </ORGANIZATION> opens here this month, protesters from animal rights activists to AIDS victims will be on hand to try to grab a bit of the spotlight. But convention organizers, who carefully orchestrate many of the events inside the convention hall, are also seeking to bring order to what could otherwise be a chaotic crush of demonstrations. The city is supplying a stage across the street from the convention site that will serve as a soapbox for a variety of causes. Protesters are being offered two-hour time slots over five days to air their views. The city will provide a stage and sound equipment in the lot, which authorities estimate can hold about 30,000 people. The demonstrators will be within sight and earshot of the delegates as they arrive and depart during the gathering July 15-18. However, the plan is being challenged in federal court by a coalition of groups seeking expanded space for demonstrations. A decision was possible as early as today. Generally, potentially antagonistic groups have not been scheduled together, although a gay rights group follows a white supremacist organization onto the stage one afternoon. By Wednesday, 25 of the 40 slots were filled, four of them by one organization, the Committee for Fair Elections. At least four other groups with ties to that committee also have reserved time. The group is the vehicle for the independent presidential campaign of <PERSON> Leonora </PERSON> <PERSON> B. </PERSON> <PERSON> Fulani </PERSON>, who says she will bring 10,000 backers to the convention. She has qualified for the ballot in all 50 states and is eligible for federal matching funds. Demonstrations coinciding with those on the stage supplied by the city will be permitted in the parking lot, but their organizers can not use powerful sound equipment. Local organizations with demonstration time include a neighborhood group that opposes the construction of a domed stadium in the neighborhood near the convention site. The Nationalist Movement, a Mississippi-based white supremacy group, has been given a parade permit and a two-hour slot on Sunday afternoon in conjunction with its annual convention. Other groups given protest time in the parking lot include: _ The <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> on <LOCATION> Latin </LOCATION> <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>, a liberal Washington-based foreign policy lobby. _ No Business As Usual, which opposes the Strategic Defense Initiative, known as Star Wars. _ Disabled In Action, a group advocating better access for the handicapped, which has ties to the <PERSON> Fulani </PERSON> campaign. _ <ORGANIZATION> U.S.-Congo </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Friendship </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>, which opposes the regime of President <PERSON> Mobuto </PERSON> Sese Seko of <LOCATION> Zaire </LOCATION>. _ Rep. <PERSON> Gus </PERSON> <PERSON> Savage </PERSON>, a <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> congressman from <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION>. _ <ORGANIZATION> Castillo </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cultural </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Centers </ORGANIZATION>, a <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> City-based performing arts group specializing in working-class history and progressive politics. _ The <ORGANIZATION> People </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Independent </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Club </ORGANIZATION>, a <LOCATION> Bronx </LOCATION>, N.Y.-based pro-Fulani organization. _ People With AIDS Coalition and March on AIDS. _ <ORGANIZATION> Arts </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Pluribus </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Unum </ORGANIZATION>, an <LOCATION> Atlanta </LOCATION> artist and activist group specializing in liberal political performances. _ Compassion Campaign ` 88, an animal rights organization. _ LEGAL, a national gay 