<HEAD>Soviets Say They Crush Protest in Armenia, Deny Deaths</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN-THOR DAHLBURG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Soviet authorities acknowledge that paratroopers crushed a protest by thousands of people who shut down a major airport in <LOCATION> Armenia </LOCATION>. But they deny activists' claims that soldiers killed as many as five protesters. The activists, pushing for annexation of a predominantly Armenian region of the neighboring republic of <LOCATION> Azerbaijan </LOCATION>, charged Wednesday that <ORGANIZATION> Red </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION> troops killed demonstrators at the airport in <LOCATION> Yerevan </LOCATION>, the Armenian capital. The latest round of protests began Monday with a general strike and intensified Tuesday night with the airport clash, officials and Armenian activists said. On Wednesday, the situation did not appear to be stabilizing. The evening television news program `` Vremya'' said hundreds of thousands of Armenians thronged <LOCATION> Yerevan </LOCATION>'s streets as the strike continued. The government daily <ORGANIZATION> Izvestia </ORGANIZATION> said mass transit was still shut down and the situation had worsened since Tuesday, when 26 factories and economic agencies in the southern republic were idled. Since February, <LOCATION> Yerevan </LOCATION> has been the scene of massive demonstrations by Armenians demanding annexation of the <LOCATION> Nagorno-Karabakh </LOCATION> region of <LOCATION> Azerbaijan </LOCATION>. Until now, the protests had reportedly been peaceful. On Wednesday, <ORGANIZATION> Foreign </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Vadim </PERSON> <PERSON> Perfilyev </PERSON> told a news conference `` the rumors that Armenians were killed are groundless.'' But he acknowledged that Soviet troops late Tuesday routed about 2,000 people from in and around the Zvartnots Airport. He said 36 people `` had to seek medical assistance'' after the clash. On Wednesday, the <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> daily <ORGANIZATION> Pravda </ORGANIZATION> said that during a Tuesday rally in <LOCATION> Yerevan </LOCATION>'s Theater Square, someone began calling for a blockade of the airport and a large column of people headed toward it on foot. Pravda said planes were allowed to land, but demonstrators `` grossly disrupted order'' and prevented them from taking off again. Hundreds of passengers were stranded, it said. `` Vremya'' said 3,000 people took part in the protest and 60 flights were grounded along with 14,000 passengers. <PERSON> Perfilyev </PERSON> said about 400 people occupied the airport's terminal; another 1,500 gathered outside, according to the official <ORGANIZATION> Tass </ORGANIZATION> news agency. The demonstrators impeded the sale of tickets and the collection of luggage, entered the landing strip and stopped passengers from coming into the terminal, <PERSON> Perfilyev </PERSON> said. Security troops then moved in to evict the protesters, who began hurling rocks and bottles _ and that's when the 36 casualties occurred, he said. In <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION>, Armenian activists said witnesses had telephoned them from <LOCATION> Yerevan </LOCATION> to say army troops carrying machine guns and backed by tanks had begun firing without warning on the protesters. `` All of a sudden, they started shooting,'' artist <PERSON> Kuryun </PERSON> <PERSON> G. </PERSON> <PERSON> Nagapetyan </PERSON> told about 50 people who gathered for a rally outside <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION>'s red-brick Armenian church. `` They were carrying clubs, like policemen in the <LOCATION> West </LOCATION>, and they beat people right and left.'' Three students were killed, he said, and 37 people reportedly were hospitalized. <PERSON> Alexei </PERSON> <PERSON> Mananikov </PERSON>, an editor of the unofficial <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> journal Glasnost, said at least one man was killed and as many as 40 people wounded by soldiers at the airport. Lev. <PERSON> G. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gambaryan </PERSON>, another A