<HEAD>Nationalists Open Party Congress With Tough Talk On Communists,
Violence</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SHIRLEY LAI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LINKOU, Taiwan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 President <PERSON> Lee </PERSON> <PERSON> Teng-hui </PERSON> opened a key congress of the ruling <ORGANIZATION> Nationalist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> today with a cautious promise of more democratic change and tough talk on rival Communist <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>. The landmark meeting began at a suburban <LOCATION> Taipei </LOCATION> sports stadium packed with more than 10,000 people. Behind the podium hung three huge portraits of the 94-year-old party's three previous leaders _ <PERSON> Sun </PERSON> <PERSON> Yat-sen </PERSON>, <PERSON> Chiang </PERSON> <PERSON> Kai-shek </PERSON> and his son, <PERSON> Chiang </PERSON> <PERSON> Ching-kuo </PERSON>, who died in January. The congress, the party's 13th, is the first in which delegates were not handpicked by top party officials and in which a <ORGANIZATION> Central </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> election was not restricted to candidates proposed by the party leader. It comes at a time of increasing political liberalization in <LOCATION> Taiwan </LOCATION>, a nation slowly emerging from its authoritarian past. The congress' 1,209 delegates are expected to elevate a new generation of party leaders to replace aging conservatives who came from the mainland with <PERSON> Chiang </PERSON> <PERSON> Kai-shek </PERSON> after the Communists forced the Nationalists from mainland <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> in 1949. An overhaul of the Cabinet also is expected after the congress, with speculation centering on the fate of 74-year-old Premier <PERSON> Yu </PERSON> <PERSON> Kuo-hwa </PERSON>, who is viewed as the leading conservative. <PERSON> Lee </PERSON>, the acting party chairman since <PERSON> Chiang </PERSON>'s death, said in his speech that the Nationalists `` should accelerate the implementation of the reforms initiated by late Chairman <PERSON> Chiang </PERSON> <PERSON> Ching-kuo </PERSON> with an even more active and responsible attitude.'' But he cautioned that `` extremism and violence are the greatest enemies of democracy,'' an apparent reference to recent street demonstrations for accelerated political change. Those protests have occasionally turned violent. In his final years, <PERSON> Chiang </PERSON> <PERSON> Ching-kuo </PERSON> ended <LOCATION> Taiwan </LOCATION>'s 38-year-old martial law, tolerated the formation of opposition parties, opened the door to unofficial contact with rival Communist <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> and relaxed controls on the press. In cautiously pushing more reform, <PERSON> Lee </PERSON>'s speech appeared tailored to placate both aging Nationalist conservatives, some of whom may step down during the congress, and younger party members who support more political, social and economic liberalization. <PERSON> Winston </PERSON> <PERSON> Chang </PERSON>, a party delegate, described <PERSON> Lee </PERSON> as `` a man of tolerance'' with elements of a good party leader. Indeed, <PERSON> Lee </PERSON> is expected to be named the party's permanent chairman on Friday. `` He accepts different opinions and absorbs them,'' said <PERSON> Chang </PERSON>, an illegitimate son of <PERSON> Chiang </PERSON> <PERSON> Ching-kuo </PERSON> who took his mother's surname <PERSON> Lee </PERSON> spent much of his 30-minute speech reiterating <LOCATION> Taiwan </LOCATION>'s hardline policy of no official contacts with the Chinese Communists Both the Nationalists, or Kuomintang, and Communists claim to be the rightful ruler of mainland <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Taiwan </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Lee </PERSON> accused <LOCATION> Beijing </LOCATION> of having `` blind ambition to destroy'' the Nationalist government. `` We have no illusions about the <ORGANIZATION> Chinese </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> regime and will make no compromise of any kind with them.'' The Nationalists have rejected <LOCATION> Beijing </LOCATION>'s call for reunification under a `` one country, two systems'' policy in which <LOCATION> Taiwan </LOCATION> could retain its capitalist economy. Unofficial contact between the two sides has increased recently, particularly with <PERSON> Chiang </PERSON> <PERSON> Ching-kuo </PERSON>'s decision last year to end a ban on travel to the mainland to allow family reunions. Indirect trade also has increased and many businessmen are seeking permission to invest and trade directly with <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>'s 1 billion people. The future <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> policy of this nation of about 20 million people is expected to be a hot topic at the congress, with some delegates pushing for increased trade and exchanges.
