<HEAD>Decline In Dollar Helps Cut US Labor Costs</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MATT YANCEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Labor Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 With the smallest wage increases of any industrial nation and help from a sinking dollar, <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> factories outperformed their foreign rivals last year in reducing labor costs and making their goods more competitive on world markets. Measured in devalued American dollars, labor costs in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> declined 1.5 percent in 1987, compared with increases of 7.5 percent in <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION>, 7.7 percent in <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION>, 13.5 percent in <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> and 23.9 percent in <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>, the <ORGANIZATION> Labor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> said Wednesday. But even before the dramatic devaluation of the dollar against major European and <LOCATION> Asian </LOCATION> currencies, the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> outperformed all but <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> in keeping a lid on labor costs. Measured by their own currency, the yen, Japanese manufacturers reduced their labor costs by 2.5 percent. Excluding <LOCATION> France </LOCATION>, labor costs rose for nine other major industrial powers. `` Clearly there's a definite improvement in out competitiveness vis-a-vis our trading partners,'' said <PERSON> Allen </PERSON> <PERSON> Sinai </PERSON>, chief economist for the <ORGANIZATION> Boston </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, a <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> consulting house. `` But we still have a long way to go to restore the competitiveness we lost over the past decade.'' The government data showed that labor costs, measured in American dollars, rose an average 3.3 percent annually from 1979 through 1985 while falling 2.3 percent in <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>, 1.8 percent in <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION>, 4.8 percent in <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION> and 2.4 percent in <LOCATION> Great </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>. Wage increases in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> averaging 6.9 percent annually those years also outpaced the gains enjoyed by workers in all of the other countries when measured in dollars. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> manufacturers, however, held hourly wage and benefit increases last year to just 1.3 percent, the lowest of any of the industrial powers, according to the government data. <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> was close with wage and benefit increases averaging 1.4 percent. But wages rose 4 percent in <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION> and 4.5 percent in <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION> while soaring 8.2 percent in <LOCATION> Great </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>. But with civilian unemployment in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> now hovering in the range of 5 -LCB- percent, <PERSON> Sinai </PERSON> noted that wage increases have been escalating rapidly the past two months. `` That suggests that our labor costs are rising at the same time that the dollar has quit falling,'' <PERSON> Sinai </PERSON> said. `` This year we will not repeat the experience of last year.'' For one thing, he said, declines in the industrial sectors of <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Great </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION> have all bottomed out and they are begining to enjoy the same rebound in manufacturing that the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> has experienced in the past year. The Labor Department figures, in fact, showed that manufacturing growth last year was slower in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> than in <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Italy </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Great </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> productivity improvements at 2.8 percent also were smaller than 4 percent gains of <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> France </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Italy </LOCATION>, 7 percent increase in <LOCATION> Great </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION> and nearly 8 percent improvement in <LOCATION> Norway </LOCATION>. While five of the nine countries had larger 1987 productivity increases than the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, only <LOCATION> Great </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Norway </LOCATION> exceeded the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> rate of improvement over the past two years, the government said. However, only the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION> experienced any employment growth in manufacturing last year. The <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> increase was only one-half of 1 percent, but it reversed two straight years of declines. Factory jobs remained about the same in <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Sweden </LOCATION> and fell by 1 percent to 2.5 percent in the other countries. For <LOCATION> France </LOCATION>, 1987 was the 13th consecutive year of manufacturing employment declines and in <LOCATION> Great </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION> factory jobs have been falling in number for the past 10 years.
