<HEAD>Exchange Students Tour Landfill, Trash Incinerator on First Outing</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID TIRRELL-WYSOCKI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LEBANON, N.H. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Soviet exchange students spending the summer at picturesque <ORGANIZATION> Dartmouth </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> College </ORGANIZATION> made their first official excursion off campus _ to a dump, a metal recycling operation and a trash incinerator. Not exactly the kind of trip you would write home about, unless you were majoring in environmental studies, which they are. So the garbage bags, piles of tires, crushed cars and discarded wood were just want they wanted to see. `` Welcome to the city of <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION> landfill,'' dump superintendent <PERSON> Alfred </PERSON> <PERSON> Besaw </PERSON> said Wednesday as the students gathered close to hear how his operation works. Some took notes, others took photos of news photographers taking photos of them and one consulted a Russian-American dictionary before asking a question about the trash. The 16 Soviet students have been in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hampshire </LOCATION> since late June, part of an exchange in which 16 Americans, mostly from <LOCATION> Dartmouth </LOCATION>, spent about six weeks at <ORGANIZATION> Moscow </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION>. The students major in areas including chemistry, molecular biology and biophysics. Most have completed four years of their five-year college studies and will likely be scientists, teachers and researchers in the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>, which is trying to deal with the same environmental problems plaguing the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> _ water and air pollution, acid rain, hazardous waste and trash disposal. The outing to the dump and Signal Environmental Systems' refuse-to-energy plant in <LOCATION> Claremont </LOCATION> was the first time the students met reporters, which meant interviews atop clay-covered mounds of trash, next to cans of discarded copper tubing or next to a garbage truck being weighed before dumping its load at the incinerator They drove from the hot, dusty dump to an adjacent hotter and dustier metal recycling area, where a shirtless <PERSON> Fred </PERSON> <PERSON> Janci </PERSON> of <ORGANIZATION> Janci </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Metal </ORGANIZATION> and Recycling explained his business. <PERSON> Dimitrij </PERSON> <PERSON> Kavtaradze </PERSON>, a <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> State professor teaching at <LOCATION> Dartmouth </LOCATION> this year, picked up a horseshoe _ `` This is the best souvenir from <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>, good luck!'' _ and asked <PERSON> Janci </PERSON> if he could keep it. <PERSON> Janci </PERSON> said yes. After seeing how trash is buried or prepared for re-use, it was off to the incinerator to learn about another way to dispose of refuse, burning _ again taking pictures and notes. Professor <PERSON> Burdin </PERSON> <PERSON> Konstantin </PERSON>, also from <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> State, said the main purpose of the visit is to learn how the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> deals with environmental problems. `` The main thing is to see what kinds of problems are in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and how do you solve these problems,'' <PERSON> Konstantin </PERSON> said. The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, he said, `` is on the frontier'' of dealing with environmental problems. The American experience, he said, should help Soviets struggling with the same problems, especially with questions of balancing growth with the environment and even with citizen opposition to construction projects such as a sewer proposal that prompted protest near <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION>. And the exchange experience may help his students understand more about <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>. `` We should understand people. We should understand problems. We can not separate problems and people,'' he said. `` In some ways it's people diplomacy. Some of the students talked about their first impressions of the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, saying they were impressed with the highways and friendly people. `` They are very friendly people,'' said <PERSON> Olga </PERSON> <PERSON> Divovich </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION>. `` They often smile at us and it's very pleasant for us.''
