<HEAD>A Brief Look at the Mexico Election</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Mexico Elections, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MEXICO CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Here, at a glance, are some facts and figures about the election in <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION>:
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
 THE PRESIDENCY _ Four men and one woman are running for a single, six-year term that begins Dec. 1. The three major candidates are <PERSON> Carlos </PERSON> <PERSON> Salinas </PERSON> <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> Gortari </PERSON> of the ruling <ORGANIZATION> Institutional </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Revolutionary </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>, known as the <ORGANIZATION> PRI </ORGANIZATION>; <PERSON> Cuauhtemoc </PERSON> <PERSON> Cardenas </PERSON> of the leftist <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Front </ORGANIZATION> coalition; and <PERSON> Manuel </PERSON> <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Clouthier </PERSON> of the conservative <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Action </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>. Also running are <PERSON> Rosario </PERSON> <PERSON> Ibarra </PERSON> <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> Piedra </PERSON> of the radical <ORGANIZATION> Revolutionary </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Workers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> and <PERSON> Gumersindo </PERSON> <PERSON> Magana </PERSON> <PERSON> Negrete </PERSON> of the tiny <ORGANIZATION> Mexican </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
 THE SENATE _ Voters elect 64 senators, two from each of <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION>'s 31 states and two from the federal district Like presidents, senators serve six years and can not be re-elected. <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> has had only one opposition senator under <ORGANIZATION> PRI </ORGANIZATION> rule.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
 CHAMBER of DEPUTIES _ 500 members of the lower house will be elected for three-year terms, expanding the size of the current chamber by 100. The ruling party has 289 seats. The rest are spread among nine opposition parties.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
 THE ISSUES _ Election fraud, a stagnating economy hobbled by inflation and a massive foreign debt.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
 THE VOTERS _ About 38 million out of an estimated 80 million population are registered. More than 10 percent have five years or less education, more than 61 percent are under 40. The electorate is about evenly split between men and women.
</TEXT>
