<HEAD>Southern Haylift To Reach `Yankee Friends' Today</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NU3</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PATRICIA BIBBY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
 Southern farmers sent more than 1,500 bales of hay to the drought-stricken <LOCATION> Midwest </LOCATION>, saying they had n't forgotten their `` Yankee friends,'' while marijuana growers in <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION> dug water pits to keep their million-dollar weeds wet. Farmers of legal crops in <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION> hoped to receive 1,000 bales of hay today, courtesy of <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Carolina </LOCATION> farmers returning a favor paid to them two years ago. And for the first time in weeks, barges were not stalled on the drought-shoaled <LOCATION> Mississppi </LOCATION> <LOCATION> River </LOCATION>. `` We're glad to show our <ORGANIZATION> Yankee </ORGANIZATION> friends we have n't forgotten them,'' <PERSON> Jim </PERSON> <PERSON> Graham </PERSON>, <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Carolina </LOCATION>'s commissioner of agriculture, said Wednesday after he threw a bale of hay onto a tractor-trailer. `` This is a good will effort on our part to reciprocate for what they did for us two years ago,'' <PERSON> Graham </PERSON> said. `` We're paying them back.'' <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION> was one of several Midwestern states that came to the aid of Southern farmers during the drought of 1986. This year, the <LOCATION> Midwest </LOCATION> has been suffering from what has been called the worst drought in 50 years. Also on Wednesday, a livestock truck loaded with about 450 bales of hay donated by <LOCATION> Burlington </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.C. </LOCATION>, farmers departed for <LOCATION> Kentucky </LOCATION> from the <ORGANIZATION> Piedmont </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Livestock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co </ORGANIZATION>. In <LOCATION> Oklahoma </LOCATION>, six <LOCATION> Burlington </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Northern </LOCATION> rail cars filled with 172 tons of donated hay left for <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Dakota </LOCATION>. Organizer <PERSON> Larry </PERSON> <PERSON> Jones </PERSON> said the hay should arr