<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Prices fell on the <ORGANIZATION> Tokyo </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> today and the dollar slipped. Dealers attributed the yen's rise to fears that the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> trade deficit may grow and Japanese official statements against letting the dollar appreciate further. The dollar closed at 132.40 yen, down 1.13 yen from Wednesday's close Its high for the day was 132.98 yen and its low was 131.65. On the <ORGANIZATION> Tokyo </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>, the <ORGANIZATION> Nikkei </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Average </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> 225 </ORGANIZATION> selected issues lost 38.47 points or 0.13 percent to move to 27,728.13. It had gained 189.43 points Wednesday on near-record trading volume of 2.8 billion. Today's volume was 2 billion shares. A broker for Vickers da Costa, who spoke on condition he not be identified, said concerns about <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> trade figures to be released next week put pressure on the dollar. He also said there was more confidence in the market after Japanese officials said they would n't let the dollar appreciate much more. `` If the dollar gets much stronger, you could well see intervention,'' he said. An exchange dealer at the <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Tokyo </ORGANIZATION> said the market's mood was bearish toward the dollar amid relatively quiet trading. `` The exchange rates are moving toward adjustment,'' said the dealer, who spoke on condition of anonymity. The dollar hit 134.85 yen Monday, its highest closing rate since Nov. 24. It had risen rapidly by nearly 10 yen in the previous three weeks.
