<HEAD>Mexico At-a-Glance</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Mexico-Elections, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
 Here, at a glance, are facts and figures about <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION>:
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
 GEOGRAPHY _ <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> forms the southern part of <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>, connecting the Central American isthmus with the bulk of the continent. It shares a 2,062-mile border with the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> defined by the 1848 Treaty of <LOCATION> Hidalgo </LOCATION>, in which <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> gave up half its territory for $ 15 million. <LOCATION> Guatemala </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Belize </LOCATION> border <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> to the southeast. There are 31 states and the Federal District, the core area of the <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION> metropolitan area.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
 POPULATION _ <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> has 80 million people, 20 million of whom live in the <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION> metropolitan area. About 55 percent of Mexicans are of <LOCATION> Spanish-Indian </LOCATION> heritage; 29 percent are Indian; and 10 percent Caucasian. More than 90 percent of Mexicans are <ORGANIZATION> Roman </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Catholic </ORGANIZATION>. Spanish is the official language.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
 GOVERNMENT _ The government, a federal republic, is headed by President <PERSON> Miguel </PERSON> de la <LOCATION> Madrid </LOCATION>, 53. A member of the <ORGANIZATION> Institutional </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Revolutionary </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>, or <ORGANIZATION> PRI </ORGANIZATION>, he became president Dec. 1, 1982 and his term ends on Nov. 30. The power of the Mexican presidency overshadows <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION>'s judiciary and legislature. All 44 members of the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> belong to the <ORGANIZATION> PRI </ORGANIZATION>. An electoral reform law provides for the number of seats reserved for opposition parties to expand from 100 to 150 in the <ORGANIZATION> Chamber </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Deputies </ORGANIZATION>, which is increasing this year to 500 members.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
 ECONOMY _ <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> has a mixed economy with the government holding several key industries. It is heavily dependent on oil, the primary source of revenues needed to pay its $ 104 billion foreign debt, the developing world's second-highest. Oil exports earned $ 7.9 billion in 1987. Inflation reached a record 159.2 percent last year, and the government froze wages, prices and the peso-dollar exchange rate to bring it under control. Inflation was 32.4 percent between January and April.
</TEXT>
