</TEXT>
<DATELINE>ASHFORD, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Officials from the towns of <LOCATION> Ashford </LOCATION> and <PERSON> Willington </PERSON> could n't see the boundary markers for the trees, but are still hoping to `` walk the line'' to settle a longstanding border dispute once fall arrives. Officials of the rural northeastern <LOCATION> Connecticut </LOCATION> towns decided to resort to the method used for centuries by <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> England </LOCATION> farmers to re-establish property lines each spring after being told that an engineer's survey of the 20 acres of disputed land would cost about $ 40,000. They tried Wendesday night, but had to abandon the effort when they discovered heavy woods made it too difficult to get their bearings. `` If we're going to actually do any walking, we've decided we have to do it when there are n't any leaves on the trees, because it's just too hard to see anything at all,'' said Ashford First Selectwoman <PERSON> Paula </PERSON> <PERSON> Faulkner </PERSON>. The officials did locate one of the key markers during their abbreviated walk Wednesday night. They expect to continue the exercise in September or October, said <PERSON> Willington </PERSON> First Selectman <PERSON> Carlton </PERSON> <PERSON> Csiki </PERSON>. `` It's a country problem, we're country people and we'll most likely resolve it in a country fashion,'' he said.
