o records indicating the origin or destination of the vessel or who was in charge of the operation. The 180-foot Encounter Bay was not flying a flag when it was spotted late last week about 600 miles offshore. The owner of the Encounter Bay was listed as <ORGANIZATION> Countess </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Shipping </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION>, and the 18-member crew included three Americans, one from <LOCATION> England </LOCATION>, one from <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Zealand </LOCATION> and 13 from <LOCATION> Indonesia </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Thailand </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Singapore </LOCATION>. Sixteen appeared Wednesday before <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Magistrate <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Weinberg </PERSON> and were advised of their rights and possible charges against them, and two others were to appear for the same purpose today when a <LOCATION> Thai </LOCATION> interpreter would be available. All are held in custody pending a detention hearing on Monday, when bail, if any, will be set, said deputy clerk <PERSON> Karen </PERSON> <PERSON> Lamborn </PERSON>. The magistrate at that time would try to determine whether there was probable cause to send the case to a grand jury, she said. If it can be proved the ship was headed for the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, crew members could prison terms of a few years to life, said <PERSON> Gary </PERSON> <PERSON> Liming </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Drug </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Enforcement </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION> special agent-in-charge. The Encounter Bay's crew was cooperative but not talkative, <PERSON> Allison </PERSON> said. He estimated there was 72 tons of high-grade marijuana on board in about 8,000 `` bales'' packed into four large shipping containers. Each `` bale,'' in a blue nylon sack, contained eight packets of marijuana vacuum-sealed in double plastic wrappings.
