<HEAD>Blast Measures 5.6 on Richter Scale, Felt in Las Vegas</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT MACY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LAS VEGAS, Nev. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A nuclear weapons test rocked the <LOCATION> Nevada </LOCATION> desert today, registering 5.6 on the <PERSON> Richter </PERSON> scale and causing a swaying motion in high-rise buildings here, 100 miles from ground zero. <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Minsch </PERSON>, a spokesman for the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Earthquake </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Information </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Golden </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Colo. </LOCATION>, said the reading indicated the test was one of the larger ones conducted at the desert site. The device was detonated 40 miles from Mercury, a tiny town on the <LOCATION> Nevada </LOCATION> Test Site where Soviet nuclear scientists are based while preparing for a joint U.S.-Soviet test next month. A controller in the tower at <LOCATION> McCarran </LOCATION> <LOCATION> International </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Airport </LOCATION> in <LOCATION> Las </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Vegas </LOCATION> said the tower rocked slightly seconds after the blast, at 8:05 a.m.. A telephone switchboard operator at <ORGANIZATION> Fitzgerald </ORGANIZATION>'s Hotel in downtown Las Vegas said a guest on the 29th floor called to ask why she felt ground motion And a receptionist at the Lionel, <PERSON> Sawyer </PERSON> law firm, atop a high-rise office building downtown, said she felt a `` dizzy, swirling feeling'' at the time of the blast. She said a hanging plant in the office began swaying. All three declined to give their names. Motion was recorded on <ORGANIZATION> Energy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> seismographs atop several hotel-casinos on the <LOCATION> Las </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Vegas </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Strip </LOCATION> and downtown. Motion was also recorded at Scotty's Castle in <LOCATION> Death </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Valley </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Calif. </LOCATION>, west of the test site. The <PERSON> Richter </PERSON> scale is a measure of ground motion as recorded on seismographs. An earthquake or explosion of 3.5 on the <PERSON> Richter </PERSON> scale can cause slight damage in the local area, 4 moderate damage, 5 considerable damage, 6 severe The test was delayed five minutes while controllers checked out a malfunctioning signal. <ORGANIZATION> Energy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Chris </PERSON> <PERSON> West </PERSON> said the test appeared to be normal, with no indications of any problems. West, who was in a control center 25 miles from ground zero, said monitors at the site indicated no radiation had escaped the ground. He said slight ground motion was felt in the control center. Today's test was the eighth conducted this year, and the sixth conducted with Soviet scientists on site. The Soviet scientists arrived earlier this year to begin preparing for next month's joint verification experiment. The Soviet scientists will monitor a <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> test in mid-August and <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> scientists will monitor a Soviet test a month later. The experiments are designed to determine the ability of each country to monitor the size of the other's tests. Such monitoring capabilities are critical in test limitation treaties. The DOE had issued a warning to managers of high-rise buildings in <LOCATION> Las </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Vegas </LOCATION> not to have workers in precarious positions at the time of today's detonation. Such warnings are issued only when the test is near 150 kilotons, the upper limits allowable under U.S.-Soviet treaties. The nuclear device was buried 2,000 feet beneath the surface of <LOCATION> Pahute </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Mesa </LOCATION>, about 100 miles northwest of <LOCATION> Las </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Vegas </LOCATION>. The most recent previous test was June 22, when two nuclear devices were detonated simultaneously in a rare experiment.
