<HEAD>Number of Teacher Strikes Unchanged at 87, Group Says</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Public school teachers staged 87 strikes in 14 states in 1987-88, the same number as the year before, a group opposed to public employee unions said Thursday. But there were more teachers involved in the 876 walkouts and almost three times as many students missed classes, the <ORGANIZATION> Public </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Research </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Foundation </ORGANIZATION> said. It said 66,043 teachers went out on strike at some point during the school year that just ended, and 945,793 students missed classes. It said in 1986-87, there were 87 strikes in a dozen states, affecting 49,546 teachers and 326,431 students. The foundation, part of an organization that opposes collective bargaining for public employees, published the figures in its fortnightly newsletter, The Government Union Critique. <PERSON> Peter </PERSON> <PERSON> W. </PERSON> <PERSON> Katsirubas </PERSON>, editor of the newsletter, said that if a school district kept schools open with substitute or non-striking teachers, students were not counted as missing classes. The biggest strike last year was the 19-day walkout by 24,000 teachers in <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION>, affecting 400,000 students. It was the ninth <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION> strike in the past 19 years. The board of education had sought to freeze teachers' wages. <PERSON> Katsirubas </PERSON> said he tallied 71 teacher strikes in 1985-86 and 100 in 1984-85. Teacher union leaders contend there are fewer strikes these days and many of those that do occur are defensive ones. Teacher salaries have risen faster than inflation for the past seven years and the average teacher now earns more than $ 28,000, the highest ever in real dollars.
