o woo an ethnic group close to the heart of the <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION> governor. The vice president will speak in <LOCATION> Boston </LOCATION> tonight before a Greek Orthodox diocesean dinner. Aides said he would talk about the importance of religion. Underscoring the political importance of Hispanics, <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> spoke in <LOCATION> Dallas </LOCATION> before the convention of the <ORGANIZATION> League </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Latin </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Citizens </ORGANIZATION> -LRB- <ORGANIZATION> LULAC </ORGANIZATION> -RRB-, the largest and oldest Hispanic civic group. Although <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> does not speak Spanish, he arranged for his son, <PERSON> Jeb </PERSON>, to fly in from <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION> to make a pitch for him. <PERSON> Jeb </PERSON> <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>, who speaks Spanish and is married to a woman from <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION>, is popular with Hispanic groups. Pledging to put a Hispanic in his Cabinet, <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> said, it was `` good to acknowledge that some things are, at this point, owed.'' He said his promise was something `` I have never made before, to anyone, to any group.'' However, he said, `` It is time. It is time and it's long overdue, and that is a solemn pledge.'' <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> said <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s vow to name a Hispanic to the Cabinet was `` about a year too late.'' <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> made the same pledge in June 1987 to the LULAC convention, held last year in <LOCATION> Corpus </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Christi </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> was to address the group on Thursday, followed by <PERSON> Jesse </PERSON> <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> on Friday. At a news conference, <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> said he would not make similar promises to other groups. `` I will be very open-minded and broad-based in who I select to serve in my <ORGANIZATION> Cabinet </ORGANIZATION>, but I'm addressing myself to righting a wrong that has been out there for many years.'' Asked if he would make a similar promise to Asian Americans, <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> said, `` I'd have to go back there and research that out.'' <PERSON> Oscar </PERSON> <PERSON> Moran </PERSON>, the Hispanic group's president, said of <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>, `` He attracted the attention of some voters who already decided on <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>. Now they will pay attention to him.'' But <PERSON> Tony </PERSON> <PERSON> Bonilla </PERSON>, an influential Democrat whom <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> singled out by name as a person he had tried to recruit for the <ORGANIZATION> GOP </ORGANIZATION>, was unmoved by the vice president's promise to put a Hispanic in the Cabinet. <PERSON> Bonilla </PERSON> said it was `` a little patronizing'' for <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> to make such a statement after serving eight years in the <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration without a Hispanic in the inner circle. `` The vice president needs to say to the president right now, ` We have goofed. We have not reciprocated to the Hispanic community''' for their support, said <PERSON> Bonilla </PERSON>, a former chairman of <ORGANIZATION> LULAC </ORGANIZATION> and the head of the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hispanic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Leadership </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Conference </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> said he had discussed the idea of a Hispanic in the Cabinet with President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>, but he added, `` I'm not president of the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>.'' His commitment was a measure of the political importance of Hispanics, particularly in key battleground states like <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION> which have a large Spanish-spe