<FIRST>r w AM-ElNinoPrediction     07-07 0687</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-El Nino Prediction,650</SECOND>
<NOTE>For Release 6:30 p.m. EDT</NOTE>
<HEAD>Scientists Report Successful El Nino Predictions</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RANDOLPH E. SCHMID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Last year's mild <ORGANIZATION> El </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nino </ORGANIZATION>, a puzzling phenomenon in which global weather disruptions follow a warming of the <LOCATION> Pacific </LOCATION>, was predicted by three different climate models, according to scientists who hope they can now serve distant warning of future recurrences. `` Looking at the results ... we feel there is a good chance of being able to assess these things as much as a year ahead. And over time we expect to get better,'' said <PERSON> Stephen </PERSON> <PERSON> Zebiak </PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION> Columbia </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Lamont-Doherty </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Geological </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Laboratory </ORGANIZATION>. `` Time will show how much value these kinds of models and predictions can have. Until there is a consensus on that, we do n't expect to see governments taking action readily based on them, although I do think that eventually that will happen,'' <PERSON> Zebiak </PERSON> said Thursday in a telephone interview `` It's a new kind of game, really, a lot of people are still quite skeptical about it.'' The successful predictions of the 1986-87 <ORGANIZATION> El </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nino </ORGANIZATION> are being formally reported in Friday's edition of Science magazine. <PERSON> El </PERSON> <PERSON> Ninos </PERSON>, still not fully understood, are events that appear to affect weather around the world. One that occurred in 1982-83, described as the strongest in this century, was blamed for an estimated 1,500 deaths and damage of $ 2 billion to $ 8 billion worldwide. The 1986-87 El Nino had much less impact, although some unusual weather was reported, including heavy rains in coastal <LOCATION> Peru </LOCATION> and drought in <LOCATION> India </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> Pacific </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Northwest </LOCATION> of the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. The events are preceded by unusually warm water temperatures in the <LOCATION> Pacific </LOCATION> and changes in barometric pressure over that ocean. <PERSON> Zebiak </PERSON> said the climate studies currently show cooler than normal <LOCATION> Pacific </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Ocean </LOCATION> temperatures _ the opposite of an <LOCATION> El </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Nino </LOCATION> _ for at least the balance of this year. These cold events do not seem to have the climate impact of the warmer <ORGANIZATION> El </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ninos </ORGANIZATION>, he added. <ORGANIZATION> El </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ninos </ORGANIZATION> take their name from the Spanish word for child, a reference to the Christ Child. This was coined by Peruvian fishermen to refer to the recurring phenomenon, which sharply reduced their fish supply and was often first noticed at Christmas time. Scientists, combining that name with a reference to changes in <LOCATION> Pacific </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Indian </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Ocean </LOCATION> air pressure, usually use the term <ORGANIZATION> ENSO </ORGANIZATION>, for El Nino-Southern Oscillation. The three different climate models that predicted the 1986-87 <LOCATION> El </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Nino </LOCATION> were: _ The Lamont-Doherty model developed by <PERSON> Mark </PERSON> <PERSON> Cane </PERSON>, <PERSON> Zebiak </PERSON> and <PERSON> Sean </PERSON> <PERSON> Dolan </PERSON> This model uses a computer to calculate changes in the ocean and atmosphere, and their relations with one another. Termed a `` dynamic'' model, meaning it uses mathematical formulas to calculate changes, it predicted the <ORGANIZATION> El </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nino </ORGANIZATION> more than a year ahead of time. _ A model based primarily on changing ocean conditions, coupled with unusual wind currents, developed by <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> O'Brien </PERSON> and <PERSON> D. </PERSON> <PERSON> Legler </PERSON> of <ORGANIZATION> Florida </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> This combined dynamic and statistical information and can issue predictions a few months in advance, <PERSON> Zebiak </PERSON> explained. _ A statistical model using wind patterns and sea-level air pressure readings over the <LOCATION> Pacific </LOCATION> and Indian oceans, which can give predictions with lead times of 3 to 9 months This pair or related models was developed by <PERSON> Timothy </PERSON> <PERSON> Barnett </PERSON> and <PERSON> Nicholas </PERSON> <PERSON> E. </PERSON> <PERSON> Graham </PERSON> at <ORGANIZATION> Scripps </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Oceanography </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> La </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Jolla </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Calif </LOCATION>. In the case of the 1986-87 <ORGANIZATION> El </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nino </ORGANIZATION>, all three models wound up making the same prediction, just at different times, <PERSON> Zebiak </PERSON> said. `` It is interesting that different models, which are based on quite different kinds of approaches, are showing consistency. I think it is basically encouraging, another piece of evidence that there really is a robust kind of signal here, which we are capturing in different ways.'' `` The fact is that these kind of forecasts are a reality now, they will continue. We and the other people are doing it sort of routinely now. What remains to be assessed is the kind of feeling for exactly how reliable they are going to be in the situations that nature throws our way,'' <PERSON> Zebiak </PERSON> said.
