<HEAD>With PM-Rushmore Fire</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
 Wildfires crackled through the country's parched forests, including a 10,000-acre blaze that threatened Mount Rushmore National Memorial and an 118,000-acre fire that burned within 10 miles of the trans-Alaska oil pipeline. More than 1,000 people had been evacuated by early today from the <LOCATION> Custer </LOCATION> <LOCATION> State </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Park </LOCATION> fire in <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Dakota </LOCATION> near the granite monument to four presidents. In <LOCATION> Alaska </LOCATION>, hundreds of firefighters battled three of the state's more serious wildfires as weather forecasts continued to offer scant hope for rain The fire burning near the pipeline on the <ORGANIZATION> Yukon </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Flats </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Wildlife </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Refuge </ORGANIZATION> grew from 110,000 acres on Monday, <ORGANIZATION> Bureau </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Land </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Management </ORGANIZATION> spokeswoman <PERSON> Sue </PERSON> <PERSON> Mitchell </PERSON> said. About 80 firefighters were assigned to the fire that is one of three the <ORGANIZATION> BLM </ORGANIZATION> either manned or monitored on the refuge. `` What they're trying to do is stop it from getting any closer to the pipeline,'' <PERSON> Mitchell </PERSON> said. The pipeline is made of heavy-gauge steel and `` is not susceptible to serious damage from a fire of that nature,'' said <PERSON> Tom </PERSON> <PERSON> Brennan </PERSON>, a spokesman for <ORGANIZATION> Alyeska </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Pipeline </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co </ORGANIZATION>. But, he said, `` We would rather not have it in the area of a pump station, because those are manned, for one thing.'' Firefighters in <LOCATION> Utah </LOCATION> finished cutting fire lines today around an 850-acre blaze that has blackened oak, brush and <PERSON> Ponderosa </PERSON> pine in Zion National Park. They expected to have the fire contained by tonight, officials said. The fire began June 19 and was allowed to burn in a small `` conditional area'' in accordance with park policy allowing natural fires to take their course, said Chief Ranger <PERSON> Bob </PERSON> <PERSON> Andrew </PERSON>. On Sunday, however, winds gusting to 60 mph fanned the flames out of the conditional area, and up to 200 firefighters were brought in. In southern <LOCATION> Utah </LOCATION>, 45 firefighters battled a 3,500-acre fire that broke out late Wednesday on <ORGANIZATION> Bureau </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Land </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Management </ORGANIZATION> and private land about three miles north of <LOCATION> Beryl </LOCATION> near the <LOCATION> Nevada </LOCATION> border. Spokeswoman <PERSON> Eulail </PERSON> <PERSON> Pickering </PERSON> said the fire was 85 percent contained and crews anticipated full containment later today. Another fire in wilderness area that also began June 19, was being held in check at 3,400 acres in south-central <LOCATION> Montana </LOCATION>. The lightning-caused fire was allowed to burn in the <ORGANIZATION> Absaroka </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Beartooth </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Wilderness </ORGANIZATION> until it flared up over the Independence Day weekend and burned more than 1,600 acres. Smokejumpers worked the north face of the fire Wednesday while four helicopters dropped water and foam, said information officer <PERSON> Jo </PERSON> <PERSON> Barnier </PERSON> in the Billings Interagency Fire Center. <LOCATION> Wyoming </LOCATION> firefighters, aided by cooler temperatures and a drop in winds overnight, contained a 1,300-acre fire in the <ORGANIZATION> Bridger-Teton </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Forest </ORGANIZATION> at 6 a.m. today, forest officials said. Two volunteer firefighters were injured, one seriously, battling the blaze, said forest spokesman <PERSON> Fred </PERSON> <PERSON> Kingwill </PERSON>. `` We still have a ways to go before we'll call it controlled,'' he said, adding that the wind in the next few days will determine the future of the fire. Officials originally said the fire had burned up 1,500 acres but downgraded the acreage to 1,300 after fire lines were dug and the blaze could be reassessed. In Yellowstone National Park, three fires covering nearly 1,900 acres of backcountry still were burning Wednesday. The fires, one covering 1,800 acres in the northwestern corner of the park and two others near <LOCATION> Shoshone </LOCATION> and <PERSON> Lewis </PERSON> lakes in the southern part of the park, were not threatening any structures and were being allowed to burn themselves out. Farther east, six small forest fires burned on in northeast <LOCATION> Pennsylvania </LOCATION>. Three of the fires were caused by weekend fireworks and three by arson, said <LOCATION> Lackawanna </LOCATION> <LOCATION> District </LOCATION> Forester <PERSON> Anthony </PERSON> <PERSON> Santoli </PERSON> in <LOCATION> Scranton </LOCATION>. The largest fire burned more than 75 acres of woodland on Montage Mountain, near <LOCATION> Moosic </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Santoli </PERSON> said. The other large fire charred about 60 acres at <LOCATION> Campbells </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Ledge </LOCATION>, near <LOCATION> Duryea </LOCATION>.
