<HEAD>Zoo Workers Try To Save Orphaned Porpoise</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TACOMA, Wash. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Workers at the Point Defiance Zoo and Aquarium are trying to keep alive a newborn harbor porpoise orphaned on a beach. The pup, named `` Indy'' because it was discovered on Independence Day, is believed to be only the second immature harbor porpoise kept alive in captivity, said <PERSON> Lily </PERSON> <PERSON> Moore </PERSON>, zoo information officer. A pup found last year at Point Defiance died within four months, and zoo officials said chances for the new baby porpoise's survival also are slim. Two young girls playing on the beach at the <LOCATION> Necanicum </LOCATION> <LOCATION> River </LOCATION> estuary near <LOCATION> Seaside </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ore. </LOCATION>, found the pup. The umbilicus _ the navel which quickly disappears _ was evident and the pup's dorsal fin was flaccid, which indicates a young age, <PERSON> Moore </PERSON> said. `` It's in very good shape, considering all that it's been through,'' she said. `` It conceivably could have been born on the day the girls found it.'' The porpoise arrived at the zoo Tuesday afternoon, measuring 33 inches long and weighing 16 pounds. Harbor porpoises will grow to about 5 feet long, <PERSON> Moore </PERSON> said. Visitors ca n't see the harbor porpoise because officials are trying to minimize stress on it.
