....'</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By SHARON L. JONES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN DIEGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 An 11-year-old boy accompanied by a retired <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> pilot ace today flew off on his quest to retrace <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Lindbergh </PERSON>'s historic flight to <LOCATION> Paris </LOCATION>, a 7,000-mile journey. <PERSON> Christopher </PERSON> <PERSON> Lee </PERSON> <PERSON> Marshall </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Oceano </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Calif. </LOCATION>, and <PERSON> Randy </PERSON> <PERSON> Cunningham </PERSON>, 46, departed from <LOCATION> Montgomery </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Field </LOCATION> at 8:32 a.m. today on the first leg of their trip to <LOCATION> Kerrville </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION>. The two, flying the first leg in a borrowed plane, will trade it for a new <PERSON> Mooney </PERSON> 252 aircraft built for the trans-Atlantic journey. Takeoff was originally scheduled for Monday, but was delayed by storms in <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION>. In 1927, <PERSON> Lindbergh </PERSON> flew from <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Diego </LOCATION> to <LOCATION> St. </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Louis </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Mo. </LOCATION>, then to <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION> before completing his 33 -LCB- - hour non-stop solo flight across the <LOCATION> Atlantic </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Ocean </LOCATION> to <LOCATION> Paris </LOCATION> Because <PERSON> Cunningham </PERSON> is limiting the boy's flying time to less than eight hours at a time, the trip will stretch out over five days and include stops in <LOCATION> Kernville </LOCATION>; <LOCATION> St. </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Louis </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Mo </LOCATION>.; <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>; <LOCATION> Montreal </LOCATION>; Sondestrom, <LOCATION> Greenland </LOCATION>, and <LOCATION> Reykjavik </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Iceland </LOCATION>. According to <PERSON> Chris </PERSON>, the flight to <LOCATION> Paris </LOCATION> would make him the world's youngest trans-Atlantic pilot. `` I'm very happy,'' he said shortly before takeoff. `` I am an ambassador to the youth of <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>, and I want to show all the youth that if I can do my dreams, anyone can.'' He said `` trying to stay awake'' would probably be the most difficult part, `` but I will.'' `` I'm not going to touch the controls unless there's an emergency. <PERSON> Chris </PERSON>' aviation skills are phenomenal,'' <PERSON> Cunningham </PERSON> said. The youngster has logged 200 hours, compared to <PERSON> Cunningham </PERSON>'s more than 7,000 miles <PERSON> Chris </PERSON>, the son of a commercial air pilot, gained fame last August when at age 10 he became the youngest aviator to fly across the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. In April, however, a 9-year-old from <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Juan </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Capistrano </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Calif. </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Tony </PERSON> <PERSON> Aliengena </PERSON>, broke the record by making a California-Massachusetts round trip. <PERSON> Chris </PERSON> and his mother, <PERSON> Gail </PERSON> <PERSON> Marshall </PERSON>, who live about 15 miles south of <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Luis </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Obispo </LOCATION> in central <LOCATION> California </LOCATION>, recruited <PERSON> Cunningham </PERSON> for this trip after meeting him at an air show last year. <PERSON> Cunningham </PERSON>, a retired <LOCATION> Miramar </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Naval </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Air </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Station </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Calif. </LOCATION>, commander, was the only <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> pilot ace in the Vietnam War and is the most-decorated <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> pilot, a <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> spokesman in <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Diego </LOCATION> said.
