<HEAD>Progress Urged on Nuclear Testing</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GENEVA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The 40-nation Conference on Disarmament opened its summer session Thursday with a call for progress toward banning nuclear weapons tests and chemical weapons. Swedish ambassador <PERSON> Maj </PERSON> <PERSON> Britt </PERSON> <PERSON> Theorin </PERSON>, in a keynote speech, said failure to agree on a final document at last month's <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> Special Session on Disarmament must not hamper the conference's negotiations She alleged that <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> negotiators prevented the 160-nation session from agreeing on a final document by blocking an extension of time. <LOCATION> U.S </LOCATION>. Ambassador <PERSON> Max </PERSON> <PERSON> Friedersdorf </PERSON> rejected the accusation as `` highly offensive and deeply insulting,'' saying other factors also contributed to the meeting's disappointing outcome. Starting off the 10-week conference session, <PERSON> Theorin </PERSON> said the U.S.-Soviet treaty eliminating intermediate-range nuclear missiles `` a major breakthrough for nuclear disarmament.'' She expressed hope the two superpowers will agree soon on halving their long-range nuclear arsenals. But indications that additional countries have stockpiled chemical weapons and their increasing sophistication give rise to `` grave concern,'' she told delegates to the world's only multilateral arms negotiating body. <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> have failed to agree on a deadline or any concrete commitment to speed the conference's 20-year negotiations on a comprehensive chemical weapons ban, she said. Several outstanding issues, including details of verification, could be settled `` if good will persists,'' she said. `` Time is not on our side.'' On nuclear testing, she said a comprehensive ban `` is as urgent as ever.'' She noted more than 1,600 atomic test explosions were set off by the end of last year and all five nuclear weapons states carried out tests in 1987. The U.S.-Soviet talks on nuclear testing should focus on limiting the number of tests as a step toward a comprehensive ban, <PERSON> Theorin </PERSON> said.
