<HEAD>Heat Blamed for 15 Deaths, Sends More Than 400 to Hospital</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PATRICK QUINN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATHENS, Greece (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A five-day heat wave blamed for 15 deaths combined with heavy smog in the <LOCATION> Athens </LOCATION> basin Thursday to send more than 500 people to hospitals, most with heart and breathing problems. Hospitals around the country were place on alert. Temperatures in <LOCATION> Athens </LOCATION> reached 106 degrees Fahrenheit at 2:45 p.m. for the second straight day. <LOCATION> Yugoslavia </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Greece </LOCATION>'s northern neighbor, reported at least 26 people dead in a heat wave that has gripped <LOCATION> Belgrade </LOCATION> for a week. The temperature soared to 104 degrees Wednesday. The Greek national weather service said temperatures were not expected to drop until Sunday. `` The smog of <LOCATION> Athens </LOCATION> sent 496 people to hospital with cardiac and respiratory problems as pollution reached murderous levels,'' said a statemment by the <ORGANIZATION> Panhellenic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ecologic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Studies </ORGANIZATION>. A report from the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Emergency </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Help </ORGANIZATION> said 404 people were treated as outpatients for heart or breathing difficulties and 92 were hospitalized. It said hospitals admitted 25 people suffering from heat stroke. <PERSON> Nikos </PERSON> <PERSON> Benardis </PERSON>, the <LOCATION> Athens </LOCATION> coroner, said the heat contributed to the deaths of 15 elderly people. `` Most of them had previous heart conditions and were on medication,'' he said. `` The heat certainly aggravated the condition of those with cardiac problems that caused their deaths.'' Soaring temperature have caused a shortage of electric fans and hundreds of people lined up at appliance stores for the few that remained. `` We had 60 fans in the store and sold them all within minutes of opening. There are people who have been waiting two or three days to buy one,'' said <PERSON> Efthimios </PERSON> <PERSON> Arevas </PERSON>, sales manager of a large appliance stores. He reported receiving orders from `` hospitals and even the army for 30 fans that we do n't have. It's worse than last year.'' One year ago, more than 900 people died in a 10-day heat wave. Lack of air conditioning in city hospitals was blamed for many of the deaths. <PERSON> Sismanogleion </PERSON> <PERSON> Hospital </PERSON> said crews were installing more air-conditioning units and the medical staff was on 24-hour alert. The environmental study center said smoke, nitrogen dioxide and total suspended particles in the <LOCATION> Athens </LOCATION> atmosphere were four to five times danger levels. No figures were available from the government <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Pollution </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Control </ORGANIZATION> because a bomb wrecked its offices early Wednesday. The leftist group <ORGANIZATION> Revolutionary </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Popular </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Struggle </ORGANIZATION> said it planted the bomb to protest environmental pollution. <LOCATION> Athens </LOCATION> has been plagued for years by the brown mass of pollutants that forms in the lower atmosphere on warm, still days and is known as the nefos, the Greek word for cloud. Government anti-pollution measures introduced in January have failed to eliminate it.
