<FIRST>r w AM-GOP-Family     07-07 0529</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-GOP-Family,530</SECOND>
<HEAD>House Republicans Introduce Family Bill</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JILL LAWRENCE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 House Republican leaders unveiled an `` American Family Act'' on Thursday, saying they hoped the bill would win Vice President <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s backing and influence issues ranging from child care to gang-busting. `` It is not enough for Republicans to deride the failures of the Great Society programs. We must provide a framework for change,'' House Republican Leader <PERSON> Bob </PERSON> <PERSON> Michel </PERSON>, R-Ill., said at a news conference The $ 2 billion package would provide federal support for promising state, local and private programs designed to strengthen the American family. Though they'll introduce the legislation in August, sponsors are really shooting for action in the next <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>, said Rep. <PERSON> Dan </PERSON> <PERSON> Coats </PERSON>, <LOCATION> R-Ind </LOCATION>., the principal author of the bill Sponsors also want to make the bill part of the <ORGANIZATION> GOP </ORGANIZATION> platform and are hoping <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>, the all-but-certain GOP presidential nominee, will endorse it in whole or in part. One of the sponsors is Rep. <PERSON> Jerry </PERSON> <PERSON> Lewis </PERSON>, R-Calif., co-chairman of the Republican Convention Platform Committee Specifically, the bill contains the following initiatives: _ Up to $ 50 million to states for experiments in school-based management, in which teachers play a major management role and districts have greater budget and curriculum flexibility _ $ 50 million to promote unrestricted school enrollment policies aimed at forcing schools to compete. _ Up to $ 450 million for `` bootstrap schools'' which have predominantly minority or low-income students _ $ 600,000 for `` character education'' pilot programs and promotion. Grants would be available only to schools that require the Pledge of Allegiance daily. _ College savings bonds, with tax-exempt interest if proceeds were used for tuition and other costs associated with higher education of the taxpayer, spouse, child or dependent Such legislation has already been introduced with the backing of <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> and <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>. _ A $ 1.3 billion proposal targeting aid to low-income working families, already introduced by Rep. <PERSON> Tom </PERSON> <PERSON> Tauke </PERSON>, <LOCATION> R-Iowa </LOCATION>, _ A multimillion-dollar program to fight gang warfare, including $ 5 million to encourage states to adopt restitution laws, $ 7 million to states with laws allowing courts to find parents liable for restitution, $ 3.5 million for law enforcement areas that want to set up a tracking system for juvenile Also, there would be grants for community reclamation and other projects. _ Child support enforcement initiatives, including mandatory automatic wage withholding and a requirement that at least 17 percent of a non-custodial parent's income go to support one child _ Allowing public housing authorities to charge no more than fair-market rent for housing Currently, families pay 30 percent of their gross incomes. _ $ 10 million in start-up money for projects that coordinate services to high risk children. The Republicans said they are planning a second family package to address the issues of housing, work and family, and possibly health. It is unclear, they said, whether the next bill will include a provision guaranteeing new parents job-protected leave. `` There's a lot of controversy about it,'' Coats said of such a requirement for parental leave, an idea promoted by Democrats and some Republicans but strongly opposed by business. `` We've resisted the temptation to pick up a politically charged issue and throw something out there that we're not 100 percent comfortable with.''
