<HEAD>Statehood Leader Has No Regrets on 30th Anniversary</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ANCHORAGE, Alaska (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Statehood did n't immunize <LOCATION> Alaska </LOCATION> from hard times _ oil prices are down and there is no more boom in the economy _ but a leader in the campaign for a 49th star on the flag has no regrets. `` Statehood has done everything Alaskans said it would do for them,'' <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Atwood </PERSON>, chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> Alaska </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Statehood </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>, said as the state marked one of its 30th birthdays. It was on July 7, 1958, that President <PERSON> Eisenhower </PERSON> signed the <LOCATION> Alaska </LOCATION> statehood bill into law. Some consider the anniversary to be June 30, the date in 1958 that <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> passed the bill to admit the huge territory into the union. Still others cite Jan. 3, 1959, when <PERSON> Eisenhower </PERSON> signed the proclamation admitting <LOCATION> Alaska </LOCATION> to the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. None of the dates is drawing much attention this year. The list of official <LOCATION> Alaska </LOCATION> holidays notes instead Seward's Day in March and <LOCATION> Alaska </LOCATION> Day in October. Seward's Day marks the 1867 signing of the treaty by which the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> purchased <LOCATION> Alaska </LOCATION> from the Russians. Alaska Day recognizes the formal transfer of the territory and the raising of the flag at <LOCATION> Sitka </LOCATION> in 1867. The struggle for statehood spanned 10 years, said <PERSON> Atwood </PERSON>, publisher of the <ORGANIZATION> Anchorage </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Times </ORGANIZATION>. `` We had our issues over statehood in <LOCATION> Alaska </LOCATION>: Would it be good for <LOCATION> Alaska </LOCATION> and Alaskans,'' he said. `` But <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> wanted to know would statehood be good for the nation. They did n't give a hoot about what would be good for <LOCATION> Alaska </LOCATION>.'' Politically, <PERSON> Atwood </PERSON> said, trying to gather votes among the nation's lawmakers was `` like trying to line up 1,000 dominoes so that when you knock one down, they all fall.'' Representatives from some of the Southern states worried <LOCATION> Alaska </LOCATION> would send <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> liberal congressmen who would bolster the civil-rights movement, he said. `` <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> did n't want to lose the title of the biggest state,'' remembered <PERSON> Atwood </PERSON>, who moved to <LOCATION> Alaska </LOCATION> in 1935. `` They joked about it, but it was a real concern to them.'' He said opposition within <LOCATION> Alaska </LOCATION> came from the canned salmon industry. `` They controlled the economics and the politics of the territory,'' he said. With statehood accomplished, <LOCATION> Alaska </LOCATION> went through governmental changes that <PERSON> Atwood </PERSON> believes helped lure investors north. Previously, he said, companies with money to stake were held back by concerns about the amount of power exerted in <LOCATION> Alaska </LOCATION> by the Secretary of the Interior. Before statehood, <PERSON> Atwood </PERSON> said, <LOCATION> Alaska </LOCATION> was a colony run out of <LOCATION> Seattle </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, <ORGANIZATION> D.C </ORGANIZATION>.
