<HEAD>Soviets Launch Unmanned Probe to Mars' Moon</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANDREW KATELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> launched an unmanned probe Thursday night on a six-month trip to Mars' moon, Phobos, for a mission designed to pave the way for a manned voyage to the red planet. The 180-foot-tall booster rocket spewed orange and blue flames as it illuminated the nighttime sky at the Baikonur space center in the Soviet Central Asian republic of <LOCATION> Kazakhstan </LOCATION>. The launch of the Proton rocket carrying the probe, <PERSON> Phobos </PERSON> <PERSON> I </PERSON>, was carried live on Soviet television, which reported that the spacecraft's flight was proceeding normally. More than a dozen nations are participating in the mission to swoop close to the surface of Phobos and drop probes onto the little, potato-shaped <PERSON> Martian </PERSON> moon that scientists say may hold clues to how the universe was formed. Delegations from around the world gathered at Baikonur for the launch of Phobos I, a joint East-West project to study the moon and Mars itself. A companion probe, <PERSON> Phobos </PERSON> <PERSON> II </PERSON>, is scheduled for launch on July 12. If all goes well, the two spacecraft will enter the gravitational pull of Mars in January 1989 and fall into orbit just behind Phobos for a three-month remote study of the surface and atmosphere of the planet. In April, the craft will drop out of their orbit and swoop to within 30 yards of the <LOCATION> moon </LOCATION>'s surface, where they will release two small landers. The Soviet news agency <ORGANIZATION> Tass </ORGANIZATION> said Thursday that in one experiment, a laser beam will be used to split a tiny piece of Phobos' rocky surface and trap a specimen for close examination. One of the landers is expected to operate for about a year in stationary position, sending back data. Another is designed to leap around the little moon in 20-yard hops gathering soil samples and analyzing them. This is the most sophisticated and ambitious of 18 Soviet and <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> unmanned missions to study Mars. Soviet space scientists have characterized the Phobos mission as an important step toward a manned flight to <LOCATION> Mars </LOCATION>, which they hope will be possible in the early 21st century. The Phobos probes will help map the surface of the planet `` in order to choose a place for the future landing,'' said <PERSON> Vyacheslav </PERSON> <PERSON> Balebanov </PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION> Soviet </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Academy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Sciences </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ' </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Space </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Research </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION>. `` Then, it is necessary to study the climate and soil characteristics and find out whether oxygen should be taken from <LOCATION> Earth </LOCATION>, or whether it can be gotten directly on the planet.'' Soviet leader <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> has proposed that the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> join in the prospective manned mission, but <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> officials have been cool to the idea, saying it would be very expensive and would require solutions to many difficult problems, one of which is the problem of astronauts' physical deterioration during long periods of weightlessness. Soviet space officials have put the cost of the Phobos mission at $ 480 million. In addition to the Soviets, <LOCATION> Austria </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Bulgaria </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Hungary </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ireland </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Finland </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> France </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Czechoslovakia </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Switzerland </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Sweden </LOCATION>, the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> European </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Space </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION> are participating in the flight. The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, a late entry, will provide tracking data with its Deep Space Network that can determine distances within yards and the velocity of objects billions of miles from <LOCATION> Earth </LOCATION>. The Phobos craft also will carry a plaque commemorating the moon's discovery by an American astronomer.
