<HEAD>Defiant Arabs Turn in Identity Cards To Protest Tax Raid</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAN IZENBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIT SAHOUR, Occupied West Bank (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Hundreds of Palestinians turned in their army-issued identity cards Thursday to protest a pre-dawn raid by Israeli tax collectors. The Palestinian action was an unprecedented gesture of defiance by Arabs toward military authorities in the occupied lands. Non-payment of taxes has become one of the chief civil disobedience tactics used by Palestinians in the uprising against <LOCATION> Israeli </LOCATION> occupation of the <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bank </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Gaza </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Strip </LOCATION> that began Dec. 8. In <LOCATION> Beit </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Sahour </LOCATION>, near <LOCATION> Bethlehem </LOCATION>, Israeli tax collectors accompanied by about 300 troops entered the homes of 50 residents at 5 a.m., seized their identity cards, and said they would n't be returned until the <LOCATION> Palestinians </LOCATION> paid their back taxes. Troops also impounded the cars of some Arabs, apparently for nonpayment of vehicle licensing and other fees. The move prompted about 250 other Arab residents to hand in their identity cards in protest. Palestinians are required to carry identity papers at all times and face immediate arrest if caught without them. The cards also must be presented when requesting permits to travel abroad or other government services. An official of <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>'s <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bank </LOCATION> military government said there had been no previous incidents of large numbers of Palestinians returning identity cards in protest even though a number of underground leaflets have called for such action. An army official said there was a large gathering outside city hall which dispersed without military intervention. He declined further comment. Dozens of <LOCATION> Beit </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Sahour </LOCATION> residents streamed into town hall to turn over the orange-colored cards, which filled a large drawer. At one point, Palestinians broke into loud cheers and applause when <PERSON> Abdullah </PERSON> <PERSON> Mousta </PERSON>, the mukhtar or leading town elder, handed over his papers. In their latest leaflet, uprising leaders ordered Palestinians not to pay taxes to `` escalate the uprising and bring us closer to total civil disobedience.'' On Thursday, <LOCATION> Beit </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Sahour </LOCATION> residents were told to report to a girls' high school where departments were set up for collecting back income taxes, value-added taxes and vehicle licensing fees. Few residents turned up to settle their bills. Some said they could not afford to pay what they owed, and others said they refused to pay out of defiance. `` The Israelis are asking the impossible,'' said a Palestinian who would only give his first name, <PERSON> Abdullah </PERSON>. `` We ca n't afford it. We live in very difficult conditions.'' <PERSON> Narri </PERSON> <PERSON> Kheir </PERSON>, a carpenter, said the army ordered him to pay $ 2,000 in taxes although he had not worked for three months. A woman, who refused to be identified, said many residents were no longer afraid of Israeli punishments. `` We have nothing to lose any more,'' she said. Prime Minister <PERSON> Yitzhak </PERSON> <PERSON> Shamir </PERSON>, meanwhile, said the first firebomb attack in Jewish west <LOCATION> Jerusalem </LOCATION> since the uprising began showed that Arabs were intent on destroying <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>. There were no casualties in the Wednesday night attack on an Israeli passenger bus in the central commercial district of Jewish west <LOCATION> Jerusalem </LOCATION>. `` The uprising is not about the question of territory ... but about our very existence,'' <PERSON> Shamir </PERSON> told <ORGANIZATION> Israel </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> radio </ORGANIZATION>. `` This shows the growing nerve of hostile elements who dare to do such a thing in the center of the state of <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>.'' Mayor <PERSON> Teddy </PERSON> <PERSON> Kollek </PERSON> described the firebombing as `` a terrible danger for the present and the future.'' Although stone-throwing and firebomb attacks have escalated recently in <LOCATION> Arab </LOCATION> <LOCATION> east </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Jerusalem </LOCATION>, where 135,000 Arabs live, the attack marked the first time violence has spread to west <LOCATION> Jerusalem </LOCATION>, where about 340,000 Jews live. Also Wednesday, assailants threw a rock from the roof of the largest commercial center in <LOCATION> Tel </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Aviv </LOCATION>, damaging the roof of a car. Police spokeswoman <PERSON> Dalia </PERSON> <PERSON> Gilad </PERSON> said police blamed Arabs and rounded up five residents of the occupied <LOCATION> Gaza </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Strip </LOCATION> for questioning. Four were later released. The trial of <PERSON> Hanna </PERSON> <PERSON> Siniora </PERSON>, editor of the pro-Palestine <ORGANIZATION> Liberation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Organization </ORGANIZATION> daily, <PERSON> Al </PERSON> <PERSON> Fajr </PERSON>, began Thursday in a <ORGANIZATION> Jerusalem </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> District </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Siniora </PERSON> was charged with violating censorship laws last year for publishing an interview with <ORGANIZATION> PLO </ORGANIZATION> leader <PERSON> Yasser </PERSON> <PERSON> Arafat </PERSON> without first submitting it to the military censor. <PERSON> Siniora </PERSON> has advocated an Arab civil disobedience campaign.
