<HEAD>GOP Consultant: Bush's Gender Gap Problem Could Beat Him In
November</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Political Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By EILEEN PUTMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A Republican political consultant said Thursday that <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> will lose in November if he does n't get the support of more women, and that even a woman running mate would not help substantially. The problem of `` gender gap'' is so serious that overcoming it is probably the most important demographic key to a <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> victory, said <PERSON> Doug </PERSON> <PERSON> Bailey </PERSON>, a respected <ORGANIZATION> GOP </ORGANIZATION> consultant. `` If he does n't bridge the gender gap he will not win ... There are not enough white men available for <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> to win this election,'' <PERSON> Bailey </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Bailey </PERSON> predicted that <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>, the likely <ORGANIZATION> Republican </ORGANIZATION> nominee, will win, however, by making changes in his campaign strategy to make him more appealing to women voters. He said the campaign's emphasis on <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s past government and military experience does not appeal to women, whose primary concerns tend to be economic issues affecting work and family. `` There's nothing wrong with playing baseball at <ORGANIZATION> Yale </ORGANIZATION>, and there surely is nothing wrong with serving your country and being a genuine war hero and there's nothing wrong with being director of the <ORGANIZATION> CIA </ORGANIZATION>,'' <PERSON> Bailey </PERSON> said. `` But frankly, that is a biography that links up dramatically with male instincts, and male interests and male priorities. It says nothing positive about linking up that agenda of issues ... of highest priority to women voters,'' he said. He recommended that the vice president concentrate on making his own family more visible at campaign appearances, and make a more forceful commitment to issues like long-term health care, job security and education. <PERSON> Bailey </PERSON> spoke at a news conference called by the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Federation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Business </ORGANIZATION> and Professional Women's Clubs, which released an analysis on the gender gap, a term used to describe differences in men and women's political preferences and behavior. The study looked at recent polls which have shown that women are more pessimistic than men about the economy and thus more likely to vote against the current administration, as represented by <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>. Polls show male voters generally split between <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> and likely Democratic nominee <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>, while women voters are more likely to lean toward <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>. `` The perception is that <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> is respectful of women and <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> is not,'' she said. <PERSON> Bailey </PERSON> acknowledged that the `` gender gap numbers over the first six months of this year have been disaster for <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>.'' Asked about the impact of the selection of a women vice presidential candidate on the Republican ticket, <PERSON> Bailey </PERSON> said that it could be negative if it is perceived as a symbolic act done because of the polls. `` Frankly, I do not think that the selection of a woman for vice president would do more than a marginal job,'' <PERSON> Bailey </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Ethel </PERSON> <PERSON> Klein </PERSON>, a political science professor at <ORGANIZATION> Columbia </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> who prepared the analysis, noted that polls in recent weeks have shown more women undecided and that <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>' support among women had eroded somewhat. Much of <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>' support comes from anti-Bush sentiment, and substantial numbers of both men and women are `` not sure at this time that either of these men are suited to be president,'' she said. In any case, women's votes will be crucial in November `` if this presidential election is as close as many analysts are predicting,'' she said.
