<FIRST>r a AM-AIDSTest     07-07 0216</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-AIDS Test,0222</SECOND>
<HEAD>Labs Licensed to Perform New AIDS Test</HEAD>
<DATELINE>EMERYVILLE, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A sophisticated test that allows detection of minute amounts of the AIDS virus in people who by conventional tests appear uninfected is being offered commercially by two <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> laboratories. The test uses a technique called polymerase chain reaction, or PCR, in which extremely small amounts of genetic material can be picked out and quickly copied to provide enough material for analysis. It has been used in rare cases to identify people carrying small amounts of the AIDS virus but who tested negative on conventional tests. The PCR test does not detect only AIDS, but any tiny amounts of genetic material. It has previously been available only for research. <ORGANIZATION> Cetus </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, which developed the technique, on Wednesday announced it has licensed the <ORGANIZATION> Pathology </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Berkeley </LOCATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Specialty </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Laboratories </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Santa </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Monica </LOCATION> to use the test. Physicians or laboratories will be able to send them blood samples for testing, which takes five days and costs about $ 145. The PCR technique is not intended to replace the standard ELISA test, which detects antibodies to the acquired immune deficiency syndrom virus. In many cases, the AIDS virus does not trigger production of antibodies for six months or more after the infection has occurred.
</TEXT>
