<HEAD>Dukakis' VP Choices: Nobody's Perfect</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP News Analysis</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DONALD M. ROTHBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Political Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 As <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> looks over his list of potential running mates _ seven names by all indications _ no one of them stands out as an unencumbered choice. The <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION> governor is expected to announce his choice next week, before the opening of the Democratic National Convention where he will be named the party's presidential nominee. <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> was on a Western campaign swing on Thursday, scheduled to return to <LOCATION> Boston </LOCATION> on Sunday. Aides said he was taking Monday off, but the expectation was he would use that time to go over the material gathered by <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> Brountas </PERSON>, the close friend and lawyer who has been heading the veep search. The following names are understood to be on the <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> list: <PERSON> Jesse </PERSON> <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON>, Sens. <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Glenn </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Lloyd </PERSON> <PERSON> Bentsen </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Bob </PERSON> <PERSON> Graham </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION> and <PERSON> Albert </PERSON> <PERSON> Gore </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Tennessee </LOCATION>, and Reps. <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Gephardt </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Missouri </LOCATION> and <PERSON> Lee </PERSON> <PERSON> Hamilton </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Indiana </LOCATION>. Three other names were on the <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> list _ Sens. <PERSON> Sam </PERSON> <PERSON> Nunn </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Georgia </LOCATION> and <PERSON> Bill </PERSON> <PERSON> Bradley </PERSON> of <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Jersey </LOCATION> and <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> Majority Leader <PERSON> Tom </PERSON> <PERSON> Foley </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>. All three said no thanks. It's always possible that the buttoned-down <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> could surprise everyone and choose someone whose name has made no lists. But the known universe is the above-named seven. Each has been asked for detailed personal and financial information and each has met privately with the governor. While strong cases can be made for each, it often is the negatives that play a key role in determining the choice. In other words, it often is as much a process of elimination as of selection. Here's a look at the downside of the seven: _ <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON>. Despite a campaign in which he was widely praised for moving into the mainstream of the <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> and addressing issues of primary concern to white as well as non-white voters, every national survey has said <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> would hurt the Democratic ticket far more than he would help it. <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> is a highly disciplined individual and would expect his running mate to be equally controlled, an expectation that would be impossible with the volatile <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON>. _ <PERSON> Glenn </PERSON>. The former astronaut and <ORGANIZATION> Marine </ORGANIZATION> pilot is a genuine national hero who would give the ticket an image of strength on defense. Polls indicate <PERSON> Glenn </PERSON> helps the ticket in nearly every section of the country. But <PERSON> Glenn </PERSON> has always done better in the polls than at the ballot box. He ran a disastrous campaign for president in 1984 and still owes more than $ 2 million. Another rap against him was best expressed by <PERSON> Jimmy </PERSON> <PERSON> Carter </PERSON> in 1976. After meeting <PERSON> Glenn </PERSON>, <PERSON> Carter </PERSON> reportedly told aides, `` He's the most boring man I've ever met.'' _ <PERSON> Bentsen </PERSON>. No Democrat has been elected president this century without carrying <PERSON> Bentsen </PERSON>'s home state of <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION>, which has the third largest number of electoral votes _ 29. But <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> also is <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s home state and there is no guarantee <PERSON> Bentsen </PERSON> would carry the state for the Democratic ticket. In addition, <PERSON> Bentsen </PERSON> is up for re-election. The old <PERSON> Lyndon </PERSON> <PERSON> B. </PERSON> <PERSON> Johnson </PERSON> law remains in effect _ legislation passed in 1960 to permit <PERSON> Johnson </PERSON> to run for re-election to the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> while he also was running for vice president. But times have changed and an effort to go for a double could cost <PERSON> Bentsen </PERSON> his <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> seat. _ <PERSON> Graham </PERSON>. <PERSON> Graham </PERSON> would probably give the Democratic ticket <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION>'s 21 electoral votes. But he's little known outside his home state and is only in his second year in the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION>. If <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> is looking for <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> experience to balance the ticket, <PERSON> Graham </PERSON> seems an unlikely choice. _ <PERSON> Gore </PERSON>. `` Damaged goods'' is the phrase some <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> advisers use to describe the <LOCATION> Tennessee </LOCATION> senator, a reference to his failed presidential campaign. A major argument <PERSON> Gore </PERSON> used during his campaign earlier this year was that <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> represented the Mondale-McGovern wing of the party. <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> McGovern </PERSON> and <PERSON> Walter </PERSON> <PERSON> Mondale </PERSON> share the distinction of having lost 49 states as Democratic presidential nominees. It was a comparison that did n't sit well with <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> _ <PERSON> Gephardt </PERSON>. Another failed challenger for the presidential nomination, <PERSON> Gephardt </PERSON> ran well in <LOCATION> Iowa </LOCATION> and creditably in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hampshire </L