<DATELINE>WILTON, Ala. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 An 88-year-old woman who sat on her porch for a month, waiting to die, has been taken by her stepchildren for a bath and a checkup. <PERSON> Annie </PERSON> <PERSON> Jeffrey </PERSON>, who can not walk, was spending Thursday at a neighbor's home. `` Older people are going to be defiant but from what I've seen here, she's not fine,'' said a stepdaughter, <PERSON> Roxie </PERSON> <PERSON> Harris </PERSON> of <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Francisco </LOCATION>. `` She did have some objections but we decided to go on in and take her away from the house.'' Mrs. <PERSON> Harris </PERSON> said she and two other stepchildren have tried for years to get Mrs. <PERSON> Jeffrey </PERSON> to live with them. `` We've been very concerned about her, but she would n't let us do anything, would n't let us take her back We were here last year to clean up the house or either to buy a mobile home to put on the lot, but she was determined that we would n't do that.'' Then, Mrs. <PERSON> Jeffrey </PERSON> could walk and seemed able to care for herself, Mrs. <PERSON> Harris </PERSON> said. `` What I've seen here is a totally different individual.'' The stepchildren, all of whom live in other states, were contacted by neighbors concerned about Mrs. <PERSON> Jeffrey </PERSON>'s physical condition, rundown house and cluttered yard. While Mrs. <PERSON> Jeffrey </PERSON> sat on the rotted porch, neighbors took her food each day and tried to persuade her to leave. She now has seen a doctor and taken a bath, but no decision has been made on where she will go when her stepchildren leave. `` I feel so much better. I can sleep now,'' said the Rev. A.L. <PERSON> Jones </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Montevallo </LOCATION>, who tried to get help for her. He said that since she did not want to leave her home, he could do little besides checking on her condition.
