<HEAD>CDC Reports First U.S. Human Anthrax Case In Four Years</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: For release 6:30 p.m. EDT.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Federal health officials reported Thursday the nation's first case of human anthrax since 1984 _ in a textile worker believed infected by contaminated cashmere. A 42-year-old maintenance man at a <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Carolina </LOCATION> mill became ill last July with a small red lesion on his arm, and developed pain, fever and chills over the following week, the <ORGANIZATION> Centers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Disease </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Control </ORGANIZATION> reported. He was diagnosed with a cutaneous form of anthrax, a severe and potentially fatal disease most common in cattle and sheep. Only nine human cases have occurred in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> in the last decade, none since 1984, the <ORGANIZATION> CDC </ORGANIZATION> said. The patient, who recovered, had n't recently been out of <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Carolina </LOCATION> or been exposed to animals or animal materials. However, the <ORGANIZATION> CDC </ORGANIZATION> noted, his mill uses wool imported from <LOCATION> Australia </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Zealand </LOCATION>, cashmere goat hair from <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION>, and camel hair from <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Mongolia </LOCATION>. Eight of 59 textile samples tested at the mill _ including five samples of <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Asian </LOCATION> cashmere _ showed contamination with anthrax bacteria, the <ORGANIZATION> CDC </ORGANIZATION> said in its weekly report. `` The West Asian cashmere was probably the contaminant,'' the <ORGANIZATION> CDC </ORGANIZATION> reported. `` Western <LOCATION> Asia </LOCATION> is an endemic area for anthrax.'' The other three contaminated samples were either debris or Australian wool which may have been cross-contaminated while stored near the cashmere, the At