<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Agriculture Secretary <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> E. </PERSON> <PERSON> Lyng </PERSON> met with six farm-state governors Thursday and emerged saying the need for legislative action to provide drought relief has now become urgent. `` There's a need to do something, it would probably take legislation to do that and there's a need to do it with some urgency,'' <PERSON> Lyng </PERSON> told a news conference following the session with governors and key lawmakers. <PERSON> Lyng </PERSON>'s call for swift action was in marked contrast to past remarks that <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> should hold off on fashioning a drought relief package until it is certain of the extent of the damage wrought by sizzling temperatures and a shortage of rainfall in the Farm Belt. Since he made those remarks several weeks ago, however, the drought has become more ominous. Spring wheat, oats and barley already are hard hit in the Grain Belt and authorities forecast drastic reductions in corn yields unless there is substantial rain in the <LOCATION> Midwest </LOCATION> within a week. `` It's a critical time when the corn is tasseling and we're in the pollinating stage,'' said <LOCATION> Iowa </LOCATION> Gov. <PERSON> Terry </PERSON> <PERSON> Branstad </PERSON> said after the meeting. `` Every day that goes by we see a substantial reduction in yields.'' Participants in the meeting at offices of the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Governors </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ' </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> said they reached broad agreement on almost all fronts. They said farmers need more assurance that <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> will act this year and that therefore bill drafting should begin quickly. `` The decision to act I think is uniform among the people who were present,'' said <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Dakota </LOCATION> Gov. <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Sinner </PERSON>, chairman of the association's committee on agriculture and rural development. `` There also was a uniform decision that <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> probably should address this.'' Bill-drafting sessions could start as early as next week in both the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> Agriculture committees, said the chairmen of those panels, Rep. E. `` Kika'' de la <PERSON> Garza </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-Texas </LOCATION>, and Sen. <PERSON> Patrick </PERSON> <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Leahy </PERSON>, D-Vt. Also on hand were Govs <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Mickelson </PERSON> of <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Dakota </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Terry </PERSON> <PERSON> Branstad </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Iowa </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Rudy </PERSON> <PERSON> Perpich </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Minnesota </LOCATION>, <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Ashcroft </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Missouri </LOCATION> and <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Martin </PERSON> of <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Carolina </LOCATION>. Seven other states were represented at the session by their lieutenant governors. <PERSON> Lyng </PERSON> said there were good prospects that President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> would sign relief legislation if it is a measure `` that is reasonable and compassionate and will help farmers.'' Officials said a consensus was forming around a few key proposals that could well be included in relief legislation. They said the measure most likely would allow farmers to keep all of the so-called deficiency payments that they have received in advance. Deficiency payments are income-support subsidies. They represent the difference between the market price of the crop and a target price set by <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> and adjusted by the secretary of agriculture. As the drought has intensified, crop prices have been rising in anticipation of scarcity later. Thus the gap between market prices and target prices has shrunk, leaving farmers with smaller payments at the same time that their crops have been wiped out. Forty percent of the deficiency payments, however, already were parceled out in advance to producers. `` I think it would be very difficult to collect advance deficiency payments from farmers who have no income,'' <PERSON> Lyng </PERSON> told reporters. The officials also said that producers of `` non-program'' crops should also receive relief under the legislation. Soybeans constitute the largest of these crops, whose producers do not receive deficiency payments. Various other fruits and vegetables also are non-program crops. The officials were less clear on exactly how much the measure would cost. De la <PERSON> Garza </PERSON> and others emphasized that the cost of the drought bill would not be able to push the cost of farm subsidies over their budgeted $ 17 billion limit. Lawmakers are expecting to save a considerable sum as a result of the smaller size of deficiency payments to many farmers. This amount in turn could be recycled and paid out in the form of drought relief, but that still would not take in aid to growers of non-program crops. `` That was discussed in there,'' said Rep. <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> <PERSON> Stenholm </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-Texas </LOCATION>. He said it was unsure where the money would come from. Governors made clear, however, that some form of relief was needed. `` Farmers in <LOCATION> Missouri </LOCATION> would face a a real economic disaster from which they would not recover if we failed to get relief,'' said <PERSON> Ashcroft </PERSON>. `` We will get relief.''
