<HEAD>Lawmakers Call For $15 Billion Housing Program</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHRISTOPHER CALLAHAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Standing in front of a run-down motel where the government pays for the lodging of homeless families, three <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> lawmakers on Thursday called for a $ 15 billion-a-year program to create new low-income housing. `` We have a responsibility,'' Rep. <PERSON> Barney </PERSON> <PERSON> Frank </PERSON>, D-Mass., told reporters and homeless activists at the <ORGANIZATION> Capital </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> City </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inn </ORGANIZATION>, a <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> motel where the government provides room and board for the homeless at an estimated cost of $ 3,000 a month per family Under <PERSON> Frank </PERSON>'s bill, about $ 75 billion would be spent over five years for construction of new housing, renovation of existing buildings, upgrading of public housing and the acquisition of additional units. <PERSON> Frank </PERSON>, joined by Reps. <PERSON> Kenneth </PERSON> <PERSON> J </PERSON>. <PERSON> Gray </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-Ill </LOCATION>, and <PERSON> Floyd </PERSON> <PERSON> Flake </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-N.Y. </LOCATION>, said the legislation is not aimed at this year, but for 1989 and the new administration. <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> said he has not discussed the proposal with <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION> Gov. <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>, the Democrat's expected presidential nominee. The lawmakers criticized the <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration's cuts in housing programs and the increasing government reliance on vouchers, designed to be used by the poor to go towards paying for rents in privately owned apartments. They said the vouchers do not work in cities such as <LOCATION> Boston </LOCATION> where there are few available low-cost housing units. The legislative program would be self-financing through a doubling of the cigarette tax, limiting deductions for business meals and entertainment expenses and other tax adjustments, <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> said. `` We can not afford not to build more affordable housing,'' said <PERSON> Flake </PERSON>. `` Homeless are human beings and they have rights too.'' The legislation was embraced by homeless activists. `` This bill can eliminate this place,'' said <PERSON> Mitch </PERSON> <PERSON> Snyder </PERSON>, pointing to the motel where he said families with four and five children live in a single room. Windows in the rooms do not open, forcing residents to leave doors open at night and making them more vulnerable to crime, <PERSON> Snyder </PERSON> said. Organizers from the Community for Creative Non-Violence said parents or older children must stay awake through the night to protect infants from rats. Officials at the motel, apparently upset by the publicity, instructed security guards to prevent <PERSON> Snyder </PERSON> and the congressmen from touring the complex with reporters and TV camera crews in tow. `` Tell him to have me arrested,'' <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> snapped at the guard. The tour continued without incident. The group did not go inside any rooms, but walked through a darkened corridor littered with food and other trash to the back where <PERSON> Snyder </PERSON> described living conditions. Motel manager <PERSON> Fadru </PERSON> <PERSON> Haji </PERSON> declined comment. `` Let them say what they want to say,'' he said. `` It's a one-sided story.'' Meanwhile, homeless organizers announced plans for demonstrations in more than 60 <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> cities and towns next Thursday to protest the plight of the homeless. Activists plan to occupy abandoned government-owned buildings as an act of civil disobedience to focus attention on structures that go unused while some poor have no place to live. The Community for Creative Non-Violence said activists also plan 24-hour vigils, rallies and marches.
