<HEAD>House Sidesteps Decision on Sensitive Issue of Base Closings</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: SUBS lead and INSERTS 1 graf after 2nd graf, The chamber, and
2 grafs after 10th graf pvs, The second, with House action Thursday</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By TIM AHERN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION>, grappling with one of its most sensitive political issues, sidestepped a decision Thursday on whether to let the <ORGANIZATION> Pentagon </ORGANIZATION> shut down unneeded military bases. The chamber was considering a pair of plans setting up complex mechanisms and procedures for closing some of the 3,800 military installations around the nation. Pentagon officials estimate that between $ 2 billion and $ 5 billion annually could be saved by shutting unneeded bases. But after a preliminary test vote, the chamber dropped the bill, in part because the debate had run longer than scheduled. House members generally do not work past Thursday afternoons, permitting members from Western states to return home for election-year campaigning. For the past 11 years, <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> has blocked any base closings because closings mean lost jobs, and lawmakers have been loath to see payrolls cut. But the federal budget deficit has forced Congess to take another look at the closings. And Rep. <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Dickinson </PERSON>, <LOCATION> R-Ala </LOCATION>., noted that this is also a politically opportune time to act `` Many things have come together to make this possible,'' <PERSON> Dickinson </PERSON> said. `` We have a window of opportunity. We have a lame-duck <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>, we have a lame-duck administration, a lame-duck secretary of defense.'' <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> Secretary <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> <PERSON> C. </PERSON> <PERSON> Carlucci </PERSON> has appointed a nine-member commission to review the nation's military facilities and decide by the end of the year which can be closed. That commission has been meeting for the past two months. Under the two plans considered Thursday, the commission would send its report to President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> next Dec. 31, who would then have until shortly before he leaves office next Jan. 20 to either accept or reject the entire list. The president could not pick or choose from among the bases. Then, under a plan proposed by Rep. <PERSON> Dick </PERSON> <PERSON> Armey </PERSON>, <LOCATION> R-Texas </LOCATION>, the bases would be closed starting Jan. 1, 1990, unless both the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> voted against the list. But under the second plan, the closings could not go forward unless both chambers voted in favor of the plan. The second plan was backed by three committees, which jointly agreed to overhaul the original <PERSON> Armey </PERSON> plan. The <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION>, in what <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Armed </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Services </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> Chairman <PERSON> Les </PERSON> <PERSON> Aspin </PERSON>, D-Wis., called a key test of views on the issue, voted 250-138 in support of an amendment providing that the base closures would go ahead unless both the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> vote to block them That provision, by Rep. <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Kasich </PERSON>, <LOCATION> R-Ohio </LOCATION>, is similar to the plan proposed by <PERSON> Armey </PERSON>. The amendment was added to the committee-backed bill. Rep. <PERSON> Jack </PERSON> <PERSON> Brooks </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-Texas </LOCATION>, chairman of one of the three panels, the <ORGANIZATION> Government </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Operations </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>, said <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> should have to vote to approve any closings. The <PERSON> Armey </PERSON> plan `` is designed to circumvent the political process,'' <PERSON> Brooks </PERSON> told his colleagues. But Rep. <PERSON> Constance </PERSON> <PERSON> Morella </PERSON>, R-Md., said the <PERSON> Armey </PERSON> proposal `` is the only way we can get this done. In addition to requiring an affirmative, rather than a negative vote, the committee-backed plan would also require the <ORGANIZATION> Pentagon </ORGANIZATION> to come up with plans to restore the environment at each outdated base, along with new studies about the economic impact of the closings. Rep. <PERSON> Les </PERSON> <PERSON> Aspin </PERSON>, D-Wis., chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> Armed </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Services </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>, noted that <ORGANIZATION> Pentagon </ORGANIZATION> budgets `` are declining The <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> ought to take every opportunity we can to make sure the money we spend on defense is spent wisely.'' In the decades after World War II, when the nation was winding down from a large-scale military structure, the Pentagon was generally allowed to do what it wanted on the issue with the exception of a handful of bases protected by key, powerful members. Between 1961 and 1977, the Pentagon closed 3,600 installations. But in 1975, the <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> proposed shutting down <ORGANIZATION> Loring </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Base </ORGANIZATION> in northern <LOCATION> Maine </LOCATION>. That state's legislators blocked the procedure by requiring lengthy _ and costly _ environmental impact studies for the <PERSON> Loring </PERSON> closing and all future closings. Since 1977, no major facilities have been shut. <PERSON> Armey </PERSON>'s proposal was defeated last year, 199-192, but he decided to try again because circumstances were different. House approval would send the plan to the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION>, which voted for its own base-closing plan two months ago. That proposal, creating a 15-member commission, was attached to a <ORGANIZATION> Pentagon </ORGANIZATION> budget bill, but was later dropped by the <ORGANIZATION> House-Senate </ORGANIZATION> conference committee called to resolve differences between the two chambers over the defense budget.
