<HEAD>Bush, Breaking Tradition, Plans to Campaign While Democrats Meet</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Updates with White House meeting, subbing 2 grafs for grafs
4-5 pvs, Playing down ... White House.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By TERENCE HUNT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP White House Correspondent</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Vice President <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>, hoping to steal thunder from <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>, is likely to break with tradition and go on the road stumping for votes and media attention during the Democratic National Convention. The plan, <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> said, is to `` get a little bit of ink'' while the spotlight is on <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> and his nomination as the Democrats' presidential candidate Traditionally, presidential candidates keep a low profile during the nominating conventions of their rivals. President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>, still playing by those rules although he is not running this year, will be at his mountaintop ranch in <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> when the Democrats meet in <LOCATION> Atlanta </LOCATION> July 18-21. On another campaign matter, <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> and <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>, seeking to limit public disagreements, directed their chiefs of staff Thursday to coordinate campaign policy pronouncements. `` I think everyone agrees that the main issue is, ` No surprises,''' presidential spokesman <PERSON> Marlin </PERSON> <PERSON> Fitzwater </PERSON> said after <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>, <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> and aides met over lunch at the White House. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> said recently he was debating whether to travel during the Democratic convention. `` I think probably some but _ you know, I do n't know, I do n't know what's the right thing to do.'' On the one hand, <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> said, he'd get news coverage by being on the road. On the other hand, he said, `` you do n't want to look like you're trying to frantically elbow your way into the news cycle. Tentatively, <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s planners are looking at events on Monday and Tuesday and Friday and Saturday of Democratic convention week _ the opening two days of the convention and the two days after it ends. Republicans already are planning to send a team of surrogates to <LOCATION> Atlanta </LOCATION> to make sure the media hears their point of view. <PERSON> Sheila </PERSON> <PERSON> Tate </PERSON>, the vice president's press secretary, said <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s schedulers were looking `` mainly at fund-raisers, nuts and bolts work that's got to get done, and it's a good time to do it. She said that Wednesday and Thursday `` are the big, big days -LRB- for the Democrats -RRB- and you keep them open.'' Wednesday night at the convention is reserved for the presidential nomination and presidential roll call, while Thursday night is set aside for the vice presidential nomination, roll call and acceptance speeches. At this point, most polls show the Dukakis-Bush race fairly close. Some surveys show <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> ahead by about four points, while others indicate it is even. With all the attention on the Democratic convention, <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> is expected to move ahead of <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> and come away from <LOCATION> Atlanta </LOCATION> with a hefty lead over the vice president, perhaps as much as 10 to 15 points, according to <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Wirthlin </PERSON>, the <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>'s pollster. `` The Republicans need some kind of major event, giving <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> the focus, the play, the visibility'' after <LOCATION> Atlanta </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Wirthlin </PERSON> said. He said an obvious thing for <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> to do would be to name his vice presidential nominee right after the Democratic convention, robbing <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> of the opportunity to bask alone in the limelight. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> has said he has not begun to focus on his running mate yet. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>, talking with reporters on <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> II Wednesday night as he returned from <LOCATION> Dallas </LOCATION>, said he would not be idle after he claims the Republican nomination at the party's convention in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Orleans </LOCATION> Aug. 15-18. He said he is thinking about having meetings in <LOCATION> Houston </LOCATION> on campaign strategy and with surrogates. He acknowledged that the general election phase of the campaign will begin ahead of the traditional Labor Day opening and talked about the demands that will pose. `` The physical thing _ I do n't want to get too tired. I'd like to get some time -LRB- off -RRB- before this last rush to judgment. But I know physically I can do this.'' He said he was still jogging, `` getting tired but I still feel up to it. `` So physically, I'm not too worried about it. I do n't want to get tired and make a lot of mistakes,'' <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> added. `` And if you do -LRB- get tired -RRB-, as I've found out, you can make mistakes.'' Referring to <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>, who is 54, the 64-year-old vice president said, `` He will not outwork me. Might do other things more, better, but he's not going to outwork me. He will not be in better shape than I am to do the physical part of this thing.''
