RRB- factual chapters, because, and I quote, ` Giving these facts to <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> would be like throwing raw meat to dogs,''' <PERSON> Wilson </PERSON> said in written testimony. He did not indicate the specific facts in question, but said the chapters dealt with `` the administration's notoriously flawed proposal to sell 96 percent of the national defense stockpile, a discussion of our recently increased dependence on the Soviet bloc for metals, the importance of South African minerals and the inequitable and noncompetitive impact of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> involvement in funding international financial institutions ... which directly subsidize competitors of the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> mining industry.'' <PERSON> Wilson </PERSON> said the American mining industry should be helped by the government, the council should be retained with a larger budget and <ORGANIZATION> OMB </ORGANIZATION>'s powers should be reduced: `` I have seen it override decisions made by cabinet secretaries who opposed it. ... <ORGANIZATION> OMB </ORGANIZATION> does not want -LRB- the council -RRB- to survive or to issue its reports in any fashion that might be helpful to the public interest. Quite frankly, I do not know who is served by their actions.'' Answering questions from the subcommittee chairman, Rep. <PERSON> Dave </PERSON> <PERSON> McGurdy </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-Okla </LOCATION>., <PERSON> Hodel </PERSON> said a single administrator `` would be stronger'' than a multimember body But the council's job, he said, might better be handled by the president's science adviser, because that adviser has experience roaming through different departments, access to the president and, just as important, access to the Office of Management and Budget.
