<DATELINE>ABERDEEN, Scotland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The Piper Alpha platform destroyed in the worst offshore oil rig disaster was an assembly of flat-roofed structures and steel towers that rose 150 above the water. It was 215 feet long and 100 feet wide, among the largest of the 123 fixed platforms that dot the British sector of the <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Sea </LOCATION> oil field. A fire burned constantly at its top, flaming off excess gas. The $ 901 million <ORGANIZATION> Piper </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Alpha </ORGANIZATION>, owned by <ORGANIZATION> Occidental </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Petroleum </ORGANIZATION>, began pumping oil and gas in December 1976 from its location 120 miles off eastern <LOCATION> Scotland </LOCATION> and was among the oldest of the <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Sea </LOCATION> rigs. Last year, the 34,000-ton platform produced a daily average of 23 million cubic feet of gas and 167,200 barrels of oil. It was linked to four other platforms in one of the most profitable sectors of the <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Sea </LOCATION> field discovered in the 1960s. More than 200 men worked the <ORGANIZATION> Piper </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Alpha </ORGANIZATION>, earning up to $ 1,000 a week in dangerous jobs. They lived on the platform for up to two weeks at a time, on a duty schedule of 12 hours on and 12 off. The <ORGANIZATION> Piper </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Alpha </ORGANIZATION> was pinned to the sea bed and supported by steel stilts, with most of its 649-foot height submerged. It included a helicopter landing pad used to ferry the workers out from <LOCATION> Aberdeen </LOCATION>, and had lifeboats with a total capacity of 300 people.
