<SECOND>AM-Antarctica Crash,490</SECOND>
<HEAD>Judge Rules Air New Zealand Crew Error Responsible for 1979 Crash</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES ROWLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The 1979 crash of an <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Zealand </ORGANIZATION> DC-10 into a mountain in <LOCATION> Antarctica </LOCATION> was the result of crew error and not any fault of <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> air traffic controllers, a judge ruled Thursday. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> District Judge <PERSON> Harold </PERSON> <PERSON> H. </PERSON> <PERSON> Greene </PERSON> blamed the airline and the crew of Flight 901 for a series of mistakes that caused the plane to fly off course into Mt. Erebus, killing all 257 people on board. <PERSON> Greene </PERSON> dismissed $ 32 million in negligence claims against the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> government by relatives and heirs of 16 of the 20 crew members who died in the Nov. 28. 1979 crash on <LOCATION> Ross </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Island </LOCATION> in <LOCATION> Antarctica </LOCATION>. The judge blamed the airline for changing the original flight plan for the sightseeing trip without briefing the crew. He also cited the crew's failure to use the airliner's internal navigation device and a weather radar system to determine its location. `` Were it not for the tragic outcome, the planning phase of Flight 901 could be described as a comedy of errors; some of these errors were perpetrated by Air <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Zealand </LOCATION>, others by members of the flight crew,'' <PERSON> Greene </PERSON> said. The change in the flight plan put the plane directly in a course over Mt. Erebus instead of down the center of McMurdo Sound. The plan called for Flight 901 to avoid the mountain by flying at an altitude of 16,000 feet. To give passengers a better view of <LOCATION> Ross </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Island </LOCATION>, the plane descended without radar assistance to less than 2,000 feet in violation of <LOCATION> Air </LOCATION> <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Zealand </LOCATION> policy, <PERSON> Greene </PERSON> said. It was flying at an altitude of 1,500 feet when it crashed into Mt. Erebus. The crew never discovered the change because it never bothered to plot the coordinates of the new flight plan, <PERSON> Greene </PERSON> said. Nor did crew members bother to use the plane's internal navigation system to determine its geographical location. `` Had a single crew member performed this simple task at any time during the last hour of flight, he would have learned that the aircraft was not on longitude 165 degrees heading down the open sound, but on a longitude of 167 degrees heading toward Mt. Erebus.'' If the crew were more alert, it would have noticed that <LOCATION> Beaufort </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Island </LOCATION> was to the plane's right instead of the left _ as it would have been if Flight 901 had flown on the original course, <PERSON> Greene </PERSON> said. `` The air traffic controllers at <LOCATION> McMurdo </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Station </LOCATION> had no reason to suspect that these errors in the most fundamental principles of planning and airmanship had occurred, and that they had profoundly altered what would otherwise have been a safe and uneventful flight,'' <PERSON> Greene </PERSON> said. `` Absent such knowledge, they had no basis for suspecting that Flight 901 was in mortal peril, or for taking extraordinary measures that even the flight crew never requested them to take,'' <PERSON> Greene </PERSON> said. The <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION>'s air traffic controllers are assigned to <LOCATION> McMurdo </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Station </LOCATION> to help direct aircraft used in scientific exploration by the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Science </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Foundation </ORGANIZATION> and other organizations.
