<HEAD>Safety Questions Over North Sea Oil Rig</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BEN DOBBIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ABERDEEN, Scotland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Roy </PERSON> <PERSON> Carey </PERSON>, a survivor of the world's worst offshore oil platform disaster, said Thursday: `` We had all that water around us and no way to get it to us We had sprinklers but they were n't strong enough.'' <PERSON> Carey </PERSON>'s remark as he lay badly burned in a hospital bed in <ORGANIZATION> Aberdeen </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Royal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Infirmary </ORGANIZATION> pointed up a bitter irony of offshore oil-drilling, one of the world's most dangerous occupations. The presumed death toll from the explosion and fire Wednesday night on the <ORGANIZATION> Piper </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Alpha </ORGANIZATION> platform in the <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Sea </LOCATION> exceeded 160. Urgent questions about safety in the offshore oil and gas industry are being raised by the disaster, which brings to more than 300 the number of people who have died in the British sector of the <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Sea </LOCATION> since gas was first pumped ashore in 1967. Drilling accidents killed 76 and a helicopter crash killed 45. Last year, six workers were killed and 59 seriously hurt among the 28,000 British workers. Three workers from <PERSON> Piper </PERSON> <PERSON> Alpha </PERSON> died after being thrown into the sea when a gangway collapsed in 1982. In 1984, a non-fatal explosion and fire forced the evacuation of 174 men. The platform, which has been producing oil since December 1976, passed its latest annual safety inspection by the <ORGANIZATION> Energy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> less than two weeks ago. Smoking and drinking are forbidden on oil platforms and a rescue vessel stands by each rig at all times. <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Brading </PERSON>, a London-based executive of <ORGANIZATION> Occidental </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Petroleum </ORGANIZATION>, which operates the platform, said workmen had been installing a vertical pipe linked to a seabed pipeline that runs to a new oil field. The platform draws mixed oil and gas from under the seabed, separates them and sends them ashore through separate pipelines. When a reporter asked if sparks from an oxyacetylene burner could have ignited gas supplies passing through the platform, <PERSON> Brading </PERSON> replied: `` It is much too early to draw any conclusions.'' A company statement said the fire's cause appeared to be a gas leak. <PERSON> Derek </PERSON> <PERSON> Ellington </PERSON>, one of the survivors, said he heard a shrieking sound just before the explosion and believed it was gas escaping from the separation system. In Parliament, lawmaker <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Prescott </PERSON> of the opposition <ORGANIZATION> Labor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> claimed inspection and maintenance of rigs had been reduced in recent years, insufficient money was spent on training, and government health and safety legislation did not apply fully to the <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Sea </LOCATION> oil and gas industry. Energy Secretary <PERSON> Cecil </PERSON> <PERSON> Parkinson </PERSON> replied that serious <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Sea </LOCATION> accidents had declined from 101 in 1986 to 59 last year. `` But that is too high a figure and we wish to keep the pressure on to ensure that improvement is maintained.'' Labor unions have complained in the past about the quality and avilability of survival gear and too few rescue helicopters. They see a conflict of interest in making the <ORGANIZATION> Energy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> responsible for oil production as well as safety.
