<HEAD>Rig Survivor: `It Was Fry And Die, Or Jump And Try'</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: SUBS 7th graf pvs, `John Maxwell ...' with 7 grafs to add
quotes from other survivors; PICKS up 8th pvs bgng, `We Were ...'</NOTE>
<HEAD>LaserPhotos LON3,4,12,20,21</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MAGGIE JACKSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ABERDEEN, Scotland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Men jumped from the blazing oil platform or slithered down searing pipes as the heat popped windows like bubbles, but most had no chance and comrades could only watch helplessly from a nearby vessel. `` It was a case of fry and die or jump and try,'' said technican <PERSON> Roy </PERSON> <PERSON> Carey </PERSON>, 45, who leaped into the cold <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Sea </LOCATION> to escape the flames that engulfed the giant <ORGANIZATION> Piper </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Alpha </ORGANIZATION> rig after an explosion Wednesday night. His face was burned and his arms were in slings. `` I was smothered with smoke. I could hardly see and could n't breathe, so it was over the side or die there,'' he said from his hospital bed in <LOCATION> Aberdeen </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Carey </PERSON> said one of the rig's survival boats floated past him and three other men. They grabbed at it and a man aboard held out his hands, `` but I could n't get a foothold. The waves were hitting me in my chest. I did n't want to drag him off so I just stayed in the water.'' Another boat picked him up half an hour later. `` We had all that water around us and no way to get it to us,'' to fight the fire, <PERSON> Carey </PERSON> said. `` We had sprinklers but they were n't strong enough. <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> McDonald </PERSON>, a 50-year-old rigger, told the <ORGANIZATION> Aberdeen </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Evening </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Express </ORGANIZATION> he waited for about 45 minutes in the crew's quarters, then he and three others decided to run for it through doors blocked by flames. `` I was n't going to sit down and get burned to death,'' <PERSON> McDonald </PERSON> said. `` You either stayed where you were and burned to death or you tried to get out.'' He said they fought past men on packed stairways to the lower levels of the platform, and `` I just forced my way through the flames,'' and slid down a hose and jumped. `` The water was red hot,'' <PERSON> McDonald </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Tony </PERSON> <PERSON> Sinnett </PERSON>, 34, was on the nearby support ship Tharos because of a shortage of beds on the <ORGANIZATION> Piper </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Alpha </ORGANIZATION>. `` There was nothing that anybody could do,'' he said. `` It was totally hopeless. It was like the platform had been hit by an atomic bomb. There was massive mushrooms and flames shooting into the air. I just thanked God I was n't on board.'' <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Maxwell </PERSON>, another rig worker, also watched from the Tharos as some of the more than 200 workers tried to get off the platform. `` We were in our survival suits ready to go to the rescue when we saw the drill derrick giving way, falling toward the pipe deck and possibly on the accommodation -LRB- crew's quarters -RRB- _ I do n't know,'' he said `` If there were men inside then, they could n't have survived. They could n't have survived all that heat. `` The heat was blowing out the windows. ... Panes of glass were all cracking off and the ferocity of the heat would suck all the oxygen out and the men inside would have smothered. It was terrible.'' <PERSON> Bill </PERSON> <PERSON> Elder </PERSON>, 48, a burly <PERSON> Scot </PERSON> who also had been on the Tharos, said he watched men slide down pipes and hoses on the side of the blazing platform. `` Some were swimming from the ship,'' he said. `` I felt helpless, sick. There was panic all around. We saw 10 guys waving from the deck. There was nothing you could do.'' He waited at a hotel in a dirty undershirt and blue sweat suit, cap stuffed in his pocket, to tell his story to investigators. Elder arrived in <LOCATION> Aberdeen </LOCATION> by helicopter, with other survivors and witnesses, more than 12 hours after the disaster. Rig worker <PERSON> Dave </PERSON> <PERSON> Lambert </PERSON> said the deck collapsed as he tried to find a way through the flames. `` The cabin slid forward and a hole appeared, so we made for it and jumped,'' he said. `` We fell in the sea. It must have been 60 or 70 feet.'' `` It was stay and get toasted or jump and chance it in the water,'' said <PERSON> Lambert </PERSON>, 38. He was in the water several hours before a rescue boat reached him. <PERSON> Bill </PERSON> <PERSON> Lobben </PERSON>, 27, his hand burned, one wrist in a cast, said he was watching a movie when the explosion shook the platform. `` We did n't see any flames so I went down and got warm gear and a survival suit and then went on the pipe deck,'' he said. `` There was a lot of flames and smoke there. There were more explosions and the rig just dropped suddenly to one side. I was terrified. I shielded myself and jumped into the water.'' <PERSON> Lobben </PERSON> clung to a piece of debris and swam to the Tharos.
