 Federal investigators offered a $ 5,000 reward Thursday for information leading to an arrest in the placing of 13 homemade bombs under bridges and behind buildings in this community. The <ORGANIZATION> Bureau </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Alcohol </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> , </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Tobacco </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Firearms </ORGANIZATION> offered the reward because of the `` inherent danger to the public safety caused by the explosive devices,'' said spokesman <PERSON> Joe </PERSON> <PERSON> Thurman </PERSON>. The bombs were found Tuesday in this small southern <LOCATION> Indiana </LOCATION> community about 30 miles north of <LOCATION> Louisville </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ky </LOCATION>. Some of the devices detonated, causing small fires, but no one was injured. <PERSON> Thurman </PERSON> said investigators continued to canvass the business district and neighborhoods, searching for clues that might lead to a suspect. `` We keep hoping each lead we run down is the one, but so far we do n't have any suspects,'' he said. <PERSON> Thurman </PERSON> declined to say whether investigators had been able to track down the source of the dynamite used to make the devices, which were found in paper grocery sacks. `` We're not going to talk about the device components. We'd just as soon keep quiet about that,'' <PERSON> Thurman </PERSON> said. `` It's normal procedure. The people we're looking for do n't need us to tell them what we're looking at.'' <PERSON> Thurman </PERSON> said there were about 35 outside investigators working on the case, representing the <ORGANIZATION> ATF </ORGANIZATION>, the <ORGANIZATION> FBI </ORGANIZATION>, the <ORGANIZATION> Indiana </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Police </ORGANIZATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION>. `` It's just a big investigation, and it's taking some time to run down the leads,'' <PERSON> Thurman </PERSON> said. Life for the 6,000 Salem residents had returned to normal by Thursday. `` There's no areas blocked off, or anything like that,'' <PERSON> Thurman </PERSON> said. `` As far as I can see, things are back to normal _ other than you have a town full of strangers here running around asking questions.'' He said residents had been urged to report any suspicious packages. `` We hope there are n't any more out there, but people should be aware that there could be another one out there. We hope we got them all,'' <PERSON> Thurman </PERSON> said.
