<FIRST>u w AM-BankBill     07-07 0535</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bank Bill,500</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bill Would Permit Bank Holding Companies To Underwrite Many
Securities</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: St Germain, no period, is cq</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DAVE SKIDMORE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Banking </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> on Thursday proposed legislation that would permit bank holding companies to underwrite many securities. The long-awaited bill from Rep. <PERSON> Fernand </PERSON> <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> St </PERSON> <PERSON> Germain </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-R.I. </LOCATION>, also would require banks to cash Social Security and other government checks and abolish an agency set up to sell property from insolvent savings institutions. It would reverse, in large part, restrictions on the mixing of investment and commercial banking that have been in place since the 1933 passage of the Glass-Steagall Act. Securities subsidiaries of bank holding companies would be able to underwrite and deal in corporate bonds, commercial paper, municipal revenue bonds and securities backed by mortgages and other kinds of loans. Banks would be precluded from underwriting in two major securities areas: corporate stocks and mutual funds. However, the subsidiaries would be able to sell mutual funds underwritten by others. The legislation provides for various `` fire walls'' to prevent losses in the securities affiliate from affecting the safety and soundness of bank deposits. Other provisions require securities subsidiaries to be regulated by the <ORGANIZATION> Securities </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION>. Also, to prevent any confusion by consumers with insured deposits in a bank, the securities subsidiary could not share a name, logo, advertising or location with an affiliated bank. This is <ORGANIZATION> St </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Germain </ORGANIZATION>'s second try at fashioning a bill that would attract enough votes to pass his committee. In March, a week before the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> passed broad legislation including bank underwriting of mutual funds and corporate stock, <ORGANIZATION> St </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Germain </ORGANIZATION> offered a much more restrictive bill. The latest effort is more permissive. In a statement, <ORGANIZATION> St </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Germain </ORGANIZATION> called it a `` consensus document'' and predicted it would get broad support in his committee and on the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> floor. Aides said a committee vote likely will be held by the end of July. However, a spokeswoman for the banking industry's largest trade group, the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bankers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION>, said bankers, who support the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> bill, are disappointed with the proposal. `` The price of paying for new consumer protections far outweighs any benefits banks would get from entering new areas,'' <ORGANIZATION> ABA </ORGANIZATION> spokeswoman <PERSON> Mary-Liz </PERSON> <PERSON> Meany </PERSON> said. In return for getting new powers, banks are being asked to cash government checks presented by non-customers, a measure aimed at helping Social Security and welfare recipients who ca n't afford to maintain a bank account. They also will be required to offer low-fee `` lifeline'' checking accounts for depositors with less than $ 1,000. Also, the bill gives a break to big competitors of banks _ so-called non-bank banks owned by <ORGANIZATION> Sears </ORGANIZATION> and other commercial companies _ which make loans or accept deposits but not both. A law enacted last summer restricted a non-bank bank's growth to 7 percent a year. However, <ORGANIZATION> St </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Germain </ORGANIZATION>'s legislation would lift the limit for two years. And, the bill curbs expansion of banks' insurance and real estate powers. An unrelated provision abolishes the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Asset </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Disposition </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION>, which has been accused of wasting money and doing a poor job of disposing of loans and real estate from closed savings institutions.
</TEXT>
