the primary vehicle for <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> economic and military aid to friendly foreign countries. As usual, the largest chunk of aid goes to <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>, which would get $ 1.2 billion in economic and $ 1.8 billion in military assistance. <LOCATION> Egypt </LOCATION> is the second-largest recipient, with $ 815 million in economic and $ 1.3 billion in military aid. Other major aid allocations include the <LOCATION> Philippines </LOCATION>, which would get $ 125 million in military aid, $ 124 million in economic aid and $ 40 million for development; $ 500 million to an African development fund, $ 101 million to an international drug control program. <LOCATION> Turkey </LOCATION> would receive $ 500 million in military aid and <LOCATION> Greece </LOCATION> $ 350 million. In <LOCATION> Central </LOCATION> <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> El </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Salvador </LOCATION> would receive $ 185 million in economic support, <LOCATION> Guatemala </LOCATION> $ 80 million, <LOCATION> Costa </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Rica </LOCATION> $ 90 million, and <LOCATION> Honduras </LOCATION> $ 85 million. The bill also would continue a ban on aid to <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION>, where strongman Gen. <PERSON> Manuel </PERSON> <PERSON> Antonio </PERSON> <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON> continues to defy <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> efforts to remove him from power, including elimination of <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION>'s lucrative <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> sugar sales quota The bill also includes a cut in aid to <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION>, which would receive $ 210 million in economic and $ 220 million in military aid. The total is $ 10 million less than the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> earmarked and $ 60 million less than the administration requested. <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION> has received favorable treatment in recent years because of its status as a conduit for <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> aid to the anti-Soviet rebels in neighboring <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION>. As the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> withdraws its troops, some in <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> are beginning to call for a re-examination of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> aid. In addition, the bill makes available $ 50 million to aid Afghan refugees and $ 362 million for other refugee programs, $ 157 million for the <ORGANIZATION> Peace </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corps </ORGANIZATION>, $ 40 million for an international program to combat AIDS and $ 1 million for the Solidarity trade union in <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION>.
