<SECOND>AM-Apple Consumption, 1st-Ld Writethru, a0716,0615</SECOND>
<HEAD>Per Capita Apple Consumption Tops 20 Pounds</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 3rd graf to CORRECT spokeswoman to spokesman.
^By NICHOLAS K. GERANIOS</NOTE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>YAKIMA, Wash. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Apple consumption in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> has risen to a record 20 pounds per person this year, good news for growers saddled with last year's largest crop in history, the <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> <ORGANIZATION> Apple </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> said Thursday. The nation has produced about 130 million 42-pound boxes of apples this season, with <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> growing about 67 million of those, the commission reported. `` We never had the supply nationally to really find out if people would eat more apples,'' said <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> <PERSON> St. </PERSON> <PERSON> John </PERSON>, spokesman for the industry marketing group based in <LOCATION> Wenatchee </LOCATION>. `` A lot of skeptics have said the industry can not increase apple production because Americans will not eat more apples,'' <PERSON> St. </PERSON> <PERSON> John </PERSON> said. `` This year we've found that people will eat more apples.'' Using its own unofficial projection methods, the commission has determined that apple consumption will be 21.6 pounds per person this year, up significantly from last year's 18.4 pounds per person, St. <PERSON> John </PERSON> said. That is the only time since 1970, date of the earliest research, that apple consumption has topped 20 pounds per person, he said. Normal consumption since 1970 has been 17 to 18 pounds per person, with a high of 19.9 pounds in 1975, which was another bumper crop year, St. <PERSON> John </PERSON> said. Consumption has been pushed up this year by the combination of a massive crop, low prices and extensive marketing activities. <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>'s 67 million boxes in 1987 easily eclipsed the previous year's record of 55 million boxes. But the huge crop lowered prices to below the $ 9.50 per box cost of production for much of the year. Only since the first of the month have prices jumped up, and currently are up to $ 19 per box for top grades, according to <ORGANIZATION> Market </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> News </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION>. `` This year has been an economic disaster from the grower's perspective,'' said <PERSON> St. </PERSON> <PERSON> John </PERSON>, although the consumption projections provide a silver lining in that dark cloud The current apple season ends in August, when the remaining 4.4 million boxes of <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> apples still in storage will be gone, St. <PERSON> John </PERSON> said. Early projection for the 1988 crop indicate it will be smaller, because of this year's low prices and because irrigation water supplies in the <LOCATION> Yakima </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Valley </LOCATION> are lower than normal due to last year's Northwest drought. The projections were created by the commission, which used production reports from around the nation, subtracted known exports and divided the remainder by the nation's population, St. <PERSON> John </PERSON> said. `` We came as close as we can to a true domestic consumption figure,'' he said. <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, which accounts for about 90 percent of apple exports, has shipped a record 12.2 million boxes to other nations so far this year, well above last year's 5.2 million boxes. The <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> consumption figure does not take into account imports from other nations, so consumption may actually be higher, St. <PERSON> John </PERSON> said. The projections assume all apples shipped to the fresh market are sold and do not include apples processed into juice, applesauce and other products, he said. The amount of apples sold for processing, for less money, varies each year and depends on how many were undesirable for the fresh market because of weather damage or undesirable color. About a quarter of <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>'s crop usually goes to processors, but up to a third of the 1987 crop was unfit for the fresh market. In other growing areas, up to half of the crop may go to processors.
</TEXT>
