<BYLINE>By GEORGE GARTIES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Police said Thursday they had few clues to who punctured orange juice cartons with hypodermic needles at three suburban markets this week and left notes warning of poison. A national expert on product tampering warned that widespread news coverage of the cases could prompt `` copycat'' crimes and noted there were more than 700 reports of product tampering across the country last year. No one drank from any of the juice cartons, discovered Monday, Tuesday and Wednesday at three supermarkets within a few miles in the <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Fernando </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Valley </LOCATION> suburbs. Police tests were incomplete, but one grocery store test cleared the first carton of cyanide contamination. Investigators have yet to find anyone who saw any of the tampering and are hampered in fingerprint checks because of the number of people who handle cartons in stores, said police Lt. <PERSON> Fred </PERSON> <PERSON> Nixon </PERSON>. `` We're treating it as very high priority despite the fact that we do n't know for certain that there is contamination present. In either case it's still a crime,'' <PERSON> Nixon </PERSON> said. Police advised consumers, particularly near the affected stores, 25 miles northwest of downtown, to check cartons before buying. The three supermarket chains involved, <ORGANIZATION> Vons </ORGANIZATION>, <PERSON> Hughes </PERSON> and <ORGANIZATION> Alpha </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Beta </ORGANIZATION>, all stepped up security in stores in the area, company spokesmen said. Involved were two national orange juice brands, <ORGANIZATION> Coca </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cola </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>'s Minute Maid and <ORGANIZATION> Procter </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; <ORGANIZATION> Gamble </ORGANIZATION>'s <LOCATION> Citrus </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hill </LOCATION>. In each case, a two-quart carton of orange juice was removed from the refrigerator case and punctured with the needle from a hypodermic syringe. The cartons, with the needles still attached, were found by customers or employees on shelves elsewhere in the markets, each with a note attached suggesting poison had been injected. <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> law makes threats of tampering with food or drugs a misdemeanor and actually contaminating a product a felony. The <ORGANIZATION> FBI </ORGANIZATION> is evaluating the case to see if federal felony tampering statutes apply, said spokesman <PERSON> Fred </PERSON> <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>. Investigators withheld some details of the tampering to make it easier to identify possible imitators. Research suggests that one nationally publicized case of product tampering leads to 30 `` copycat'' crimes across the country, said <PERSON> Park </PERSON> <PERSON> Elliott </PERSON> <PERSON> Dietz </PERSON>, a psychiatrist at the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Virginia </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Charlottesville </LOCATION> who studies such cases and has consulted for the <ORGANIZATION> FBI </ORGANIZATION>. `` The major determinant of how many cases there will be in the next three months is how widely this is publicized,'' <PERSON> Dietz </PERSON> said in a telephone interview. `` The consensus of how to handle this is to make sure the public is informed about potential risk _ in that geographic area.'' According to statistics from the <ORGANIZATION> Food </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Drug </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION>, threatened and actual product tampering increased ninefold in 1986, to 1,698 reported cases, after the death of a <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> woman who took a poisoned Tylenol pain capsule. In 1987, the <ORGANIZATION> FDA </ORGANIZATION> received 774 consumer complaints of tampering with food, drugs and other regulated products, and confirmed 84 cases of tampering with packages or their contents. Cases of threats combined with some form of tampering, as in the <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> incidents, are much more rare, said <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Swanson </PERSON>, director of emergency operations for the <ORGANIZATION> FDA </ORGANIZATION>. He was n't able to provide statistics on such cases.
