<DOCNO> AP880707-0167 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-07-88 1350EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>a a PM-BusinessMirror Adv08   07-07 0603</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Business Mirror, Adv 08,0620</SECOND>
<NOTE>$adv 08</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release PMs Friday July 8</NOTE>
<HEAD>Everyone Believes in Quality</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Also on financial wires.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JOHN CUNNIFF</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Analyst</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The war over, their industries wasted and their recovery prospects dim, the Japanese attached themselves to a concept that, as much as anything else, helped them rise up from the ashes. The concept was industrial quality, which presupposes that you offer a customer the very best you can produce because that, and nothing less, is what the customer expects. In concept or practice it was n't new. Americans had learned the trick years before, and its authorities on the subject were quite willing to share their ideas. A flock of them trekked to <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>; the Japanese listened and improved. Now, one of the great authorities on the subject, <PERSON> Armand </PERSON> <PERSON> Feigenbaum </PERSON>, former manager of <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Electric </ORGANIZATION>'s worldwide manufacturing operations, has finished offering a revolutionary idea to the Soviets. The notion: The customer is always right. And what the customer wants, needs, demands is quality. On reading that advice, most people consider it too obvious for comment. But the fact of the matter is that it is n't at all. Time after time companies have fallen on bad times because they forget it. Repeatedly, companies have resurrected themselves on rediscovering it. And not just companies but entire nations, as witness the Japanese. The notion was all but lost in the labyrinthic Soviet production system, which for decades has emphasized production goals over customer needs, and thereby affirmed one of <PERSON> Feigenbaum </PERSON>'s basic no-nos, to wit: `` The wrong way is for the manufacturer of a product or the provider of a service to satisfy his own perceived internal needs at the expense of the customer's requirements.'' The message was delivered last month to an audience at the 32nd annual conference of the <ORGANIZATION> European </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Organization </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Quality </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Control </ORGANIZATION>, made up mostly of Russians bent on improving Soviet production and export prowess. Will the Russians take heed as the Japanese did? And as much to the point: Will Americans remain competitive by practicing quality control; or will they forget, as they did for 20 years or so prior to the 1980s. <PERSON> Feigenbaum </PERSON>, author of `` Total Quality Control,'' a bible on the subject, is now president of <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Systems </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, a <LOCATION> Pittsfield </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Mass. </LOCATION>, company that installs quality control systems throughout the world. These are some of the points he made to the Russians, and which he suggests might draw the attention of American producers of products and services: _ Quality is everybody's job but it will become nobody's job unless management provides operating systems that support the work of individuals and promote teamwork among individuals and departments _ Quality and cost are partners, not adversaries The essence of both higher quality and lower costs is fully effective use of resources. Anything less produces waste, which means higher costs. _ Automation is no substitute for quality Unless installed as an integrated part of an overall quality system, automation merely produces the same bad products faster. _ Quality is not just a technical function or department It is an operating system that extends throughout the organization and provides the social stability and economic efficiency essential to quality. _ Quality improvement does n't come through sloganeering, bumper stickers, occasional quality fireworks called campaigns, or the dusting off of a few traditional quality-control techniques Customers perceive quality and they relate it to price. Quality shows through, he says, and when it is n't there it does n't take long for the customer to know it ... in <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>, the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> or the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv PMs Fri July 8</NOTE>
