<HEAD>Man Thought to Be Doctor Now Behind Bars</HEAD>
<NOTE>With LaserPhoto</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JOAN GOESSL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ALBUQUERQUE, N.M. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 One-time friends say the man they knew as Dr. <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Kelley </PERSON> told them he came here for a quieter life of medical practice and part-time teaching at the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mexico </ORGANIZATION> medical school. <PERSON> Kelley </PERSON> seemed to have a physician's demeanor and plenty of medical knowledge. He wore a white lab coat embroidered with his name and told stories about his teaching job. But it turns out that nobody at the university had ever heard of him and that the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mexico </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Medical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Examiner </ORGANIZATION>'s Board had no record of a <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Kelley </PERSON> being licensed to practice medicine in the state. And now his former friends _ remembering inconsistencies in his story that they once glossed over _ say they are embarrassed and angry they wee taken in by a man they describe as confident, extroverted, entertaining and smart. They're troubled by his criminal past and the story of his relationship with a teen-age boy who died. And they're relieved that one acquaintance `` outconned the con,'' as an investigator put it, and helped bring about his arrest. A <LOCATION> Bernalillo </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> grand jury returned a 34-count indictment in April charging him with multiple counts of practicing medicine without a license in <LOCATION> Albuquerque </LOCATION> in 1986 and 1987. `` He was so successful at convincing very well-educated people that he's something he's not,'' said <PERSON> Bill </PERSON> <PERSON> Copeland </PERSON>, the district attorney's investigator who handled the case. `` Part of his motive was he loved the high lifestyle. He enjoyed status, enjoyed the high roller-type lifestyle.'' <PERSON> Ke