 Then there's the story of his relationship with 18-year-old <PERSON> Ronnie </PERSON> <PERSON> Teunis </PERSON>. <PERSON> Kelley </PERSON> and <PERSON> Teunis </PERSON>, who lived together in the former's opulent <LOCATION> Oakland </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Calif. </LOCATION>, apartment, took out a $ 100,000 life insurance policy on each other in November 1982. <PERSON> Teunis </PERSON> died in a motorcycle accident two weeks later. The district attorney's office in <LOCATION> Oakland </LOCATION> has closed the case, according to investigator <PERSON> Nicole </PERSON> <PERSON> Lee </PERSON>. But it's not closed as far as <ORGANIZATION> Allstate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Life </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Insurance </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> is concerned. <PERSON> Kelley </PERSON> collected $ 203,365 from <ORGANIZATION> Allstate </ORGANIZATION>, a sum that included interest and payment on a double indemnity clause. The insuror now is trying to recover the money plus $ 600,000 in punitive damages, contending that <PERSON> Kelley </PERSON>, or <PERSON> Lampkins </PERSON>, misrepresented himself as <PERSON> Teunis </PERSON>' stepfather. A newspaper's legal notice of the insurance company's suit added to <LOCATION> Albuquerque </LOCATION> friends' vague uneasiness about <PERSON> Kelley </PERSON>. `` Things would happen to sow a seed inside you, but then nothing would happen for a while,'' said a woman whose family regularly invited <PERSON> Kelley </PERSON> to dinner and parties. A small, balding man described by friends as slightly effeminate and given to talking dramatically with his hands, he was good company, highly intelligent, schooled in the arts and well-traveled. He drove a <ORGANIZATION> Mercedes-Benz </ORGANIZATION> and carried a business card saying he was a Ph.D. as well as a medical doctor. The woman and her husband, who spoke on condition they not be identified, said <PERSON> Kelley </PERSON> avoided doctors whom they tried to introduce him socially and sometimes gave inconsistent accounts of his marital status _ divorced in one version, widowed in another. He wept while telling about the motorcycle accident that killed <PERSON> Ronnie </PERSON>, they said. But he said it happened in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, not <LOCATION> California </LOCATION>, and that the boy was an underprivileged youth his family had taken in. Every time <PERSON> Kelley </PERSON> piqued the couple's suspicions, the wife said, he'd offer a gift or a compliment _ `` something nice to overcome the feelings I had.'' But the legal notice was too much. The couple discussed their suspicions with a friend who passed them on to <PERSON> Cheryl </PERSON> <PERSON> Boll </PERSON>, a <LOCATION> Placitas </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.M. </LOCATION>, kennel owner who had befriended <PERSON> Kelley </PERSON> through their mutual interest in dogs. `` I think several people began snapping to this person who was not who he said he was. But she pegged him as a phony and a manipulator. Eventually she out-conned the con guy,'' <PERSON> Copeland </PERSON>, the prosecutor's investigator, said of Mrs. <PERSON> Boll </PERSON>. `` I talked to him almost every day,'' she said. `` Basically I played a role as his dearest and best friend. Call me <PERSON> Judas </PERSON>. That's a good name. Her motivation, she said, was to stop a phony doctor. She eventually told what she knew to the district attorney's office. An arrest warrant accusing <PERSON> Gerald </PERSON> <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> <PERSON> Lampkins </PERSON> of practicing medicine without a license _ and listing more than six aliases _ was filed last Feb. 12. <PERSON> Lampkins </PERSON>, who had fled <LOCATION> Albuquerque </LOCATION> after being served with the <ORGANIZATION> Allstate </ORGANIZATION> summons three months earlier, was then living in <LOCATION> Tempe </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ariz. </LOCATION>. Lt. <PERSON> Stephen </PERSON> <PERSON> Graehling </PERSON> and other <LOCATION> Tempe </LOCATION> officers knocked on his door `` We stood around for a few minutes,'' Graehling says. `` He came out the back door, which empties onto a golf course, and tried to run out back. But I had two deputies out back who arrested him. He did n't run very far.''
