<FIRST>a a AM-Drought-Report Adv11   07-07 0968</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Drought-Report, Adv 11,0994</SECOND>
<NOTE>$Adv11</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Monday AMs, July 11, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Widely Followed Weekly Report Is One Of Least Scientific Surveys</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEVEN P. ROSENFELD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DES MOINES, Iowa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 They often are based on seat-of-the-pants judgments rather than scientific measurements, but the government's weekly crop reports are among the most eagerly awaited figures for commodity traders, farmers and other drought watchers. Another round of reports will be released Monday afternoon and analysts will be looking to see how the nation's corn fields are standing up to dry conditions during a pollination period that is crucial to the survival of the crop. For soybeans, that make-it-or-break-it point is still weeks away. In <LOCATION> Iowa </LOCATION>, like other farm states, the reports are assembled from hundreds of questionnaires returned by farmer volunteers, government employees and bank officers who make farm loans. There are few yardsticks for the responses that, among other things, rate crops from excellent to very poor. Participants say they rely on their own judgment. `` It's probably one of the least scientific surveys we do. However, it's the most popular release we have,'' says <PERSON> Duane </PERSON> <PERSON> Skow </PERSON>, state statistician for <LOCATION> Iowa </LOCATION> for the <ORGANIZATION> Agricultural </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Statistics </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> of the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agriculture </ORGANIZATION>. `` It's a subjective report. It's not based on measurements.'' To farmers, the figures help in making decisions on when to buy hay, corn or soybean meal to feed livestock or whether to sell livestock and break up herds because of concern adequate feed will be too costly in winter. Farmers also may use the reports to base decisions on buying or selling crop surpluses or contracting for future sales or purchases. Public policymakers are watching the figures as they consider drought-relief programs. This year, for example, reports are being distributed for the first time to members of the <ORGANIZATION> Iowa </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Legislature </ORGANIZATION> and are being circulated to members of state drought task forces. Commodity firms, traders and market watchers view the figures as an important benchmark for grain and livestock markets _ providing regular progress reports on the condition of crops months before the harvest, as well as assessments on the availability of grains and grasses used as livestock feeds. `` These numbers are closely followed by grain trade analysts,'' says <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Wisner </PERSON>, an extension economist and grain market specialist at <ORGANIZATION> Iowa </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION>. `` They are used for a general indication of whether the crop is improving or deteriorating in condition,'' <PERSON> Wisner </PERSON> said. `` Obviously, they are not precise enough to forecast exact yields per acre, but these are good indicators.'' Last week's report for <LOCATION> Iowa </LOCATION>, for example, indicated a slight improvement in the soybean crop from the previous week, when triple-digit temperatures blistered fields. In the June 27 report, none of the <LOCATION> Iowa </LOCATION> soybean crop was rated excellent and 16 percent was graded poor. But on July 5, four percent was given an excellent rating and 12 percent was poor. In general, a normal crop is considered good, better than that is excellent and below normal is either fair, poor or very poor. The people who fill out the weekly questionnaires say it is easier to distinguish between the excellent and poor crops than to make distinctions between crops that are good or fair. `` Excellent and failure are real easy to identify,'' said <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Thuma </PERSON>, extension service director and agriculturalist in <LOCATION> Henry </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> in southeast <LOCATION> Iowa </LOCATION>, who has been participating in such surveys for 36 years. But sometimes, a conversation with a farmer will determine how some parts of the survey are answered. Is subsoil moisture inadequate? <PERSON> Thuma </PERSON> said it is when `` a farmer tells me he dug a fence post three feet deep and did n't find water.'' In <LOCATION> Iowa </LOCATION>, 427 questionnaires go out each Wednesday, asking for ratings of crops, an assessment of the moisture content of the soil and subsoil, progress on hay harvests and general comments on livestock, weather effects, fertilizer supplies, soil erosion or related topics. As the growing season progresses, questions are added each week to track the progress of corn and soybean crops. Last week's survey marked the start of questions on corn pollination, a critical period that will determine if kernel-filled ears will develop. Tassels already have formed on some stalks and must drop pollen on silks that are beginning to form on the ears. The silks must be moist and sticky enough to catch the pollen, `` otherwise you have a cob without corn,'' <PERSON> Skow </PERSON> said. Survey participants are asked to complete the forms on Friday or on Saturday morning, and replies received Monday morning in <LOCATION> Des </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Moines </LOCATION> are tabulated and combined with data provided by the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Weather </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> and the state climatologist. Last week's <LOCATION> Iowa </LOCATION> report was based on 222 questionnaires returned in time for use. <PERSON> Skow </PERSON>'s office strives to avoid sensationalizing the reports _ as he put it, `` to limit the adjectives.'' A typical passage last week said: `` The rain and cooler temperatures helped sustain the condition of <LOCATION> Iowa </LOCATION>'s corn crop this past week, particularly in the northern and western parts of the state. Overall the corn was in fair-to-good condition.'' This year in <LOCATION> Iowa </LOCATION>, because legislators restored cut funds supporting such projects, the weekly reports not only give statewide summaries, but also have restored a section that provides figures on soil moisture and crop progress for nine areas of the state. The people who compile and contribute to the report say that even if ideal conditions return, the corn crop has suffered. `` I'm not one to overdramatize this situation, but I'm also a realist,'' said <PERSON> Roger </PERSON> <PERSON> Brummett </PERSON>, a farmer and an agriculturalist at the extension service in <LOCATION> Taylor </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> who responds to the questionnaires in his southwest <LOCATION> Iowa </LOCATION> community. `` We're looking at a potential 40 percent to 60 percent -LRB- corn crop -RRB- loss right now in this county.''
</TEXT>
