<HEAD>From Rock to Rodeos to Democrats, The Omni Has Seen It All</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN A. BOLT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The rusty-looking building the Democrats will crowd into next week has been home over the years to revivals, rodeos and rock concerts; tennis, tractor-pulls and title fights; <PERSON> Springsteen </PERSON>, <PERSON> Sinatra </PERSON> and soccer. And basketball, especially basketball. The Omni arena, which opened in 1972 with a professional hockey game, was built at a cost of about $ 17 million on a platform over land owned by a group of developers who also put together the adjacent Omni International business-office-hotel complex. Since then, the building housing the businesses has been sold to <PERSON> Ted </PERSON> <PERSON> Turner </PERSON>. He changed the name to <ORGANIZATION> CNN </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION> after his <ORGANIZATION> Cable </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> News </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Network </ORGANIZATION>, which moved into space originally occupied by an indoor amusement park. A Turner-owned company manages the arena, but it remains owned by a joint city-county authority. The arena was constructed mainly to provide a home for the <ORGANIZATION> Atlanta </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hawks </ORGANIZATION>, a professional basketball team, said former Mayor <PERSON> Sam </PERSON> <PERSON> Massell </PERSON>. He spearheaded the negotiations with then-Hawks owner <PERSON> Tom </PERSON> <PERSON> Cousins </PERSON>, who was also the lead developer in the larger complex. Turner now is majority owner of the <ORGANIZATION> Hawks </ORGANIZATION>. There was `` a thirst for professional sports,'' <PERSON> Massell </PERSON> said, and a hope that the arena would serve as a catalyst for development on a neglected side of downtown <LOCATION> Atlanta </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Massell </PERSON> admitted that has n't happened as rapidly as some predicted. The building's exterior was intentionally designed to rust, to cut down on maintenance costs. Its roofline of 25 pyramid-shaped pods has been compared to an upside-down egg crate, the configuration designed to provide external support and to avoid columns inside. Indoors, the arena floor runs diagonally, to give more room for 16,237 seats for basketball and to provide space in the corners for private clubs. That space is going to be at a premium for the Democrats since construction of the podium and of skyboxes for network television will reduce the seating to about 11,000, forcing off the convention floor many of the non-delegates accustomed to priority seating in the past. Little controversy has surrounded the building, aside from periodic griping about concession prices, beer drinking and drug use at rock concerts. As for the unusual name, <PERSON> Massell </PERSON> recalled that as one of the few controversies 16 years ago. He said the name `` came from the dictionary,'' which defines the Latin-derived prefix `` omni'' as `` all, universal ... without restriction.'' It's been quite appropriate considering the ice shows, circuses and conventions staged there year in and year out. <PERSON> Massell </PERSON> said the name `` omni'' was unusual when the complex was built, but the <ORGANIZATION> Omni </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hotel </ORGANIZATION> was the beginning of what's become a chain of upscale hotels
