<HEAD>Amid the Bustle and Polish, The Poor Are Overlooked</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOSEPH B. FRAZIER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> Atlanta </LOCATION> is dressing up for the Democrats with the hope that the 35,000 visitors to the party's national convention will take home a rosy impression of the city. But the newly-planted flowers along <LOCATION> Peachtree </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Street </LOCATION> and the scrubbed down convention center will be unable to hide the rickety shanties of <LOCATION> Cabbagetown </LOCATION> and the thousands of homeless. This prosperous heart of the new South has a core city that ranks as the second-poorest in the nation, and activists estimate that 7,000 to 10,000 people are homeless. Leaders say they plan to make their plight known during the convention in July. <PERSON> Anita </PERSON> <PERSON> Beatty </PERSON>, co-director of the <ORGANIZATION> Atlanta </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Task </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> for the Homeless, said there are no plans for large marches or demonstrations during the convention because the impact would be lost. Instead, with representatives of national homeless groups, task force members will occupy some of the 1,300 empty public housing units in <LOCATION> Atlanta </LOCATION> for an undetermined time starting July 14, four days before the opening gavel. `` Who among the Democrats will take action to solve the problem if the problem is not visible?'' Mrs. <PERSON> Beatty </PERSON> said. `` It's nice to have 58 facilities to house the homeless, but it is kind of like letting steam out of the kettle.'' The coalition plans a `` sanctuary space,'' either in a church or large tent, where homeless can go and not fear arrest in clean-up drives. The city also decided some months ago to keep open a shelter for about 150 men that would have closed at the end of March and to add three more shelters, each housing about 30 people. Statistically, <LOCATION> Atlanta </LOCATION> is an island of prosperity in the South, but the numbers for the `` <LOCATION> Atlanta </LOCATION> area'' say little about the city proper, which has only about 20 percent of the metropolitan area's 2.2 million residents Suburban <LOCATION> Atlanta </LOCATION> is composed of large, shaded lots, nice brick homes, golf courses, shopping malls and white faces. Urban <LOCATION> Atlanta </LOCATION> is overwhelmingly black with about 27 percent of the residents living below the poverty line, second only to <LOCATION> Newark </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.J. </LOCATION>, according to <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Census figures. <LOCATION> Fulton </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION>, which includes the city of <LOCATION> Atlanta </LOCATION>, has an unemployment rate of 6.2 percent. The average for the four surrounding metropolitan area counties is 4.3 percent. Some of <LOCATION> Atlanta </LOCATION>'s homeless live under a viaduct that runs past the convention site, within the projected security zone around the convention area. City officials say the indigents must vacate the shantytown for security reasons. `` I do n't see why they're tryin' to hide us. It ai n't like we done nothing wrong. We just ai n't got nowhere else to stay,'' said <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> <PERSON> Prater </PERSON>, 37, one of the group. Mrs. <PERSON> Beatty </PERSON> fears that `` some Draconian things are going to be done.''
