<HEAD>Civil Rights Leaders Remember Jackson's Movement Days</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SONYA ROSS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Jesse </PERSON> <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> and his days in the 1960s civil rights movement are not topics of easy conversation on the home ground of the late Rev. <PERSON> Martin </PERSON> <PERSON> Luther </PERSON> <PERSON> King </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON>. Few among the civil rights old guard want to talk about <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON>'s time with <PERSON> King </PERSON>'s <ORGANIZATION> Southern </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Christian </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Leadership </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Conference </ORGANIZATION> And those willing to discuss the subject sometimes paint a less than flattering picture of the man who went on to run for president. King's widow, <PERSON> Coretta </PERSON> <PERSON> Scott </PERSON> <PERSON> King </PERSON>, declined to reminisce publicly about <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON>, except to say he was the one who told her King had been shot and instructed her to `` take the next thing smoking'' to <LOCATION> Memphis </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Tenn. </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Ralph </PERSON> <PERSON> Abernathy </PERSON> and <PERSON> Andrew </PERSON> <PERSON> Young </PERSON>, <PERSON> King </PERSON>'s top aides, did not return repeated telephone calls seeking comment on <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> The Rev. <PERSON> Joseph </PERSON> <PERSON> Lowery </PERSON>, the current <ORGANIZATION> SCLC </ORGANIZATION> president and a <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> supporter, paused for several minutes when asked for movement memories of the Democratic presidential candidate. `` I do n't remember nothin','' he said. <LOCATION> Atlanta </LOCATION> City Councilman <PERSON> Hosea </PERSON> <PERSON> Williams </PERSON>, who worked in field operations for the <ORGANIZATION> SCLC </ORGANIZATION>, said <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON>'s desire to work with King led to a meteoric rise in the organization and a post running its <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION> departments. `` <PERSON> Jesse </PERSON> was smart, energetic, charismatic; he really impressed Dr. <PERSON> King </PERSON>,'' <PERSON> Williams </PERSON> said. But <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> also had an obvious disdain for following rules, <PERSON> Williams </PERSON> said, and would use the funds he raised for his <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION> operations, without prior approval of <ORGANIZATION> SCLC </ORGANIZATION> officials. King and the rest of the <ORGANIZATION> SCLC </ORGANIZATION> executive council grew tired of <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON>'s rule-bending, <PERSON> Williams </PERSON> said, and emotions came to a head in late March 1968. During an <LOCATION> Atlanta </LOCATION> meeting five days before his death, King had a heated exchange with <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> and stormed out of the room in uncharacteristic anger. `` He turned around and looked at <PERSON> Jesse </PERSON> and said, ` <PERSON> Jesse </PERSON>, if you want to start your own national organization, I understand. It's OK with me. But do n't try to destroy me in the interim,''' <PERSON> Williams </PERSON> said. After King's death, <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> had other rifts with <ORGANIZATION> SCLC </ORGANIZATION> officials into the early 1970s, leading him to `` walk away'' from the organization and never return, <PERSON> Williams </PERSON> said. One major source of friction with civil rights leaders was the bloody shirt incident. <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> created an uproar when, hours after <PERSON> King </PERSON>'s assassination, he appeared in <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION> and on national television, wearing a bloodstained turtleneck sweater and saying he had cradled King as he died Civil rights leaders were outraged. `` When I got up there, <PERSON> Abernathy </PERSON> was cradling <PERSON> Doc </PERSON>'s head, and <PERSON> Andy </PERSON> had gone into the room to get a towel,'' <PERSON> Williams </PERSON> said. `` We got Doc in the car and they headed to the hospital _ <PERSON> Abernathy </PERSON> went with him. `` All at once I heard someone say ` I was the last man in the world King talked to.' I looked around, and it was <PERSON> Jesse </PERSON>. With all the press around, he said ` All this blood on my shirt, I got it when I cradled his head.''' <PERSON> Williams </PERSON> said <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> was not on the <LOCATION> Memphis </LOCATION> motel balcony when the shots were fired. <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> had been standing in the parking lot with the chauffeur and the Rev. <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Bevel </PERSON>, the <ORGANIZATION> SCLC </ORGANIZATION> field strategist who brought <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> into the organization in 1965. <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> generally declines to talk about the incident, but <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Washington </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Post </ORGANIZATION> quoted him in April as saying, `` It happened the way I said it did.'' Later, <PERSON> Williams </PERSON> said, King's aides gathered and pledged their support to <PERSON> Abernathy </PERSON>, <PERSON> King </PERSON>'s best friend, as the new president of <ORGANIZATION> SCLC </ORGANIZATION>. `` I remember <PERSON> Jesse </PERSON> saying he was sick; he said ` I'm going to my room.' What <PERSON> Jesse </PERSON> did is <PERSON> Jesse </PERSON> went to <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION>,'' <PERSON> Williams </PERSON> said, describing how King's horrified aides watched as <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> wore the blood-smeared sweater on the `` Today'' show and during hearings before the <ORGANIZATION> Chicago </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> City </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION>. `` Some of those like <PERSON> Andy </PERSON> and Coretta and others have never been able to forgive <PERSON> Jesse </PERSON> for that,'' he said. Rep. <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Lewis </PERSON>, D-Ga., who worked with the <ORGANIZATION> Student </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Non-Violent </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Coordinating </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> during the 1960s,