ich both major parties opened their conventions with the outcome uncertain was in 1952. Gen. <PERSON> Dwight </PERSON> <PERSON> D. </PERSON> <PERSON> Eisenhower </PERSON> beat out <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION> Sen. <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Taft </PERSON>, the choice of conservatives, for the <ORGANIZATION> GOP </ORGANIZATION> nomination on the first ballot. The uncertainty was greater on the Democratic side. Eleven candidates were nominated. The front-runner, Sen. <PERSON> Estes </PERSON> <PERSON> Kefauver </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Tennessee </LOCATION>, could muster only 28 percent on the first ballot. Democratic kingmakers began to look elsewhere. Their eyes fell on <ORGANIZATION> Illinois </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ' </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> governor, <PERSON> Adlai </PERSON> <PERSON> E. </PERSON> <PERSON> Stevenson </PERSON>, who had delivered a stirring keynote address. <PERSON> Stevenson </PERSON> refused to run. A draft movement was formed and on the third ballot it succeeded. The longest convention in the history of either party was the Democratic conclave of 1924 in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>. There were 103 roll calls over 17 days. <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> Gov. <PERSON> Al </PERSON> <PERSON> Smith </PERSON> passed <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Gibbs </PERSON> <PERSON> McAdoo </PERSON>, secretary of the treasury in the <PERSON> Woodrow </PERSON> <PERSON> Wilson </PERSON> administration, on the 86th ballot of the political marathon in a convention divided between rural and big city elements. Humorist <PERSON> Will </PERSON> <PERSON> Rogers </PERSON> complained that <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION> had invited delegates to visit the place, not live there permanently. <PERSON> McAdoo </PERSON> recaptured the lead on the 94th but released his delegates on the 99th. Wall Street lawyer <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> W. </PERSON> <PERSON> Davis </PERSON>, who had received just 31 votes on the first ballot, finally prevailed on the 103rd and marched off to defeat by <PERSON> Calvin </PERSON> <PERSON> Coolidge </PERSON> in November. It was the Republican convention of 1920 that produced that classic symbol of a brokered convention, `` the smoke-filled room.'' There is disagreement on whether there was actually a smoke-filled room in <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION> where party bosses turned to Sen. <PERSON> Warren </PERSON> <PERSON> Harding </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION>. But there is no disagreement that the term has entered <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> political history as a powerful symbol of a manipulated convention. According to the <PERSON> Boller </PERSON> account, <PERSON> Harry </PERSON> <PERSON> M. </PERSON> <PERSON> Daughtery </PERSON>, <PERSON> Harding </PERSON>'s campaign manager, had predicted four months before the convention that delegates would deadlock and weary party bosses would select <PERSON> Harding </PERSON> in a hotel room meeting in the early morning hours Actually, <PERSON> Harding </PERSON> was called before <ORGANIZATION> Republican </ORGANIZATION> leaders at 2:00 a.m., told he might win the nomination the next day, and asked whether there was anything in his background that might prove embarrassing or harm his effectiveness as candidate or president. <PERSON> Harding </PERSON> was left alone to think about it, then declared there was `` nothing, no obstacle'' to his candidacy _ a declaration that might have been less than candid considering <PERSON> Harding </PERSON>'s affair at the time with a married woman. After it was all over, according to <PERSON> Boller </PERSON>, someone called <LOCATION> Pennsylvania </LOCATION> Sen. <PERSON> Boies </PERSON> <PERSON> Penrose </PERSON>, who had helped orchestrate <PERSON> Harding </PERSON>'s selection, and said he hoped <PERSON> Harding </PERSON>'s weakness for women would n't be brought up