<HEAD>Stocks Fall; Automakers Report Sales Jump</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
 A selling wave has reversed an advance in the stock market, but <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> automakers reported their late June sales strengthened from a year earlier. On Wall Street, the Dow Jones average of 30 industrials fell 28.45 points Wednesday to finish at 2,130.16. The loss wiped out a 27.03-point advance on Tuesday that had carried the Dow average and other widely-followed market indicators to new highs for this year. Analysts attributed the drop partly to selling by professionals engaged in computer-program trading strategies involving stock-index futures and `` baskets'' of individual stocks. The stock market also suffered from renewed inflation worries, analysts said. Prices of some key farm commodities such as soybeans jumped late in the session on a forecast of more hot, dry weather in the <LOCATION> Midwest </LOCATION>. Oil prices also rose. The latest bout of inflation jitters, combined with the weaker dollar, also dragged down bond prices. The <ORGANIZATION> Treasury </ORGANIZATION>'s closely watched 30-year bond dropped by $ 12.50 per $ 1,000 in face value, while its yield soared to 8.98 percent from 8.87 percent late Tuesday. In their auto sales reports, <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Motor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Motors </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> each said their car sales climbed in the last 10 days of June, and the Big Three automakers all finished the first half of 1988 ahead of the same period last year. Many foreign automakers also reported upturns after a slow start on the year. <ORGANIZATION> Honda </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Toyota </ORGANIZATION> reported sales increases on both their domestic and foreign-made cars. In other economic developments Wednesday: _ The <ORGANIZATION> Labor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> reported that only <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> among the world's industrial powers bested the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> in reducing manufacturing labor costs in absolute terms last But measured in devalued dollars, labor costs in <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> soared 13.5 percent compared with a 1.5 percent decline in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, which had lower hourly increases in wages and benefits than any of its nine largest industrial competitors. _ Fears of higher interest rates and rising inflation weakened consumer buying plans in June as confidence in the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> economy slipped from an 18-year high in May, according to a survey by the <ORGANIZATION> Conference </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION>
