<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>, trying to appease big brokers and small investors, is abandoning a post-crash limit on computerized program trading while considering a plan to give individuals speedier access to the market. Directors of the nation's biggest securities market were discussing the changes at their regularly scheduled meeting today, said sources familiar with the <ORGANIZATION> Big </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION>'s plans who spoke on condition they not be identified. Scrapping the so-called `` collar'' restraint on high-volume computerized program trades would end one of the most controversial confidence-boosting revisions undertaken by <ORGANIZATION> NYSE </ORGANIZATION> in the aftermath of the October crash. The sources said there was widespread thinking, especially among large brokerages which utilize program trading, that the collar no longer was needed because the market has been relatively stable in recent weeks. The other measure, which the sources likened to a rush-hour `` express lane'' for individual investors, is designed to counter a perception that the <ORGANIZATION> NYSE </ORGANIZATION> ignores small trading orders in favor of the larger and more profitable transactions from big brokers and their institutional clients. <ORGANIZATION> NYSE </ORGANIZATION> spokeswoman <PERSON> Sharon </PERSON> <PERSON> Gamsin </PERSON> said she could not comment on matters before the board. But she said the collar limitation, implemented in February, never was meant to be permanent. Trading professionals gave mixed reactions to the collar news. Some called the limit useless, but others said it played a valuable role in calming the wild price swings that frightened away investors during and after the crash. Under the collar, the <ORGANIZATION> NYSE </ORGANIZATION> banned use of its order system for a popular form of computerized program trading called index arbitrage on days when the Dow Jones industrial average rose or fell at least 50 points from the previous close. `` If they take the rule off, I think there will be more volatility,'' said <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Johnson </PERSON>, president and chief executive of <PERSON> Johnson </PERSON>, <PERSON> Lane </PERSON>, Space, <ORGANIZATION> Smith </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, a brokerage in <LOCATION> Savannah </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ga. </LOCATION> `` That means there will be less inclination for the individual to participate in this market.'' <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Kirby </PERSON>, head of <ORGANIZATION> Capital </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Guardian </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trust </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION> and an outspoken critic of index arbitrage, said he thought the collar had helped curb computer-armed speculators from rampantly trading stocks to capture short-term profits regardless of underlying values. `` Investors are being flushed out of the system by a bunch of Star Wars guys,'' <PERSON> Kirby </PERSON> said. `` Markets are going to go where they go, but I'd like to see them driven by investors, not computers.'' The individual-investor proposal before the <ORGANIZATION> NYSE </ORGANIZATION> board also got a mixed reaction, with some calling it a confidence builder and others discounting it as a symbolic gesture. Under this proposal, individuals placing orders of less than 1,000 shares would have a special computerized `` express lane'' to the <ORGANIZATION> NYSE </ORGANIZATION> floor on days when the Dow average swung more than 25 points from the previous close. During the crash, many small investors complained they could not get their sell orders to the <ORGANIZATION> NYSE </ORGANIZATION> floor quickly because of the congestion caused by large institutional orders. This meant individuals were forced to sell at much lower prices, while larger investors were able to sell first. `` I think the individual should have equal access,'' said <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Bachmann </PERSON>, chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> Securities </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Industry </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> and managing partner of <ORGANIZATION> Edward </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> D. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Jones </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, a St. Louis-based brokerage. `` Anybody who thinks the individual had equal access last time -LRB- during the crash -RRB- were wrong.'' But <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Markese </PERSON>, vice president of the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Individual </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Investors </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION>, said he was not sure such a proposal would help small stockholders. `` It's holding out a hand,'' he said. `` It's going in the right direction, but it may prove to be a token gesture.''
