<HEAD>NY State Judge Throws Out Irving Poison Pill Provision</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Rodgin is cq in 6th graf.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By VIVIAN MARINO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Irving </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> has vowed to appeal a state court ruling striking down a provision of its `` poison pill'' defense aimed at thwarting <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION>'s hostile merger efforts. <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> Justice <PERSON> Herman </PERSON> <PERSON> Cahn </PERSON> on Wednesday granted a preliminary injunction against the provision, ruling it unfairly discriminated against <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> and the company would suffer `` irreparable harm'' from <PERSON> Irving </PERSON>'s takeover defense. The defense would allow all of Irving shareholders _ except a hostile suitor _ to buy $ 400 worth of Irving shares for $ 200 if any suitor bought more than 20 percent of Irving stock without the support of <PERSON> Irving </PERSON>'s management. Such provisions are intended to make unsolicited takeover bids prohibitively expensive. <PERSON> Irving </PERSON> attorney <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Falise </PERSON> said the bank planned to appeal <PERSON> Cahn </PERSON>'s ruling, which he called `` erroneous.'' But <PERSON> Falise </PERSON> said he was pleased the judge did not reject <PERSON> Irving </PERSON>'s entire poison pill, which adheres to a <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> state anti-takeover law that prevents an unfriendly merger for at least five years <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> reaffirmed its outstanding buyout offer and said it would seek a 60-day extension from the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reserve </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> for conditional approval of its proposed merger with <PERSON> Irving </PERSON>. The <ORGANIZATION> Fed </ORGANIZATION>'s approval was due to run out Saturday. <PERSON> Rodgin </PERSON> <PERSON> Cohen </PERSON>, an attorney for <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION>, said <PERSON> Cahn </PERSON>'s ruling `` should remove the single biggest question they -LRB- the <ORGANIZATION> Fed </ORGANIZATION> -RRB- had, and that was the ability to complete the merger. <PERSON> Mark </PERSON> <PERSON> Alpert </PERSON>, a banking analyst with <ORGANIZATION> Bear </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> , </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stearns </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, predicted the <ORGANIZATION> Fed </ORGANIZATION> would grant an extension. `` If the <ORGANIZATION> Fed </ORGANIZATION> had wanted to stop this -LRB- the takeover battle -RRB-, they would have spoken up now.'' <PERSON> Alpert </PERSON> said it was unlikely <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> would attempt to amass a larger stake in <LOCATION> Irving </LOCATION> for fear that <PERSON> Irving </PERSON> would win an appeal that would trigger the poison pill. He also noted that even if an appeals court ruled in favor of <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> the state anti-takeover law would force <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> to operate <PERSON> Irving </PERSON> as a separate subsidiary. <PERSON> Cahn </PERSON>'s decision came a day after <PERS