<HEAD>Labor-Management Safety Agreement Received Coolly</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto WX7 of July 6</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAN SEWELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION> unions and management are not ready to declare peace is at hand, despite an agreement to separate safety issues from their other disputes. `` The key word to use is ` guardedly' optimistic because there's been such an extended period of mistrust,'' said <PERSON> J.B. </PERSON> <PERSON> Stokes </PERSON>, a spokesman for the Eastern local of the <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Line </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Pilots </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION>, which represents 3,500 pilots `` You have to be somewhat cautious.'' The pact announced Wednesday comes a month after federal investigators warned that safety could be threatened at financially-troubled <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION>, the nation's sixth-largest airline, if its labor problems were not resolved quickly. The deal spells out procedures for the company and its 32,500 workers to discuss complaints and disagreements. `` We are optimistic and hopeful this will represent a breakthrough in relations,'' said <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> <PERSON> E. </PERSON> <PERSON> Bryan </PERSON>, district president of the <ORGANIZATION> Machinists </ORGANIZATION> union, <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION>'s largest labor group with 12,000 members. `` We do n't think this is going to be a total cure for all the problems of Eastern.'' <PERSON> Judy </PERSON> <PERSON> Coughlin </PERSON>, secretary-treasurer of the <ORGANIZATION> Transport </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Workers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Union </ORGANIZATION> local, representing 7,000 Eastern flight attendants, said her union was skeptical of the deal but supported any attempt to improve safety. `` We're willing to cooperate on anything, but the problems are not going to be solved until our people can go to work and not worry about being fired,'' she said. <PERSON> Robin </PERSON> <PERSON> Matell </PERSON>, a company spokesman, said <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION> would not characterize the agreement beyond a statement by President <PERSON> Phil </PERSON> <PERSON> Bakes </PERSON>, who said the pact would keep safety out of collective bargaining issues. But Bakes also noted it was essential to complete negotiations on economic issues with the machinists and pilots unions. Former Labor Secretary <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> E. </PERSON> <PERSON> Brock </PERSON>, chosen by federal officials June 2 to find ways to ease <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION>'s labor-management relations, said he found `` tensions were accelerated to an unbelievable level'' between the two sides. Years of disputes, including lawsuits, lobbying in <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> and negative newspaper advertisements, have made passengers afraid to fly Eastern and had created a situation where the airline is losing $ 1 million daily, <PERSON> Brock </PERSON> said. Transportation Secretary <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> H. </PERSON> <PERSON> Burnley </PERSON> <PERSON> IV </PERSON> called the agreement `` a good beginning'' and said federal inspectors would continue stepped-up monitoring of Eastern `` to assure the flying public that it remains a safe, fit airline.'' Rank-and-file reaction to the safety agreement seemed mixed as reports reached <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION> employees in its <LOCATION> Miami </LOCATION> base. A mechanic fired 18 months ago said he was skeptical about how well the deal would ease tensions. `` There have been so many things done to people and their families, it would be awfully hard to forgive and forget,'' said the mechanic, who asked that his name not be used because his case is in federal arbitration. A flight attendant arriving at <LOCATION> Miami </LOCATION> <LOCATION> International </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Airport </LOCATION> said she found it encouraging that `` some agreement, any agreement was made. You have to start somewhere,'' said the woman, who like many <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION> employees asked that her name not be used. The pact calls for the establishment of a master safety committee consisting of top company and union officials, which will help resolve safety problems pointed out by employees. Panels will be established throughout the country at which local managers and union leaders will attempt to resolve issues such as captains' authority, the handling of calls to the company's complaint lines, training of maintenance workers and a study of workplace injuries `` The document is worthless if there is not compliance,'' <PERSON> Bryan </PERSON> told reporters. `` We have a collective bargaining agreement -LRB- which -RRB- has been blatantly violated consistently by this management. So there was some reservation about putting a lot of confidence in this document.'' A measure of the continued mistrust was the inability to get management and union leaders to appear together at the <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> news conference. Eastern has been marked by labor-management conflicts for more than a decade, as a period of cooperation under former Chairman <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> <PERSON> Borman </PERSON> deteriorated and led to the money-losing airline's sale in 1986 to Houston-based <ORGANIZATION> Texas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>. <ORGANIZATION> Texas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION>'s management led by Chairman <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> <PERSON> Lorenzo </PERSON> heightened tensions by saying <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION> had to cut its labor costs by up to 30 Eastern lost $ 241 million last year, and <ORGANIZATION> Texas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> lost $ 466 million. The Machinists, in federal mediation with management since January, have refused to take wage concessions of up to 50 percent for some non-mechanics, such as baggage handlers. Eastern says it ca n't reverse its losses without the concessions. A group of Eastern pilots testified before <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> last year that they were pressured repeatedly to fly aircraft they considered unsafe. The agreement pledges that, `` No employee will be harassed, threatened or disciplined for reporting or causing to report an unsafe condition on an aircraft.'' Federal officials conducted special inspections of aircraft flown by <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Continental </ORGANIZATION> last spring and also examined <ORGANIZATION> Texas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION>'s management and finances. They announced they had not found unsafe conditions but warned of possible safety problems because of the labor-management battles. The <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Aviation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION> in April proposed an $ 823,000 fine against Eastern for recordkeeping and maintenance infractions. Fourteen months earlier, the airline had agreed to pay a record $ 9.5 million penalty.
