<FIRST>r f PM-MergerFees     07-07 0574</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Merger Fees,0593</SECOND>
<HEAD>Atlanta Fed Researchers Say Huge Fees Worth The Price In Big
Mergers</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN A. BOLT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A study of the fees paid to investment bankers in friendly business mergers concludes that such payments, which may total millions of dollars, are no more excessive than the transaction fees paid to real estate agents. Researchers <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Curt </PERSON> <PERSON> Hunter </PERSON> and <PERSON> Mary </PERSON> <PERSON> Beth </PERSON> <PERSON> Walker </PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reserve </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Atlanta </ORGANIZATION> stated their review of 125 friendly mergers between 1979 and 1985 indicated `` the bankers' fees, though large in absolute terms, are only a small percentage of the economic value created by the mergers.'' `` On average, when measured against the gain that the merger creates for the new entity, ... the fee approximates that of a typical real estate transaction,'' said the researchers, who figured the average fee equalled about 6.6 percent of the economic gain created by the mergers. Furthermore, the investment bankers' fees averaged a `` very reasonable'' less than 1 percent of the total transaction price, with the highest being 3.4 percent of the price, <PERSON> Hunter </PERSON> said. The study was published in the <ORGANIZATION> Atlanta </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Fed </ORGANIZATION>'s Economic Review publication. The researchers limited their survey to friendly mergers of public companies and did not look at those where investment banks provided only fairness or underwriting services. <PERSON> Walker </PERSON> said it was the first survey to compare fees with services rendered. The mergers ranged in value from $ 34 million to $ 6 billion, with fees ranging from $ 100,000 to $ 20 million. The two largest fees came from the $ 2.8 billion deal in 1984 that joined <ORGANIZATION> Beatrice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Foods </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Esmark </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> and the $ 5 billion merger in 1985 of <ORGANIZATION> Allied </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp </ORGANIZATION> with the <ORGANIZATION> Signal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cos. </ORGANIZATION>. Inc.. <PERSON> Hunter </PERSON> said each deal paid $ 20 million to the investment banks involved _ <ORGANIZATION> First </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Boston </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Lazard </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Freres </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Beatrice-Esmark </LOCATION>; <ORGANIZATION> Lazard </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Salomon </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Brothers </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Oppenheimer </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> in the <ORGANIZATION> Allied-Signal </ORGANIZATION> The wave of mergers and acquisitions in recent years has brought more attention to the fees paid investment bankers, with some critics claiming the fees are excessive. Trade publications have discussed the fees in articles with titles like `` Merger Fees That Bend the Mind'' and `` Wall Street's Overpaid Young Stars. The merger departments of three separate Wall Street firms each earned $ 200 million in 1985. <PERSON> Hunter </PERSON> said the attention and worry have caused some merger-minded companies to consider a do-it-yourself approach. But <PERSON> Hunter </PERSON> and Ms. <PERSON> Walker </PERSON> argued against bypassing the investment bankers. `` Bringing together of buyer and seller and advising on what price to pay _ from that point of view, -LRB- investment bankers -RRB- seem to be well worth their fee,'' <PERSON> Hunter </PERSON> said in an interview. `` Firms contemplating a do-it-yourself approach simply because fees charged by professional merger intermediaries appear excessive would do well to scrutinize the costs and benefits of self-search,'' <PERSON> Hunter </PERSON> and Ms. <PERSON> Walker </PERSON> wrote. The researchers note that investment banks traditionally have provided a range of services, including underwriting, market-making and advice on capital structure, dividend policy, mergers, acquisitions and divestitures. `` While other financial institutions provide many of these same services, the investment banks' specialization and expertise in corporate financial matters, along with their position overlooking capital markets as a whole, give them a comparative advantage that permits them to command handsome fees,'' they wrote. <PERSON> Hunter </PERSON> also said investment bankers are constantly gathering and assessing information on corporate assets, research that would have to be done otherwise by individual suitors.
</TEXT>
