<HEAD>Judge Rules Gillette Issued Misleading Reports On Proxy Rival</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRIAN MURPHY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Assoicated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Gillette </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> inaccurately portrayed a New York-based partnership during a proxy battle earlier this year but did not mislead shareholders by withholding information about potential buyers, says a federal judge. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> District Court Judge <PERSON> Mark </PERSON> <PERSON> L. </PERSON> <PERSON> Wolf </PERSON> issued his ruling Wednesday but withheld a decision on whether to invalidate an April shareholder vote that defeated a dissident slate of directors nominated by the investment group <ORGANIZATION> Coniston </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Partners </ORGANIZATION>. The judge postponed that decision until after further testimony by <ORGANIZATION> Gillette </ORGANIZATION> on alleged proxy violations by <ORGANIZATION> Coniston </ORGANIZATION>. In a prepared statement, <ORGANIZATION> Gillette </ORGANIZATION> said it was `` surprised and disappointed'' by the ruling on the advertisements. `` While <ORGANIZATION> Gillette </ORGANIZATION> disagrees with -LRB- the -RRB- ruling and believes its conduct was proper, its immediate efforts will be directed vigorously toward the further critical issues in the case relating to <ORGANIZATION> Coniston </ORGANIZATION>'s conduct,'' the statement said. <ORGANIZATION> Coniston </ORGANIZATION> principals were not in their <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> offices when called for comment Wednesday. During the trial, which began June 20, both sides alleged violations and misrepresentations occurred during their nearly three-month proxy battle over four seats on the <ORGANIZATION> Gillette </ORGANIZATION> board of directors. <PERSON> Wolf </PERSON> ruled that several newspaper advertisements by <ORGANIZATION> Gillette </ORGANIZATION> during the proxy solicition contained `` falsely misleading'' information about <ORGANIZATION> Coniston </ORGANIZATION>. But <PERSON> Wolf </PERSON> said he still was reviewing whether <ORGANIZATION> Coniston </ORGANIZATION> violated full disclosure laws in its filings with the <ORGANIZATION> Securities </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION>. He also ruled that <ORGANIZATION> Gillette </ORGANIZATION> was not required to provide stockholders with names of companies interested in acquiring the Boston-based company, including <ORGANIZATION> Ralston </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Purina </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Anheuser </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Busch </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>. At least 10 companies have signed agreements not to seek control of <ORGANIZATION> Gillette </ORGANIZATION> without first notifying <ORGANIZATION> Gillette </ORGANIZATION> management, according to court testimony Most of the pacts expire in November. <ORGANIZATION> Gillette </ORGANIZATION> on April 14 filed suit seeking to block <ORGANIZATION> Coniston </ORGANIZATION>'s proxy bid on the grounds <ORGANIZATION> Coniston </ORGANIZATION> falsified <ORGANIZATION> SEC </ORGANIZATION> filings and did not fully acknowledge all of its investors, including Swiss finacier <PERSON> Tito </PERSON> <PERSON> Tettamanti </PERSON> Judge <PERSON> Rya </PERSON> <PERSON> Zobel </PERSON> allowed the suit but rejected the bid for the temporary injunction. A countersuit by <ORGANIZATION> Coniston </ORGANIZATION> filed on April 19 alleged <ORGANIZATION> Gillette </ORGANIZATION> misrepresented <ORGANIZATION> Coniston </ORGANIZATION> in advertisements and mailings to the company's 27,000 shareholders and failed to publicly disclose the companies that had expressed interest in buying <ORGANIZATION> Gillette </ORGANIZATION>. <ORGANIZATION> Gillette </ORGANIZATION> shareholders rejected the dissident <ORGANIZATION> Coniston </ORGANIZATION> slate by a 52 percent to 48 percent vote during the April 21 annual meeting. The candidates _ <ORGANIZATION> Coniston </ORGANIZATION> partners <PERSON> Augustus </PERSON> <PERSON> K. </PERSON> <PERSON> Oliver </PERSON>, <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> E. </PERSON> <PERSON> Tierney </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON>, <PERSON> Keith </PERSON> <PERSON> R. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gollust </PERSON> and cable television executive <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Strassler </PERSON> _ had indicated they would urge the 12-member <ORGANIZATION> Gillette </ORGANIZATION> board to sell the company. Two <ORGANIZATION> Coniston </ORGANIZATION> subsidiaries own 6.76 million <ORGANIZATION> Gillette </ORGANIZATION> shares, or about 5.8 percent of the shares outstanding. <PERSON> Zobel </PERSON> withdrew from the case June 11 on the grounds that she and <ORGANIZATION> Gillette </ORGANIZATION> Chairman and Chief Executive Officer <PERSON> Colman </PERSON> <PERSON> Mockler </PERSON> are affiliated with <ORGANIZATION> Harvard </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION>.
