<HEAD>Jobs Ads Edged Up in May, Conference Board Says</HEAD>
<NOTE>For Release 6 p.m. EDT _ time set for source</NOTE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The pace of new hiring slowed during May as the steady improvement in labor conditions leveled off, a research group said Thursday. The <ORGANIZATION> Conference </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION>, a business-financed research organization, said its help-wanted advertising index edged up three points in May to 160. The index measures the monthly volume of classified advertising in 51 major newspapers in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. The group said such advertising increased moderately in all sections of the country, except for <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Louisiana </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Oklahoma </LOCATION>, which saw a 4.1 percent decline. Elsewhere, the gains ranged from 6.5 percent in the <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York-Pennsylvania </LOCATION> area to 0.5 percent in the <LOCATION> Nebraska </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Minnesota </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Missouri </LOCATION> region. Job growth in the second half of the year is expected to lag behind the first half of 1988, the <ORGANIZATION> Conference </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> said. `` This should be good news for those still concerned about the economy overheating and setting off inflation sparks,'' said <PERSON> Kenneth </PERSON> <PERSON> Goldstein </PERSON>, an economist for the organization. With the latest employment data showing little change, new hiring is unlikely to rise sharply in the next few months, <PERSON> Goldstein </PERSON> said. May's 5.6 percent unemployment rate matched the March level. `` All of this suggests that the long, steady improvement in labor market conditions has run its course,'' he said.
