<HEAD>Airlines Step Up Security in Wake of Persian Gulf Incident</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARCY GORDON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The big <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> airlines that fly overseas say they are taking no chances with retaliation from terrorists and have stepped up their defenses in response to the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION>'s downing of an <ORGANIZATION> Iran </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> jetliner. `` We take the threat seriously,'' said <PERSON> Stephen </PERSON> <PERSON> Heckscher </PERSON>, a spokesman in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> for <ORGANIZATION> Trans </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> World </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION>' international division. The incident in the <LOCATION> Persian </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Gulf </LOCATION> last weekend, which killed nearly 300 civilians, has raised fears of a retaliatory attack by <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION>. Political experts have suggested that revenge could take the form of a terrorist assault against <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> military bases or personnel overseas, or against other American targets _ including commercial airline flights. <PERSON> Bob </PERSON> <PERSON> Kierce </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> TWA </ORGANIZATION>'s director of international security, said the airline has taken steps to ensure that its already tight security precautions `` are being exercised to the fullest.'' <PERSON> Kierce </PERSON> said the airline also has added some new measures at several airports, which he declined to name. Those measures include having a senior member of management on duty whenever a <ORGANIZATION> TWA </ORGANIZATION> plane is on the ground at those locations. <ORGANIZATION> TWA </ORGANIZATION>, the nation's seventh-largest airline, has been the target of some of the most notorious terrorist attacks against jetliners in recent years. In June 1985, Lebanese Shiite Moslems hijacked a <ORGANIZATION> TWA </ORGANIZATION> flight over the <LOCATION> Mediterranean </LOCATION> and diverted it to <LOCATION> Beirut </LOCATION>, where they killed a passenger. The hostages were n't freed until 17 days later. Terrorists set off a bomb in the passenger cabin of a <ORGANIZATION> TWA </ORGANIZATION> jetliner over <LOCATION> Greece </LOCATION> in April 1986, killing four Americans. Other <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> airlines that carry passengers abroad also have been on alert following the <ORGANIZATION> Iran </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> disaster, beefing up security in the midst of the peak summer travel season, experts say. Like <ORGANIZATION> TWA </ORGANIZATION>, most big carriers have their own security divisions but also contract with outside security companies for passenger screening in airports and other protective services. Many of the airlines are touchy about security and refuse to discuss what they're doing. But they emphasize that anti-terrorist defenses are always intensified after such an incident. `` -LRB- The airlines -RRB- do n't need a crystal ball; it's so obvious,'' said <PERSON> Dick </PERSON> <PERSON> Lally </PERSON>, assistant vice president for security at the <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Transport </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION>, a Washington-based trade group that represents the nation's major carriers. The airlines have most likely tightened their security in consultation with the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Aviation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION>, <PERSON> Lally </PERSON> suggested. <PERSON> Pamela </PERSON> <PERSON> Hanlon </PERSON>, a spokeswoman for <ORGANIZATION> Pan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Am </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, said there is always `` heightened awareness'' of security when a potential terrorist attack looms. `` Our security, we believe, is overall very, very good,'' she said. In addition to its <ORGANIZATION> World </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Services </ORGANIZATION> subsidiary, which sells security, maintenance and other services to government agencies and other airlines, <ORGANIZATION> Pan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Am </ORGANIZATION> also has an internal security division. After <ORGANIZATION> TWA </ORGANIZATION>, Pan Am probably has the highest profile among the American carriers that are active overseas. <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION> has increased security at some of the foreign airports it uses, spokesman <PERSON> Dan </PERSON> <PERSON> Sheehy </PERSON> said. United, the nation's largest carrier with scores of domestic flights, has all its overseas operations in the <LOCATION> Far </LOCATION> <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> In a similar way, <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION> specializes in <LOCATION> Latin </LOCATION> <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> as its foreign market. `` We are taking additional precautions,'' said <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION> spokeswoman <PERSON> Paula </PERSON> <PERSON> Musto </PERSON>. Eastern, a subsidiary of giant <ORGANIZATION> Texas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, was the target of several hijackings to <LOCATION> Cuba </LOCATION> between 1979 and 1981, but drug smuggling is now its biggest security headache. Airlines from countries that are identified as close allies of the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> could also be potential targets of the Iranians' ire <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>'s national <ORGANIZATION> El </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Al </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION> has a reputation as the world's toughest carrier when it comes to security In some instances in <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>, <ORGANIZATION> El </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Al </ORGANIZATION> has kept its flight routes secret from passengers until they actually boarded the plane. El Al also sometimes uses planes of a subsidiary that do not carry the carrier's brigh