<HEAD>Oil Prices Jump But Analysts Do Not Expect Big Impact</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 8 grafs to UPDATE with apparent cause of accident,
more closures. Picks up 9th graf pvs, ``There's pressure ...''</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By COTTEN TIMBERLAKE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A massive oil rig fire off the coast of <LOCATION> Scotland </LOCATION> will worsen a shortage of <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Sea </LOCATION> oil, but the disaster is not likely to have a big impact on the industry, experts say. The fatal accident, which caused a jump in world oil prices Thursday, prompted the government's <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Energy </ORGANIZATION> to postpone the process for granting new off-shore licenses, which would open up more areas for exploration. The department had been scheduled to announce on Thursday the blocks for which it was inviting bids for the licenses. `` Because of what happened, we've decided to postpone that at the moment,'' said a department spokesman, who spoke anonymously in keeping with British practice. The price of Brent Blend, the most widely traded international crude oil, jumped on Thursday to $ 15.05 a barrel for September delivery, up 32 cents from late Wednesday. <ORGANIZATION> Occidental </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Petroleum </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, owner of the <ORGANIZATION> Piper </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Alpha </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> rig </ORGANIZATION>, said a gas leak apparently was to blame for the disaster. The rig produced 167,200 barrels a day, the company said. A barrel contains 42 gallons. In addition to the Piper oil field, five other fields were shut down, the department said. They were the Claymore, Tartan, <LOCATION> Highland </LOCATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Scapa </ORGANIZATION> and <LOCATION> Petronella </LOCATION> fields, it said. That meant production was cut by a total of about 220,000 barrels a day to 250,000 barrels a day, or about one-tenth of the British sector's production, the department and analysts said. `` There's pressure on the immediate availability for <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Sea </LOCATION> crude,'' said <PERSON> Philip </PERSON> <PERSON> Morgan </PERSON>, an oil analyst with the <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> investment firm <ORGANIZATION> Warburg </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Securities </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Lucy </PERSON> <PERSON> Mullins </PERSON>, an oil analyst with the <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> investment firm <ORGANIZATION> Barclays </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> de </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Zoete </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Wedd </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ltd. </ORGANIZATION>, added, however: `` That's going to be fairly short-term.'' The related fields should be back in production in a week, and <ORGANIZATION> Piper </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Alpha </ORGANIZATION> probably will be out of production for up to a year, Ms. <PERSON> Mullins </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Morgan </PERSON> said the industry already was experiencing a shortage because of regular maintenance, which oil companies generally do in the summmer when the weather is milder. <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Sea </LOCATION> oil production in the British sector averages 2 -LCB- million barrels a day, the <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Energy </ORGANIZATION> says. Production is down 400,000 barrels a day from that level because of the maintenance, <PERSON> Morgan </PERSON> said. Producers of the <ORGANIZATION> Organization </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Petroleum </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exporting </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Countries </ORGANIZATION>, of which <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION> is not a member, will step in to meet demand, Ms. <PERSON> Mullins </PERSON> said. The oil price also has been boosted by favorable statistics released this week, <PERSON> Morgan </PERSON> said. `` There is starting to be a perception that the glut in world supplies in general is not as bad as people thought,'' <PERSON> Morgan </PERSON> said. <ORGANIZATION> Occidental </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Petroleum </ORGANIZATION>'s production wo n't be severely affected by the fire, because it has other outlets, Ms. <PERSON> Mullins </PERSON> said. There were concerns about claims against the company, however, and <ORGANIZATION> Occidental </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Petroleum </ORGANIZATION>'s stock fell 50 cents to $ 26.25 in early trading on the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>. The stock price of <ORGANIZATION> British </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Petroleum </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>. PLC, the biggest producer in the British sector, fell 3 cents to $ 4.49 in afternoon trading on <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Stock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> The disaster could prove expensive for the <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Sea </LOCATION> oil producers in general, <PERSON> Morgan </PERSON> said. `` Obviously, questions are going to be raised about safety which might involve companies in a lot more expenditure,'' <PERSON> Morgan </PERSON> said. The British sector of the <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Sea </LOCATION> oil fields runs from the <LOCATION> Shetland </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Islands </LOCATION> north of <LOCATION> Scotland </LOCATION> down to <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Anglia </LOCATION> on <LOCATION> England </LOCATION>'s southeast coast, covering hundreds of thousands of square miles The first British sector gas fields were discovered in 1964 and oil production began in 1975, the <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Energy </ORGANIZATION> said. The sector employed 28,000 people in offshore facilities at the end of last year, it said. There are 123 fixed installations, including the <ORGANIZATION> Piper </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Alpha </ORGANIZATION> platform, in the British sector, with 40 mobile rigs, the depa