<HEAD>Federal Reserve Nominee Quizzed on `Golden Parachute'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM LUTHER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>'s latest nominee for a seat on the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reserve </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> was accused Thursday of attempting to dodge taxes in negotiating a $ 2.5-million `` golden parachute'' compensation agreement with the <LOCATION> Boston </LOCATION> bank holding company he heads. `` I am concerned about it,'' Sen. <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Proxmire </PERSON>, D-Wis., chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Banking </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>, said of the agreement at the end of a confirmation hearing for <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> P. </PERSON> <PERSON> LaWare </PERSON>, chairman of <ORGANIZATION> Shawmut </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> LaWare </PERSON> said `` I'm not sure a tax dodge was involved'' in the compensation agreement, which he said was offered to assure him that his annual income of about $ 500,000 would be continued until he reaches age He turned 60 on Feb. 20. Despite <PERSON> Proxmire </PERSON>'s concern that the bank _ not <PERSON> LaWare </PERSON> _ is obligated to pay a special excise tax on a portion of the pay agreement, there was no indication the issue would affect LaWare's nomination In fact, <PERSON> Proxmire </PERSON> told <PERSON> LaWare </PERSON>, `` You are a very impressive candidate for the job.'' However, committee aides say some Democrats are reluctant to see the nomination approved because it would mean that <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> would have filled all seven seats on the board, which controls the nation's money supply. These senators are hoping that fellow Democrat <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> will be elected president and could promptly fill the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reserve </ORGANIZATION> seat after taking office next January. <PERSON> LaWare </PERSON>, a registered Democrat, would replace <PERSON> Henry </PERSON> <PERSON> G. </PERSON> <PERSON> Wallich </PERSON>, who resigned. The 14-year term would expire Jan. 31, 2002. <PERSON> Proxmire </PERSON> told reporters he will confer with committee members before deciding whether the panel should vote on the LaWare nomination this year. Should the panel recommend the nomination, it would be up to Majority Leader <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> C. </PERSON> <PERSON> Byrd </PERSON>, D-W. <LOCATION> Va. </LOCATION>, to determine whether the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> should consider the nomination this The issue of monetary policy was barely mentioned at the hearing. Most questions were about the federal budget and trade deficits, the increasing share of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> debt held by foreign investors and Third World debt. <PERSON> LaWare </PERSON> said he is little concerned about the fact that only one of the world's 10 biggest banks is American. `` I do n't think that makes much difference,'' he said. `` It's how well-managed and profitable they are ... I am more concerned with the profit-and-loss statement'' than with size. None of the other committee members took up <PERSON> Proxmire </PERSON>'s line of questioning about the `` golden parachute'' agreement, which was negotiated earlier this year as part of the merger that created <ORGANIZATION> Shamut </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp </ORGANIZATION>. Similar agreements are used to reward executives when control or ownership of a corporation changes. In 1984, <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> required recipients of such arrangements to pay a 20 percent excise tax on the portion that the law considers excessive. In addition, corporations were barred from taking a tax deduction for the excessive payments. Under <PERSON> LaWare </PERSON>'s agreement, which he acknowledged to be worth about $ 500,000 a year, the corporation itself is obligated to pay the 20 percent tax. <PERSON> Proxmire </PERSON> estimated that would save LaWare about $ 200,000 in taxes. `` How do you justify such an attempt to dodge the tax code?'' <PERSON> Proxmire </PERSON> asked. The idea behind the 1984 law, he said, `` was to discourage excessive payments which officers and directors vote themselves.'' `` I'm not sure it's a dodge,'' <PERSON> LaWare </PERSON> said. `` The tax is being paid, regardless'' and the federal government is losing no money, he said. <PERSON> LaWare </PERSON> must pay income tax on the full amount of the `` golden parachute'' payment, including whatever amount the bank chips in to cover the special excise tax.
