<HEAD>General Mills' Profit Up 53 Percent in Fourth Quarter</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MINNEAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mills </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> said its profit jumped 53 percent in its fourth quarter from a year earlier, boosted by a lower tax rate, good volume growth in consumer foods, strong performance by key restaurant chains, and significant productivity gains. The food giant reported Thursday that its profit for the quarter ended May 29 rose to $ 54.9 million, or 65 cents a share, from $ 36.1 million, or 41 cents a share, in the fourth quarter of fiscal 1987. Fourth-quarter sales increased to $ 1.3 billion from $ 1.2 billion a year earlier. For fiscal 1988, which was one week shorter than fiscal 1987, earnings rose 27 percent to $ 283.1 million, or $ 3.25 a share, from $ 222 million, or $ 2.50 a share. Sales in fiscal 1988 were up 10 percent, to $ 5.2 billion from $ 4.7 billion the previous year. The earnings report for the fourth quarter includes the discontinued specialty retailing operations of <ORGANIZATION> Talbots </ORGANIZATION> and <PERSON> Eddie </PERSON> <PERSON> Bauer </PERSON>. General <PERSON> Mills </PERSON> will post a $ 200 million gain after taxes in the first quarter of fiscal 1989 from the sale of the retailing companies. General Mills Chairman <PERSON> Bruce </PERSON> <PERSON> Atwater </PERSON> said the consumer foods division achieved a 4 percent increase in domestic packaged food volume, leading to annual sales and operating profit gains of 9 percent and 11 percent, respectively. The company said the success of several new microwave food products and growing acceptance of Yoplait yogurt and other new foods contributed to the earnings increase. Spending on Big G cereals for the fourth quarter was particularly strong, as both volume and market share grew, <PERSON> Atwater </PERSON> said. In the restaurant division, <ORGANIZATION> Red </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lobster </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Olive </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATIO