o buy a majority stake in <LOCATION> Irving </LOCATION> as an alternative to <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION>'s hostile bid. The Milan-based bank is offering $ 80 a share for 51 percent of <PERSON> Irving </PERSON>'s 18.5 million common shares outstanding and the special dividend for the remaining 49 percent. Earlier this week it sweetened the offer to include warrants entitling shareholders to buy newly issued <PERSON> Irving </PERSON> stock at $ 65 a share over the next seven years. Stockholders would receive one warrant for every four shares they now own. The offer is valued at a minimum of $ 79.50 a share. <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION>, which owns a 4.9 percent stake in <LOCATION> Irving </LOCATION>, is offering $ 15 in cash and 1.575 shares of its own stock for each of <PERSON> Irving </PERSON>'s common shares outstanding. The offer is valued at around $ 68 a share or $ 1.2 billion. `` From a practical standpoint I would think if the <ORGANIZATION> Fed </ORGANIZATION> was to disallow the -LRB- <ORGANIZATION> Banca </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commerciale </ORGANIZATION> -RRB- special dividend ... that would place pressure on BCI to increase its offer in a tangible manner,'' said <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Starr </PERSON>, a banking analyst with <ORGANIZATION> Duff </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Phelps </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> `` I would n't think it would have to be a dollar-for-dollar match. I do n't think the market expected the full $ 10 to go through anyway. That was a major ` if.''' A number of analysts agreed that at some point it might no longer be economically feasible for <ORGANIZATION> Banca </ORGANIZ