<FIRST>u f AM-SEC Bjt   07-07 0803</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-SEC, Bjt,0830</SECOND>
<HEAD>Commission OKs One-Share, One-Vote Rule</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVE SKIDMORE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Securities </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> voted Thursday to limit the ability of American companies to weaken the voting power of their stockholders as way of fighting hostile corporate raids. The new one-share, one-vote rule, approved 4-1, does not altogether ban dual classes of common stock, but rather spells out how shares with reduced voting power can be issued. One popular takeover defense, in which companies entice stockholders into giving up their voting rights by offering a special one-time dividend, would be prohibited. Also barred would be rules that require a stock purchaser to wait, sometimes for several years, before newly acquired shares accrue full voting rights. Companies will have to comply with the new <ORGANIZATION> SEC </ORGANIZATION> rule if they want their stock traded on an exchange or through the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Securities </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Dealers </ORGANIZATION>' automated quotation system. However, in another voting rights area, the <ORGANIZATION> SEC </ORGANIZATION> decided to defer to the states. In states that allow it, companies will be permitted to deny voting power to takeover raiders unless the other shareholders approve. About a dozen states have adopted such laws and the <ORGANIZATION> SEC </ORGANIZATION>, in friend-of-the-court briefs, has argued that they improperly interfere with national securities markets. In unrelated action, the commission voted unanimously to back off from recommending congressional legislation barring brokerage firms from requiring customers to agree in advance to settle disputes before an arbitration panel. State securities regulators and others have been arguing that so-called `` pre-dispute arbitration clauses'' in the fine print of account agreements are unfair because they require customers, in some cases unwittingly, to sign away their right to sue in court before they know the nature of any disagreement that may arise. <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> G. </PERSON> <PERSON> Ketchum </PERSON>, director of the <ORGANIZATION> SEC </ORGANIZATION>'s division of market regulation, said he doubted the new one-share, one-vote rule would have a dramatic effect on takeovers. But he conceded that in a few cases takeovers would be easier because the rule eliminates some `` extremely effective'' defenses. Commissioner <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> <PERSON> C. </PERSON> <PERSON> Cox </PERSON>, the only member to vote against the rule, said he believed the <ORGANIZATION> SEC </ORGANIZATION> was intruding into an area that has traditionally been left to states: the chartering and governance of corporations. `` I believe this is an improper use of the listing standards to tamper with corporate governance,'' he said. However, <ORGANIZATION> SEC </ORGANIZATION> Chairman <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Ruder </PERSON> said the rule is structured `` to be as least intrusive as possible.'' Companies will still be permitted to issue new shares with diluted voting power. Diluted-power shares can also be issued to accomplish a merger. And private companies going public will be able to issue both strong-voting and weak-voting shares. However, corporations will not be able to issue `` supershares'' that have more voting power than common stock already issued. That would have allowed company insiders, such as managers, to buy up the strong shares to acquire control over the company. Stocks of foreign companies traded in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> will be exempted from the regulations. The 359 <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> companies that had disparate voting rights before Thursday will also be exempted, as will the stocks of small companies listed in the <ORGANIZATION> NASD </ORGANIZATION>'s so-called `` pink sheets'' and traded by brokers over the telephone. Despite the exceptions, the rule drew praise from the <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Shareholders </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION>, which is headed by <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> oilman and takeover specialist <PERSON> T. </PERSON> <PERSON> Boone </PERSON> <PERSON> Pickens </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON> `` The <ORGANIZATION> SEC </ORGANIZATION>'s action helps to restore democracy to corporate <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>,'' <PERSON> Pickens </PERSON> said in a statement. Commission debate over the rule approved Thursday began nearly two years ago when the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> in September 1986 asked for <ORGANIZATION> SEC </ORGANIZATION> permission to drop its 60-year-old one-share, one-vote standard. Exchange officials said they were dropping the standard reluctantly out of fear of losing business to the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>, which had more liberal rules, and the <ORGANIZATION> NASD </ORGANIZATION>, which had no such standard. Sen. <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Proxmire </PERSON>, D-Wis., chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Banking </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>, and others have argued that the <ORGANIZATION> SEC </ORGANIZATION> does not have jurisdiction over the matter and should defer to <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> However, Commissioner <PERSON> Edward </PERSON> <PERSON> H. </PERSON> <PERSON> Fleischman </PERSON> said <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> has not acted in two years and that the law requires the <ORGANIZATION> SEC </ORGANIZATION> to approve or disapprove changes in exchange rules. On the arbitration issue, the <ORGANIZATION> SEC </ORGANIZATION> voted to ask the stock exchanges and the <ORGANIZATION> NASD </ORGANIZATION> to study pre-dispute clauses and to report back to the commission by Oct. 15. Nevertheless, Reps. <PERSON> Rick </PERSON> <PERSON> Boucher </PERSON>, D-Va.; <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> D. </PERSON> <PERSON> Dingell </PERSON>, D-Mich., and <PERSON> Edward </PERSON> <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Markey </PERSON>, D-Mass., have gone ahead and introduced a The head of the <ORGANIZATION> North </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Securities </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administrators </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION>, which represents state regulators, called the <ORGANIZATION> SEC </ORGANIZATION> decision `` disappointing.'' `` Small investors will see the commission failure to act as another sign that the deck is stacked against them,'' said <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> C. </PERSON> <PERSON> Meyer </PERSON>, president of the association and <LOCATION> Tennessee </LOCATION>'s top securities regulator.
</TEXT>
