<HEAD>Grain Futures Plunge As Weekend Looks Wetter</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Retransmitting to restore Bjt designtaion</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DAVID DISHNEAU</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
 Most grain and soybean futures prices plummeted their limits for daily trading Thursday on the <ORGANIZATION> Chicago </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trade </ORGANIZATION>, taking some analysts by surprise and leaving them divided on the reasons for the move. On other markets, gasoline futures soared and other energy futures also gained; livestock and meat were mixed; precious metals advanced; and stock-index futures gained. `` I'm astounded,'' <PERSON> Katharina </PERSON> <PERSON> Zimmer </PERSON>, New York-based grains analyst for <ORGANIZATION> Merrill </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lynch </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Capital </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Markets </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, said after the grain and soybean markets closed. Most corn, soybean and oat contracts plunged their respective 15 -, 30 - and 10-cent limits for daily trading, and the limitless contracts for July delivery fell even Wheat contracts for December, March and July 1989 delivery tumbled 20 cents a bushel, the limit in that market. Despite new forecasts for weekend rains in the dry and dusty <LOCATION> Midwest </LOCATION>, Ms. <PERSON> Zimmer </PERSON> said the sell-off was technically inspired. `` This market has nothing to do with fundamentals any more,'' she said. Instead, she said, Thursday's action was dominated by so-called technicians, who base their trading decisions on historical chart patterns. On Thursday, the charts indicated it was time to sell, Ms. <PERSON> Zimmer </PERSON> said. More likely, the drop was caused by a combination of technical and fundamental factors, said <PERSON> Ted </PERSON> <PERSON> Mao </PERSON>, grain specialist with <ORGANIZATION> Shearson </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lehman </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hutton </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>. Though prices turned lower shortly after the opening, <PERSON> Mao </PERSON> said the sharpest drop followed midday news reports that <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> Minority Leader <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Dole </PERSON>, R-Kan., had said the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> may consider measures allowing farmers to plant soybeans and oats on a portion of their acreage idled under government crop programs But <PERSON> Dole </PERSON>, speaking to the <ORGANIZATION> Commodity </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Club </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, said the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> probably would not act on the matter for at least another month. Private forecasts for moderate rainfall this weekend in the northern Corn Belt also pressured the markets, <PERSON> Mao </PERSON> said. `` The market continues to show its sensitivity to prospects of getting even a little bit of rain,'' he said. `` That's nonsense,'' countered Ms. <PERSON> Zimmer </PERSON>, who dismissed the expected rain as `` sprinkles.'' `` To tell an <LOCATION> Illinois </LOCATION> farmer we're locked limit-down because of the rain we're going to get, I do n't know what they'd say, but it probably would not be printable,'' she said. Wheat settled 15 -LCB- cents to 20 cents lower with the contract for delivery in July at $ 3.78 a bushel; corn was 14 -LCB- cents to 22 cents lower with July at $ 3.20 a bushel; oats were 10 cents to 22 cents lower with July at $ 3.01 a bushel; soybeans were 26 cents to 49 -LCB- cents lower with July at $ 9.34 -LCB- a bushel. Prices for future delivery of unleaded gasoline and heating oil soared on the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mercantile </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> in reaction to Wednesday's weekly <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Petroleum </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION> report showing a sharp drawdown in gasoline supplies, analysts said. Energy futures were broadly supported by reports that the tragic explosion of a <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Sea </LOCATION> oil rig could cause production of <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Sea </LOCATION> crude oil to fall by 30,000 barrels a day, said <PERSON> Nauman </PERSON> <PERSON> Barakat </PERSON>, energy analyst with <ORGANIZATION> Shearson </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lehman </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hutton </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc </ORGANIZATION>. Crude-oil futures declined on profit-taking in the second half of the session, he said. West Texas Intermediate crude oil settled 43 cents to 55 cents higher with August at $ 15.83 a barrel; heating oil was 1.37 cents to 1.68 cents higher with August at 44.29 cents a gallon; unleaded gasoline was 1.23 cents to 2.56 cents higher with August at 53.12 cents a gallon. The inflationary implications of higher energy prices supported precious metals futures on <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Commodity </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>, analysts said. Gold settled 40 cents to $ 1.20 higher with August at $ 441.10 a troy ounce; silver was 11.5 cents to 13.6 cents higher with July at $ 6.935 a troy ounce. Livestock and meat futures finished mixed on the <ORGANIZATION> Chicago </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mercantile </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>. The drop in grain prices prompted reversals of recent drought-related trends in the cattle and hog markets, and pork bellies rebounded sharply after touching 8-year lows on Wednesday, said <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> Hare </PERSON>, an analyst with <ORGANIZATION> Linnco </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Futures </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION>. Live cattle were .60 cent lower to .15 cent higher with August at 64.75 cents a pound; feeder cattle were .05 cent to .38 cent higher with A