<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Electric </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>'s largest union, representing 40,000 workers, overwhelmingly ratified a new contract and 11 smaller unions were expected to follow suit, labor leaders said Thursday. Members of the <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Union </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Electronic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Workers </ORGANIZATION> voted nearly 5-to-1 in favor of the three-year pact with all but two of the 72 locals reporting, union spokesman <PERSON> Jerry </PERSON> <PERSON> Borstel </PERSON>. The two locals who had not reported represent just 20 workers. `` It's pretty final,'' <PERSON> Borstel </PERSON> said. Sixty-six locals approved the pact, three rejected it, and one local split evenly. The vote was 33,378 to 6,785 to approve the pact, he said. `` The overwhelming vote to ratify shows that the <ORGANIZATION> IUE </ORGANIZATION> membership is satisfied with this settlement, which is worth more than the 1985 contract and is better than any other agreement negotiated in industry this year,'' said <ORGANIZATION> IUE </ORGANIZATION> President <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Bywater </PERSON>. <PERSON> Bywater </PERSON> said he expected the 11 smaller unions that joined the <ORGANIZATION> IUE </ORGANIZATION> at the bargaining table to ratify the contract. The tentative agreement, reached June 26, calls for a special early retirement package; three annual wage increases of 2.5 percent, 1.5 percent and 1.5 percent; two cash bonuses; reduced employee pension contributions; preferential hiring for <ORGANIZATION> IUE </ORGANIZATION> members; dependent care aid, and other improvements. The average hourly wage of $ 12.02 would rise to $ 13.40, assuming 4.5 percent annual inflation, according to GE figures. The average employee stands to gain about $ 6,100 over the life of the contract. Workers covered by the pact produce everything from light bulbs to appliances, medical equipment to aerospace products, and maintain factories and machinery. Each union must ratify the pact by Sunday for its terms to be retroactive, <ORGANIZATION> GE </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Jack </PERSON> <PERSON> Batty </PERSON> said.
