<HEAD>Reading &amp; Bates Plans To Sell Subsidiary</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GIL BROYLES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TULSA, Okla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Reading & amp; <ORGANIZATION> Bates </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> announced Thursday it will sell its oil and gas subsidiary and move its corporate headquarters to <LOCATION> Houston </LOCATION>, where it will concentrate on offshore drilling. About 30 employees were laid off Thursday, and another 100 will lose their jobs in the next few months, officials said. The company has about 2,000 employees worldwide. J.W. <PERSON> Bates </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON>, chairman and chief executive officer, said the move to <LOCATION> Houston </LOCATION> is expected to be completed by the end of the year. Another subsidiary, <ORGANIZATION> Reading </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; <ORGANIZATION> Bates </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Drilling </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> has maintained offices in <LOCATION> Houston </LOCATION> for more than 30 years. `` Obviously, the decision has been a very difficult one,'' said <PERSON> Bates </PERSON>, who helped start the company in 1955. But he said it is necessary because there has been no turnaround for the oil industry. Reading & amp; <PERSON> Bates </PERSON> has had three years of losses and a fourth is anticipated, he said. `` I think there's no question it'll get better,'' <PERSON> Bates </PERSON> said. `` The question is, when. If the company is to survive as a major international offshore drilling contractor, which has been our principal business throughout the years, we have no alternative.'' Reading & amp; <PERSON> Bates </PERSON> operates a fleet of 18 offshore drilling rigs throughout the world. The company also owns <ORGANIZATION> Resources </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Conservation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, a process engineering company located in <LOCATION> Seattle </LOCATION>, and <ORGANIZATION> Reading </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; <ORGANIZATION> Bates </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Coal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> operating in eastern <LOCATION> Kentucky </LOCATION>. Reading & amp; <PERSON> Bates </PERSON> disposed of its pipeline construction business in 1985. In 1987, the company completed sale of its foreign oil and gas production, its horizontal drilling operations and its part of a land drilling venture in <LOCATION> Argentina </LOCATION>. It reported losses of $ 191 million, in 1987, $ 145.8 million in 1986 and $ 190.6 million in 1985. The company is in default of all leases, subject to continuing negotiations, in an amount estimated at $ 272.2 million as of Dec. 31, 1987. The company and its lenders are continuing to negotiate terms of a restructuring agreement, <PERSON> Bates </PERSON> said. `` Hopefully, that will be accomplished by the end of the year, or certainly next year,'' he said. <PERSON> Bates </PERSON> said he does not believe the company will have any trouble finding a buyer for the petroleum company. Reading & amp; <ORGANIZATION> Bates </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Petroleum </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> had operating revenues of about $ 25 million in 1987, and proved developed reserves in the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> of 5.7 million barrels of oil and 70 billion cubic feet of natural gas. `` There is intense interest in acquiring reserves,'' <PERSON> Bates </PERSON> said.
