<FIRST>u f AM-SEC-Arbitration     07-07 0567</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-SEC-Arbitration,0586</SECOND>
<HEAD>SEC Backs Down on Plan to Give Investors Right to Sue Brokers</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-SEC, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVE SKIDMORE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Securities </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> on Thursday backed off from recommending legislation that would guarantee investors the right to sue their stock broker in court. The commission had been considering asking <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> to outlaw clauses in brokerage account agreements requiring customers to settle disputes through industry-sponsored arbitration panels, rather than through the courts. But, by a 5-0 vote, the commission decided instead to ask stock exchanges and other organizations that run arbitration systems to study the matter and report back by Oct. 15. Rep. <PERSON> Edward </PERSON> <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Markey </PERSON>, D-Mass., chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> subcommittee with jurisdiction over the securities markets, said the <ORGANIZATION> SEC </ORGANIZATION> had caved in to industry lobbying with its decision `` Apparently there was a full-court press by the industry that was successful,'' <PERSON> Markey </PERSON> said. `` ... I think the industry stared into the <ORGANIZATION> SEC </ORGANIZATION>'s eyes on this issue and the <ORGANIZATION> SEC </ORGANIZATION> blinked.'' When the commission discussed the arbitration clauses last month, the legislative recommendation looked headed for approval. It was supported by <ORGANIZATION> SEC </ORGANIZATION> Chairman <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Ruder </PERSON> and member <PERSON> Aulana </PERSON> <PERSON> L. </PERSON> <PERSON> Peters </PERSON>. Commissioner <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> <PERSON> C. </PERSON> <PERSON> Cox </PERSON> said he was inclined to favor it but wanted to hear from securities firms, which strongly opposed banning the clauses. But, on Thursday, <PERSON> Ruder </PERSON> retreated from his earlier support. He said he was persuaded to defer action after learning the industry would at least favor disclosure notices to customers explaining the meaning of the clauses. An <ORGANIZATION> SEC </ORGANIZATION> survey found that 39 percent of cash accounts carry arbitration agreements and that firms holding another 40 percent were considering using such clauses. But <PERSON> Ruder </PERSON> said many firms that were once looking into using the clauses for cash accounts appear to be holding off at least for now. He also said some regional firms have recently made a point of advertising that they will open cash accounts without arbitration clauses. However, nearly all firms surveyed, 95 percent, require arbitration agreements for option and margin accounts, where the risk of loss is greater. Proponents of the clauses argue that customers are free to negotiate the clauses out of the contract and that firms have a right to set the conditions under which they're willing to do business. Administration officials, including <PERSON> Beryl </PERSON> <PERSON> Sprinkel </PERSON>, chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Economic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Advisers </ORGANIZATION>, had sent letters to the <ORGANIZATION> SEC </ORGANIZATION> criticizing staff proposals on arbitration clauses. Despite the lack of <ORGANIZATION> SEC </ORGANIZATION> support, Reps. <PERSON> Rick </PERSON> <PERSON> Boucher </PERSON>, D-Va.; <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> D. </PERSON> <PERSON> Dingell </PERSON>, D-Mich., and <PERSON> Edward </PERSON> <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Markey </PERSON>, D-Mass., have introduced The bill is backed by state securities regulators and others who say arbitration clauses are unfair because they require customers to sign away their right to sue before they know the nature of any disagreement that may arise. The head of the <ORGANIZATION> North </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Securities </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administrators </ORGANIZATION> <ORGA