<HEAD>Takeshita Aide Implicated in Political Scandal</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 17th graf pvs, Ko Marita ... with 1 graf to CORRECT
spelling to Morita.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By ERIC TALMADGE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A former secretary to Prime Minister <PERSON> Noboru </PERSON> <PERSON> Takeshita </PERSON> was added Thursday to the list of aides to top politicians who reportedly profited from questionable stock dealings in a scandal sweeping Japanese business and politics. <PERSON> Takeshita </PERSON> told reporters that his former secretary, <PERSON> Ihei </PERSON> <PERSON> Aoki </PERSON>, earned profits by trading the shares of the real estate company <ORGANIZATION> Recruit-Cosmos </ORGANIZATION>. He said <PERSON> Aoki </PERSON> obtained shares from the company and then sold them shortly after Recruit-Cosmos went public in October 1986, when <PERSON> Takeshita </PERSON> was finance minister. In related developments, the president of <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>'s leading economic newspaper and the chairman of <ORGANIZATION> Recruit-Cosmos </ORGANIZATION> resigned. The chairman of Recruit-Cosmos and its parent company also announced he will step down. The dealings were not illegal, but critics said the case illustrates doubtful ethics in the links between <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>'s politicians and businessmen <PERSON> Takeshita </PERSON> did not elaborate on the number of shares <PERSON> Aoki </PERSON> traded or his profits from the deal, and refused to take responsibility for his former aide's action. But <PERSON> Takeshita </PERSON> acknowledged that the scandal would seriously affect an upcoming session of the Diet, <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>'s parliament, when the administration hopes to push through a major tax reform measure. The controversy surfaced last month as a bribery case in a local government, but entered a new phase with revelations that aides to leaders of the governing <ORGANIZATION> Liberal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> profited with <ORGANIZATION> Recruit-Cosmos </ORGANIZATION> stock. In addition to <PERSON> Takeshita </PERSON>, the scandal has affected secretaries of Finance Minister <P