<HEAD>Sun to Spin Off U.S. Exploration and Production Arm to
Shareholders</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES WEBB</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PHILADELPHIA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Sun Co.. <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>'s board of directors on Thursday approved a major restructuring plan that will spin off the company's $ 4.8 billion domestic oil and gas exploration and production business into an independent company and trim its work force by more than 1,000 The plan also calls for the nation's 10th largest oil company to expand its international exploration and production operations, as well as its refining and marketing business, which will be retained by the restructured Sun, company officials said. It comes two days after <PERSON> Sun </PERSON> announced it had agreed to buy <ORGANIZATION> Atlantic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Petroleum </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, a Northeast refiner and retailer, for $ 513 million from oil trader <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Duess </PERSON>. The reorganization is projected as a major-cost savings move for the Radnor-based company, said <PERSON> Peter </PERSON> <PERSON> Waitneight </PERSON>, vice president of corporate financing. `` The earnings have not been growing in the rather weak market for crude oil and natural gas,'' <PERSON> Waitneight </PERSON> said in a telephone interview. He said company officials believe that payroll reductions and independent management structures for the separate companies would result in higher earnings that would boost profits. Under the plan, current <ORGANIZATION> Sun </ORGANIZATION> shareholders would receive a one-for-one tax-free distribution of stock in the newly created <ORGANIZATION> Sun </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exploration </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Production </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, which will handle domestic oil and gas exploration and production. The redistribution is subject to approval by shareholders and dependent on the <ORGANIZATION> Internal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Revenue </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> granting it tax-free status. The new company, to be headquartered in <LOCATION> Dallas </LOCATION>, would become the largest independent oil and gas producer in <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>, with approximately $ 4.8 billion in assets and $ 1.6 billion in revenue in 1987, Sun officials said. The original Sun would restructure with more than $ 9 billion in assets. Excluding the domestic oil and gas exploration and production business, Sun totaled $ 9.1 billion in revenue last year. <PERSON> Waitneight </PERSON> said the distribution would be presented for shareholders' consideration during a special meeting in early October, with distribution of shares, if approved, planned for the end of October. Reduction of the work force will begin immediately, <PERSON> Waitneight </PERSON> said. About 800 Sun workers employed in the new company's operations, most of them in the <LOCATION> Western </LOCATION> <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, will lose their jobs, <PERSON> Waitneight </PERSON> said. Another 250 workers at the restructured Sun, most of them in the East and many in the <LOCATION> Philadelphia </LOCATION> area, also will lose their jobs, he said. Company officials said some employees would be offered early retirment incentives, but <PERSON> Waitneight </PERSON> would not specify how many. Sun officials expect the restructuring to produce $ 65 million in after-tax savings for <ORGANIZATION> Sun </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> E </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; P each year and $ 15 million for the restructured Sun each year, most of that through payroll reductions. `` The driving force behind this decision is to enhance value for holders of <ORGANIZATION> Sun </ORGANIZATION> stock,'' said <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> McClements </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON>, chairman and chief executive officer of Sun. <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> P. </PERSON> <PERSON> Hau